    {
      "id": "0d6r0p2s",
      "title": "Store and Manage ROS Data",
      "content": "Refer https://www.reduct.store/blog/tutorial-store-ros-data\n\nArchitecting a Production-Ready Data Pipeline for Edge Robotics with ROS 2 and ReductStore\n\n\nIntroduction\n\nModern robotics systems operating at the edge generate a torrent of high-volume, real-time data from a multitude of sensors. Effectively managing this data is a critical challenge, yet it is the cornerstone of advancing robotics capabilities—from training sophisticated machine learning models to enabling remote diagnostics and operational analysis. This white paper presents a comprehensive architectural blueprint for a robust data acquisition, storage, and management pipeline built on the Robot Operating System (ROS 2). The proposed solution leverages ReductStore as a specialized time-series object store to systematically address key challenges inherent in professional robotics deployments, including resource-constrained hardware, intermittent network connectivity, and the need for data scalability across entire fleets.\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\n1. The Core Challenge: Data Management in Edge Robotics\n\nEffective data management is strategically vital for unlocking the full potential of robotics. The data collected from robots in the field fuels the entire development lifecycle, enabling everything from debugging and performance analysis to the training of next-generation AI models. However, designing data systems for edge environments presents a unique set of obstacles that must be overcome. This section deconstructs the primary architectural challenges encountered in edge robotics.\n\n* Resource-Constrained Hardware: Edge devices, such as the Raspberry Pi used in the reference architecture, impose strict limitations on processing power, memory, and storage. These constraints dictate an architectural reliance on lightweight, efficient components that minimize their footprint and avoid impacting the robot's primary operational functions.\n* High-Volume Sensor Streams: Sensors like cameras and lidars produce a continuous deluge of data, with a single high-resolution camera capable of generating gigabytes per hour. An effective architecture must be capable of ingesting, processing, and storing these streams without frame loss or performance degradation, requiring a purpose-built storage engine optimized for high-throughput blob data.\n* Intermittent Network Connectivity: Field robotics often operate in environments with unreliable or non-existent network connections, from warehouses with spotty Wi-Fi to remote agricultural fields. The data pipeline must therefore be architected for offline-first operation, capable of durably storing data locally and seamlessly synchronizing with central servers once connectivity is restored.\n* Data Scalability and Fleet Management: The complexity of data management multiplies when scaling from a single prototype to a distributed fleet. A production-ready architecture must provide a consistent, scalable method for aggregating data from hundreds of units, enabling centralized analysis and fleet-wide monitoring without overwhelming network or storage infrastructure.\n\nTo overcome these challenges systematically, a purpose-built architecture that addresses each of these constraints as a core design principle is required.\n\n2. An Architectural Blueprint for a Scalable ROS 2 Data Pipeline\n\nThe proposed architecture provides a cohesive and production-ready solution for managing robotics data from the point of capture to a central repository. This system is built upon four key architectural pillars: intelligent on-device data acquisition and processing, efficient edge storage, configurable data capture and segmentation, and seamless, resilient data replication.\n\nSystem Architecture Overview\n\nThe system consists of two primary architectural components that create an end-to-end data flow:\n\n* The Edge Node: A resource-constrained device, such as a Raspberry Pi, running ROS 2. This node serves as the point of data origin, equipped with sensors (e.g., a USB camera), on-device processing for real-time data enrichment (a lightweight YOLOv5n object detection model), and a local instance of ReductStore for immediate, durable storage.\n* The Central Data Store: A more powerful machine, such as a server or cloud instance, that runs a separate ReductStore instance. This component acts as the central aggregation point for data replicated from one or more edge nodes, serving as the foundation for long-term storage and large-scale analysis.\n\nThe fundamental data flow begins with sensor capture on the edge. This data is enriched with machine learning-derived metadata, published as ROS 2 topics, and then recorded by a specialized agent into the local ReductStore instance. Finally, this data is reliably replicated to the central store.\n\nEdge Node: Intelligent Data Acquisition and Processing\n\nThe edge node is architected to not only capture raw environmental data but also to enrich it with valuable context through real-time analysis at the source.\n\nFirst, the v4l2_camera ROS 2 package provides a standardized interface to a USB camera, abstracting the hardware details. It captures video frames and publishes them as a raw image topic (/image_raw) within the ROS 2 ecosystem, making the high-volume sensor stream available to other processes on the robot.\n\nSecond, an on-device machine learning component performs data enrichment at the source. The combination of a lightweight model like YOLOv5n and an efficient inference engine like ONNX Runtime represents a sound architectural decision for edge ML. This approach decouples the inference engine from the training framework, maximizes performance on ARM-based CPUs common in robotics, and minimizes the dependency footprint. A custom YoloDetectorNode subscribes to /image_raw, runs inference, and publishes derived metadata topics (object_detected, confidence_score). This adds immediate, queryable context to the raw data, making the entire dataset more valuable downstream without requiring expensive post-processing.\n\nEdge Storage and Management: The Role of ReductStore\n\nReductStore serves as the local time-series object storage solution on the edge device, purpose-built for high-volume blob data from sensors. Its lightweight nature and simple deployment via Snap or Docker make it ideally suited for resource-constrained edge environments. Architecturally, data is isolated within logical containers called buckets (e.g., pi_robot). This enables granular management of data streams, including distinct retention policies and replication rules on a per-bucket basis, providing crucial flexibility for complex robotics systems.\n\nData Capture and Segmentation with \n\nThe reductstore_agent is the critical ROS 2 node that bridges the ROS 2 ecosystem with the ReductStore database. It is responsible for recording specified topics into the local ReductStore instance as segmented MCAP files, governed by a declarative YAML configuration.\n\nKey configuration parameters and their architectural functions include:\n\n* url, api_token, bucket: These parameters define the connection to the local ReductStore instance, specifying the server address, authentication token, and the target bucket for storage.\n* include_topics: This list enables the principle of selective data persistence. It allows the architect to filter out unnecessary data at the source and focus recording efforts exclusively on valuable streams like /image_raw, /object_detected, /confidence_score, and /rosout for system diagnostics.\n* split (max_duration_s, max_size_bytes): These settings are fundamental to operational resilience. By automatically segmenting continuous data streams into smaller MCAP files based on time or size, the architecture prevents a single corrupted write or failed transfer from invalidating an entire recording session—a critical consideration in unstable edge environments. This segmentation also directly enhances the efficiency of the replication process.\n* compression (zstd): This parameter enables on-the-fly compression, which is essential for maximizing data density. Using an efficient algorithm like Zstandard significantly reduces the storage footprint on the edge device, increasing the amount of data that can be durably stored before offloading.\n\nWhile this intelligent local capture system guarantees data integrity at the edge, its value is fully realized only when synchronized with a central repository. The next section details the resilient replication architecture designed for this purpose.\n\n3. Real-Time Data Synchronization via Robust Replication\n\nCapturing data effectively on an edge device is only half the battle; the other is transferring it reliably to a central location for long-term storage, analysis, and model training. ReductStore's built-in replication feature provides the mechanism for achieving this synchronization with resilience and efficiency.\n\nThe Push-Based Replication Model\n\nThe architecture employs a push-based replication model, where the edge node actively sends new data segments to the central store as they are created. This approach is architecturally superior to traditional polling methods for edge devices, as it eliminates the resource overhead of a central server constantly querying the edge node for new data.\n\nCrucially, this model is inherently resilient to network instability. If a robot loses connectivity, the replication process pauses while data continues to be collected and queued locally. Once the network is restored, the replication task automatically resumes, pushing the queued data to the destination without manual intervention or data loss.\n\nConfiguring Replication for Central Data Aggregation\n\nThe replication link is defined by a set of parameters specifying the source, destination, and data entries, creating a durable, push-based data stream from edge to central store. This is configured on the source (edge) instance, establishing a one-way flow of information. The key parameters for a replication task are the Source Bucket on the edge device, the Destination URL of the central server, the Destination Bucket name, and the specific Entries (data streams) to be replicated. Once activated, the task monitors the source bucket and automatically forwards new data segments in real-time. The success of this data flow can be verified by observing the appearance of these segments in the destination bucket on the central store.\n\nThis robust replication mechanism completes the end-to-end data pipeline, ensuring a reliable flow of information from the sensor on the robot to a central platform ready for analysis.\n\n4. Production Best Practices and Scalability\n\nMoving from a single-robot implementation to a scalable, fleet-wide strategy requires adopting production-grade data management principles. The following three strategies are integral design principles for building a truly robust and economically viable system for large-scale operations.\n\nData Tiering and Segregation\n\nA core architectural principle is to separate ROS topics into different storage streams or pipelines based on their characteristics and purpose. This segregation allows for the application of distinct retention policies, replication rules, and access controls tailored to each data type.\n\nCategory\tExamples\tCharacteristics\nLightweight telemetry\tGPS, IMU, joint states, system status\tLow bandwidth, near real-time. Essential for real-time fleet monitoring and business intelligence dashboards.\nDownsampled sensor data\tLower framerate/resolution camera or lidar data\tMid-size. Excellent for remote operational monitoring and rapid incident triage without high bandwidth costs.\nFull-resolution data\tRaw camera frames, high-fps lidar, depth maps\tHigh volume (up to 1TB/hour). Critical for detailed debugging, root cause analysis, and ML model retraining.\n\nBy tiering data, an organization can replicate telemetry in real-time for live dashboards while only replicating high-resolution sensor data on demand or over a more cost-effective network connection.\n\nSelective Replication and On-Device Transformation (ELT)\n\nFor applications that generate extreme data volumes, a powerful ELT (Extract-Load-Transform) pattern is a core architectural strategy. This approach transforms the robot from a simple data source into an active participant in the data pipeline. High-fidelity data is stored locally on the robot's primary storage (e.g., an SSD), while only a downsampled or summarized version is replicated to the central server. For example, a robot could store 30 FPS raw video on its local drive but replicate only a 1 FPS stream to the cloud for remote monitoring. This strategy dramatically reduces network bandwidth consumption and central storage costs while ensuring the full-resolution data remains available on the device for high-priority retrieval.\n\nLong-Term Archiving with Cold Storage\n\nTo optimize costs for long-term data retention, a key business practice is to offload older data from the primary \"hot\" ReductStore instance to cheaper cold storage solutions, such as Google Cloud Storage or Amazon S3 Glacier. An automated policy can maintain the most recent data (e.g., 30 days) in the primary store for immediate access while archiving anything older. This practice ensures data remains accessible for future needs, such as retraining models on historical datasets, without incurring the high cost of primary storage.\n\nThese principles transform the base architecture into a flexible and economically sustainable system designed for long-term, large-scale robotics operations.\n\n5. Conclusion\n\nThis white paper has detailed a production-ready architectural blueprint for managing the complex data demands of edge robotics. It directly confronts the primary challenges of resource-constrained hardware, high-volume data streams, intermittent connectivity, and fleet scalability. By integrating the versatile ROS 2 ecosystem with the specialized capabilities of ReductStore, the described architecture provides a robust, scalable, and resilient solution for data acquisition, storage, and synchronization. The complete pipeline—from on-device ML enrichment and intelligent data segmentation to push-based replication and principles of production scalability—offers a solid foundation for any organization looking to harness the full value of its robotics data and accelerate its innovation cycle.\n",
      "tags": [
        "mcap",
        "data",
        "storage"
      ],
