    {
      "id": "4b20mt6h",
      "title": "RLPD - Reinforcement Learning with Prior Data",
      "content": " Content Reference:- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U7mDe4p4iQw&t=65s\n\n- The method relies on using offline data(prior trajetcories) to improve sample efficiency in online off-policy RL\nThe provided source is a transcript from a YouTube tutorial video titled \"RLPD with Isaac Sim\" from the \"robot mania\" channel. This tutorial focuses on the RLPD algorithm (Reinforcement Learning with Prior Data) and its implementation.\nHere's a comprehensive explanation of everything discussed in the source:\n1. Introduction to RLPD Algorithm\n• What is RLPD? RLPD stands for Reinforcement Learning with Prior Data.\n• Purpose: This method is designed to improve sample efficiency in online off-policy Reinforcement Learning (RL) by utilising offline data, such as expert trajectories.\n• Demonstration: The tutorial shows an agent that initially moves randomly and fails to reach its goal, but after training with RLPD, it becomes capable of reaching the goal \"decently well\".\n2. Challenges in Reinforcement Learning that RLPD Addresses\nThe tutorial first explains why sample inefficiency arises and the problems associated with using offline data directly:\n2.1. Sample Inefficiency Causes\n• Sparse Rewards: In many environments, rewards are only obtained for specific actions or states (e.g., reaching a goal). This means an agent might make many unsuccessful attempts before receiving any reward, leading to slow learning.\n• Random Exploration: Off-policy algorithms (like DQN, SAC, DDPG) often rely on extensive random exploration initially. This can lead to the collection of a vast amount of \"boring transitions\" before the agent stumbles upon something meaningful.\n2.2. Problems with Naively Mixing Online and Offline Data\nWhile adding high-quality trajectories (offline data) seems intuitive for accelerating learning, simply mixing online and offline data can be detrimental due to two main issues:\n• Distributional Shift: This occurs when an agent learns a policy using data from one distribution (the offline dataset) but then evaluates or updates its value function and policy on states and actions it hasn't encountered in that offline data.\n    ◦ Consequence: The Q-function or policy, trained on the offline dataset, might not cover the entire state-action space. If the learned policy starts selecting actions outside the distribution of the offline data, the model is forced to extrapolate, often resulting in inaccurate Q-value estimates.\n    ◦ Example: An agent trained to move on a green road using specific actions might take incorrect actions when encountering an unknown road.\n• Bootstrapping Error Accumulation: Off-policy RL algorithms use bootstrapping, meaning the current Q-value is estimated from the immediate reward plus the discounted value of the next state-action.\n    ◦ Consequence: If the Q-function is inaccurate on out-of-distribution states due to distributional shift, these errors don't just stay isolated; they propagate and amplify because each update uses previous, potentially wrong estimates.\n    ◦ Outcome: This accumulation of errors directly causes Q-value divergence.\n3. RLPD Improvements to Mitigate These Problems\nRLPD introduces three key improvements to address distributional shift and bootstrapping error accumulation:\n• 1. Replay Design:\n    ◦ For each training batch, 50% of the data is sampled from the online replay buffer, and the remaining 50% is sampled from the offline data buffer.\n    ◦ Benefit: This sampling strategy keeps the agent \"grounded\" in current online data while still leveraging the offline data for better coverage and early guidance during learning.\n• 2. Critic Regularisation via Ensembling:\n    ◦ At update time, combining estimates from several \"critics\" (multiple value functions) helps to reduce over-optimistic Q-values.\n    ◦ Finding: The original paper demonstrated that ensembles consistently outperform other regularisation methods like dropout and weight decay.\n• 3. Layer Normalisation in the Critic Network:\n    ◦ Layer normalisation is applied to the critic network.\n    ◦ Benefit: It implicitly limits the scale of Q-values, which in turn helps in reducing catastrophic value divergence.\n4. The Problem Solved in the Tutorial (Robot Navigation)\nThe tutorial applies RLPD to a specific simulation problem:\n• Environment: A 72x72 meter field, divided into nine large squares, with each large square further divided into nine small squares.\n• Start and Goal: The robot's start area is in the middle of the upper-left large square, and the goal area is in the middle of the lower-right large square.\n• Obstacles: Two black cubes are placed inside each large square, except for the large squares containing the start or goal areas. The location of these cube pairs changes randomly within their respective large squares in each episode.\n• Objective: To train the robot to move from the start to the goal area without colliding with the cubes.\n4.1. Robot's State, Action, and Reward System\n• State Space: The agent uses a LiDAR (LAR) scan taken every 18 degrees, along with the y-difference between the robot's coordinate and the centre of the goal area. The state space is represented as a one-dimensional array with 22 elements.\n• Action Space: The robot moves forward with constant velocity. The only action it can take is to steer the front wheels, so the action space is represented as a one-dimensional array with one element.\n• Reward System:\n    ◦ Positive Reward: Given if the distance to the goal in the current step is shorter than in the previous step.\n    ◦ Reduced Reward: Applied if the robot is closer to a cube than a predefined threshold value.\n    ◦ Negative Reward: Given if the robot hits a cube, or if the distance to the goal in the current step is larger than in the previous step.\n    ◦ Episode Termination: The episode ends immediately if the robot hits a cube.\n5. Tutorial Implementation Steps\nThe tutorial provides practical instructions for setting up and running the RLPD training:\n5.1. Prerequisites and Setup\n• Software: Viewers are expected to have ROS 2 Humble and Isaac Sim 4.5 installed.\n• File Organisation: Download and extract the RLPD tutorial zip file, then move the two folders (RLPD_data_creation and RLPD_Isaac) to the home directory.\n    ◦ RLPD_data_creation contains USD files for the environment and a script to generate offline data.\n    ◦ RLPD_Isaac contains files for training.\n5.2. Offline Data Generation\n• Script: Data is generated using the create_pkl.py Python script.\n• Nodes in create_pkl.py:\n    ◦ A node managing Isaac Sim.\n    ◦ A node getting robot position and orientation.\n    ◦ A node subscribing to the laser scanner.\n    ◦ A node calculating clashes between the robot and obstacles.\n    ◦ A node subscribing to a joystick (joypad).\n• Data Saving: Data is saved at the end of each episode and then compiled into a .pkl file after a predefined number of episodes.\n• Steps to Generate Data:\n    1. Build packages using the Colcon build command.\n    2. Launch the manual_operation_launch.py script.\n    3. Execute the create_pkl.py script.\n    4. Manually navigate the car to the goal using only the left stick of a PS4 controller.\n    5. After the program ends, the .pkl file will be saved.\n    6. Move this .pkl file to the train_data directory.\n5.3. Training Setup and Execution\n• Memory Management Issue: When using a LAR sensor in Isaac Sim, memory is not released, which can lead to an \"out of memory\" error during long training sessions.\n• Solution: To mitigate this, training-related calculations are run in the main thread, while Isaac Sim runs in a child thread. Isaac Sim is then restarted completely after a certain number of steps to avoid memory issues.\n• Required Packages: Before training, users must install necessary packages using the requirements.txt file.\n• Running Training: Execute the train_rlpd.py script.\n• Visualisation:\n    ◦ Training results can be viewed using TensorBoard.\n    ◦ For visualisation during the tutorial, training is run with an opened application window.\n    ◦ To save computational resources, it's recommended to set the headless argument to true; this hides the application window, but robot behaviour can still be observed using RViz.\n6. Training Results Analysis\nThe tutorial presents and explains the results after 35,000 training steps:\n• Actor Loss:\n    ◦ Trend: Steadily decreases towards -150.\n    ◦ Indication: A decreasing actor loss generally indicates that the policy is improving. This is because the actor is trained to minimise an equation where a large and positive Q-value makes the entire equation negative (as the entropy term is typically smaller in magnitude).\n    ◦ Observation: The Q-value is observed to be increasing throughout training.\n• Critic Loss:\n    ◦ Trend: Increases over training and shows some oscillations.\n    ◦ Indication: As the agent discovers higher-value behaviours, it is encouraged to explore new areas, leading to visits to more diverse states. This increased diversity can lead to oscillations in the critic loss.\n• Entropy:\n    ◦ Trend: Starts relatively high, then decreases towards -0.5.\n    ◦ Indication: Lower entropy signifies that the policy is becoming more deterministic. This aligns with the expected learning process: starting with broad exploration and then committing to effective actions.\n• Temperature Loss:\n    ◦ Trend: Quickly decays towards zero.\n    ◦ Indication: This means the entropy regularisation target is being satisfied, showing that the entropy adjustment mechanism is working correctly.\n\n\n\n# Reinforcement Learning Variants\n\nThis document provides a structured overview of reinforcement learning (RL) methods, focusing on **on-policy vs off-policy learning**, and extending to other key variants.\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 1. On-Policy vs Off-Policy\n\n* **On-Policy RL**\n\n  * Learns only from data generated by the *current policy*.\n  * Examples: **SARSA, REINFORCE, PPO**.\n\n* **Off-Policy RL**\n\n  * Learns from data generated by a *different behavior policy* (e.g., ε-greedy, random, human demos).\n  * Enables replay buffers, sample reuse, and better efficiency.\n  * Examples: **Q-learning, DQN, DDPG, TD3, SAC**.\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 2. Model-Free vs Model-Based\n\n* **Model-Free RL**\n\n  * No explicit model of environment dynamics.\n  * Subtypes:\n\n    * **Value-based**: learn value functions (e.g., Q-learning, DQN).\n    * **Policy-based**: directly optimize the policy (e.g., REINFORCE, PPO).\n    * **Actor-Critic**: combine both (e.g., A3C, DDPG).\n\n* **Model-Based RL**\n\n  * Learns a transition/reward model of the environment for planning.\n  * Examples: **MBPO, PETS, Dreamer**.\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 3. Online vs Offline (Batch) RL\n\n* **Online RL**\n\n  * Agent interacts with the environment while learning.\n\n* **Offline (Batch) RL**\n\n  * Learns solely from a fixed dataset without further environment interaction.\n  * Examples: **BCQ, CQL**.\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 4. Imitation and Inverse RL\n\n* **Imitation Learning**\n\n  * Learn from demonstrations (supervised or adversarial).\n  * Examples: **Behavioral Cloning, GAIL**.\n\n* **Inverse Reinforcement Learning (IRL)**\n\n  * Infers the reward function from expert demonstrations.\n  * Examples: **AIRL, MaxEnt IRL**.\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 5. RL Taxonomy Tree\n\n```text\nReinforcement Learning\n│\n├── On-Policy\n│   ├── Value-based (SARSA)\n│   ├── Policy-based (REINFORCE, PPO)\n│   └── Actor-Critic (A2C, A3C)\n│\n├── Off-Policy\n│   ├── Value-based (Q-learning, DQN)\n│   ├── Policy-based (Deterministic Policy Gradients)\n│   └── Actor-Critic (DDPG, TD3, SAC)\n│\n├── Model-Free\n│   └── (Value, Policy, Actor-Critic families)\n│\n├── Model-Based (MBPO, PETS, Dreamer)\n│\n├── Offline RL (BCQ, CQL)\n│\n└── Imitation / IRL\n    ├── Imitation (BC, GAIL)\n    └── Inverse RL (AIRL, MaxEnt IRL)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 Intuition Recap\n\n* **On-policy**: Learn from your *own shots*.\n* **Off-policy**: Learn from *others’ play footage*.\n* **Model-based**: *Imagine games in your head*.\n* **Offline RL**: *Train from a playbook only*.\n* **Imitation**: *Copy the expert*.\n* **IRL**: *Figure out what motivates the expert*.\n",
