      "id": "c41k7if7",
      "title": "Dynamic Obstacle Avoidance for Motion Planning",
      "content": "# 📘 Study Notes: Dynamic Obstacle Avoidance & Signed Distance Fields\n\n---\n\n## 1. Dynamic Obstacle Avoidance in MoveIt\n\n### How it works “out of the box”\n\n* MoveIt can handle dynamic obstacles **if**:\n\n  1. The **Planning Scene** is updated in real time (from perception → collision world).\n  2. The **execution strategy** allows re-planning during motion (hybrid planning, Servo).\n\n### Execution strategies\n\n* **Hybrid Planning (global + local):**\n\n  * Start with a global plan.\n  * Local planner monitors scene and re-plans on the fly if an obstacle appears.\n* **MoveIt Servo (reactive jog):**\n\n  * High-rate velocity controller with continuous collision checking.\n  * Great for teleop or sudden obstacle intrusion.\n\n### Key enablers\n\n* **Continuous collision checking in time** (not just waypoints).\n* **PlanningSceneMonitor** must be active and multi-threaded.\n* **Perception integration**: feed collision objects/occupancy from depth/LiDAR.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Current Trends in Dynamic Obstacle Avoidance Research\n\n* **GPU-accelerated planners (cuRobo / cuMotion):**\n\n  * Parallel optimization on GPU.\n  * Millisecond-scale re-planning.\n  * Integrates with SDFs for smooth trajectories.\n* **SDF-based collision layers (nvblox ESDF):**\n\n  * Real-time signed distance fields from depth sensors.\n  * Enables smooth clearance costs instead of binary collision checks.\n* **Hybrid planning architectures:**\n\n  * Global + local replanning.\n  * First-class feature in MoveIt 2.\n* **Safety filters with Control Barrier Functions (CBFs):**\n\n  * Mathematical safety “shield” around any planner or learned policy.\n* **Learned policies with constraints:**\n\n  * Diffusion or imitation policies guided by SDF/CBF constraints.\n* **Human-aware prediction:**\n\n  * Planning under uncertainty to account for human motion.\n\n---\n\n## 3. OctoMap vs. nvblox\n\n| Feature              | OctoMap                   | nvblox (TSDF + ESDF)             |\n| -------------------- | ------------------------- | -------------------------------- |\n| **Core idea**        | Occupancy (free/occupied) | Distance to nearest surface      |\n| **Data per voxel**   | Probability               | Signed distance                  |\n| **Query type**       | Is cell occupied?         | How far from obstacle?           |\n| **Planner use**      | Binary collision check    | Continuous clearance & gradients |\n| **Update speed**     | CPU, slower (octree)      | GPU, real-time                   |\n| **Dynamic handling** | Coarse                    | High-rate updates                |\n| **Resolution**       | Adaptive octree           | Dense voxel grid                 |\n| **Best for**         | Static mapping            | Reactive manipulation            |\n\n---\n\n## 4. TSDF vs. ESDF\n\n### TSDF (Truncated Signed Distance Field)\n\n* Stores distance to nearest **observed surface along a ray**.\n* Values truncated to a local band (e.g., ±5 cm).\n* Good for surface reconstruction & meshing.\n* **Local view** around surfaces.\n\n### ESDF (Euclidean Signed Distance Field)\n\n* Stores **shortest Euclidean distance** to any surface.\n* Computed from TSDF via distance transform.\n* Good for motion planning & collision avoidance.\n* **Global clearance map** (distance known everywhere).\n\n👉 In practice:\n**nvblox builds a TSDF → then derives an ESDF → publishes ESDF to planners.**\n\n---\n\n## 5. SDF Sign Convention\n\n* **Outside obstacle (free space):** Positive distance\n* **On the surface:** Zero\n* **Inside obstacle:** Negative distance\n\nThis is the standard convention in robotics (nvblox, MoveIt, cuRobo, physics engines).\n⚠️ Some graphics papers flip this, so always check.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Direction vs. Sign\n\n* **Sign** only encodes inside/outside.\n* **Gradient (∇SDF)** gives the **direction of increasing clearance**.\n* Example:\n\n  * At the center of a square room, distances to all walls are **positive** and equal.\n  * No “left wall = negative, right wall = positive.”\n  * If you move closer to the right wall, nearest distance = smaller positive.\n  * Inside the wall → negative value.\n  * Gradient points toward nearest free space.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Intuition & Analogies\n\n* **SDF as a heat map:**\n\n  * Positive = safe regions.\n  * Zero = surface boundary.\n  * Negative = inside obstacle.\n* **OctoMap = binary grid** (occupied vs. free).\n* **ESDF = topographic map of clearance** (smooth hills of safety).\n* **TSDF = local fog around observed surfaces.**\n\n---\n\n## 8. Practical Integration Pipeline\n\n* **Perception:** Depth camera → nvblox (TSDF → ESDF).\n* **Scene Update:** nvblox publishes ESDF to MoveIt’s Planning Scene.\n* **Planner:**\n\n  * Start with OMPL/TrajOpt.\n  * For high reactivity, switch to cuMotion (GPU planner).\n* **Execution:** Hybrid Planning or Servo for online re-planning.\n\n---\n\n✅ **Big Picture Takeaway:**\n\n* OctoMap = slow, binary → safe but conservative.\n* nvblox ESDF = fast, smooth, GPU-native → ideal for dynamic, human-in-the-loop manipulation.\n* Planners + Servo + Hybrid Execution turn this into **real-time dynamic obstacle avoidance**.\n",
      "tags": [
        "obstacleavoidance",
        "motionplanning",
        "nvblox",
        "moveit"
      ],
