    {
      "id": "cfrkbu5b",
      "title": "Servo using Moveit2 ROS2",
      "content": "### Introduction to MoveIt Servo\n \n * **MoveIt Servo is a real-time component of MoveIt** designed for **real-time robot jogging**.\n * It performs calculations **faster than one kilohertz**, exceeding the requirements of most robots.\n * Key applications include **visual servoing, teleoperation (especially for medical tasks), and contact tasks** where the robot needs to react in real-time to unpredictable events.\n * The goal is to achieve **at least a kilohertz control rate**.\n \n ### Core Functionalities\n \n * **Real-time Robot Jogging**: MoveIt Servo enables robots to be jogged in real-time, with calculations performed at high speeds.\n * **Predictable Straight-Line Motion**: The Jacobian-based approach ensures that the end-effector follows a **predictable straight-line path**, which is vital for sensitive applications like surgery to avoid erratic movements.\n * **Local Optimisation**:\n * It **minimises tracking error locally**.\n * It **minimises joint velocities locally**.\n * A side effect is that it's **optimally good at avoiding singularities locally**.\n * **Versatility with Degrees of Freedom (DoF)**:\n * Works with **any number of DoF**.\n * For **under-actuated systems** (e.g., a 5-DoF arm tracking a 6-DoF pose), it minimises pose error, getting as close as possible with the available joints.\n * It also supports **over-actuated systems** (robots with more than six joints).\n * **Pose Tracking**: A newer feature allowing users to send an **absolute Cartesian pose** to the end-effector, rather than just relative changes.\n * Uses a **control loop** (similar to a PID controller).\n * Features a **\"drift dimension\"** which eliminates an output direction of less concern (e.g., only controlling orientation), making the manipulator redundant and less susceptible to singularities for certain tasks.\n * **Singularity Avoidance**:\n * It has a **threshold to stop the robot** before it drives into a singularity, preventing unpredictable \"divide by zero\" errors and erratic behaviour.\n * It also **stops before hitting joint limits and collisions**.\n \n ### Technical Underpinnings\n \n * **Differential Kinematics**:\n * At its core, MoveIt Servo uses **differential kinematics**.\n * It employs a **Jacobian matrix** (a collection of partial derivatives) that relates changes in joint angles to changes in the end-effector's Cartesian pose.\n * **Calculation Process**: A desired change in Cartesian pose (e.g., from a joystick or image) is fed in, multiplied by the **inverted Jacobian matrix**, to produce a change in joint angles. This change is added to the current joint positions to get the new target for the robot.\n * **Re-linearisation**: The Jacobian matrix is **calculated on the fly and re-linearised with each iteration** to accurately reflect the robot's current configuration. This can be computationally expensive for a large number of joints.\n * **Real-Time Definition**:\n * MoveIt Servo currently achieves **soft real-time**, meaning it makes its best effort to meet deadlines, but timeliness is not guaranteed. Missing a deadline is not catastrophic.\n * It is not yet **hard real-time** (guaranteed timeliness) due to factors like running on a non-real-time kernel, dynamic memory allocation in ROS 1 publishers/subscribers, and the use of mutexes for thread synchronisation.\n * **ROS Compatibility**:\n * **Originally developed for ROS 1**, but has been **ported to MoveIt 2 (ROS 2)** and is now stable and functional.\n * **ROS 2 control** has been designed with real-time in mind, avoiding dynamic memory allocation and mutexes at lower levels, which improves real-time potential once the message reaches the control stack.\n * **Collision Checking**:\n * It is computationally intensive, typically taking **0.1 to 5 milliseconds per iteration**, which is too slow for the main real-time control thread.\n * To address this, collision checking runs in a **separate thread**, and its output is combined with the main control logic to decelerate the robot based on proximity to a collision.\n * Recent optimisations have **sped up collision checking runtime by approximately 50%** by identifying and making variables allocated in a loop **thread-local**, avoiding recreation in each iteration. This is most beneficial for complex variables with non-trivial constructors.\n * **Handling Singularities (Damped Least Squares)**:\n * Near singularities, the Jacobian becomes unstable to invert, and joint velocities can become infinite.\n * **Damped Least Squares** involves adding a damping factor to the diagonal of the Jacobian matrix during inversion, which stabilises the system at the cost of some tracking error.\n * **Selectively Damped Least Squares** adds different weights to different parts of the diagonal, offering more refined control.\n * An approach proposed is to switch to damped least squares only when near a singularity, keeping damping close to zero otherwise.\n * **Null Space**:\n * For **over-actuated robots** (e.g., a 7-DoF robot with a 6-DoF task), the extra degree of freedom (the null space of the Jacobian) can be used to achieve **secondary objectives**.\n * This includes avoiding joint limits or maximising distance to collisions, often through a **\"stack of tasks\" hierarchy**.\n \n ### Real-World Applications\n \n * **Visual Servoing**: Real-time tracking of a visual target, such as a robot following an image.\n * **Teleoperation**: Remote control of robots, particularly important in **medical applications and surgery** for precise and safe movements.\n * **Contact Tasks**: Enabling robots to **react in real-time to unexpected contact** with objects.\n * **Specific Pose Tracking**:\n * A camera stays pointed at a gripper while the robot moves.\n * A camera automatically tracking a valve using pose information from gmapping while the robot is driven.\n\n\n # Important takeaways:\n * Only a certain set of controllers works with Telop/Servo logic, although the robot could work with\n   all kinds of controllers.\n * Similarly, Moveit plans can generally work only with FollowJointTrajectory type controllers\n * The system design for the workflow should be as follows:\n    - There is a node that can send incremental axis movement. In this case, the Joy Node.\n    - The controller_to_servo_node from moveit_servo is the one responsible for subscribing to the joy node outputs and converting them to\n      /servo_node/delta_twist_cmds and /servo_node/delta_joint_cmds that is accepted by the servo node, which does the differential IK\n * The output of the differential IK from the Servo Node is passed to the respective controllers that talk to the robot in sim or real\n",
      "tags": [
        "servo",
        "moveit2",
        "ros",
        "teleop"
      ],
