    {
      "id": "y9etz0jc",
      "title": "Storage and Manage ROS Data - Part 2",
      "content": "# Multimodal IL Data: Storage, Logging, Timing & Export (README Notes)\n\n## TL;DR (Practical Playbook)\n\n1. **Record** demos as **MCAP** (rosbag2-mcap) with **Zstd** compression and **32 MB** chunks.  \n2. **Images pre-compressed** at the source (JPEG/H.264; depth as PNG). Don’t log raw RGB unless you must.  \n3. **Batch high-rate numeric topics** (e.g., joints/wrench) into arrays (50–200 samples/message).  \n4. **Unify clocks** (ROS wall time) and add a **1 Hz `/heartbeat`** topic to detect/correct drift.  \n5. **Inspect** logs; measure topic offsets vs heartbeat.  \n6. **Export shards** for training: **WebDataset** (frame-centric) or **Parquet/Zarr** (sequence-centric).  \n7. **Train** from shards; keep MCAP as durable source-of-truth.\n\n---\n\n## NumPy vs MCAP — When to Use What\n\n| Aspect | NumPy (`.npy` / `.npz`) | MCAP / rosbag2-mcap |\n|---|---|---|\n| Best for | Single/few large arrays, static tensors | **Streaming**, multi-topic, time-stamped logs |\n| Space | `.npy` ≈ raw+tiny header; `.npz`=ZIP/deflate | Per-message overhead; **Zstd chunk** compression |\n| Speed | Bulk load/save is very fast | High-throughput append; **fast time/topic slicing** |\n| Structure | No timestamps/topics/index | **Topics, timestamps, index, metadata, integrity** |\n| Ergonomics | Painful for long, time-stamped sessions | **Ideal** for demos, slicing, replay |\n\n**Rule:** Log with **MCAP**, then export to training shards. Use NumPy only for final, de-timestamped arrays.\n\n---\n\n## Images: “Already-Compressed” at the Source\n\n- Raw 1080p RGB ≈ **~6 MB/frame** → huge files.  \n- **Compress before logging:**  \n  - RGB: **JPEG** (quality 90–95) or **H.264/H.265**  \n  - Depth: **PNG** (lossless) or device-native  \n- MCAP’s Zstd won’t beat JPEG/H.264 on image entropy → store compressed frames directly.  \n- For IL, moderate JPEG artifacts rarely hurt; often act as benign augmentation.\n\n---\n\n## What to Log (Per Modality)\n\n| Modality | Topic Type | Encoding | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| RGB | `sensor_msgs/CompressedImage` | JPEG/H.264 | Avoid raw RGB |\n| Depth | `sensor_msgs/Image` or compressed | PNG / device-native | Keep metric depth integrity |\n| Joint state, q̇, τ, TCP, wrench | **Custom “Batch” messages** | Float arrays batched | 50–200 samples/msg |\n| Events/labels | Small struct/JSON | — | Start/stop, phases |\n| Calibration | MCAP metadata + JSON | — | Intrinsics/extrinsics, frames, units |\n\n**MCAP settings (good defaults):**\n```yaml\ncompression: zstd\ncompression_level: 5\nchunk_size_mb: 32\n```\n\n---\n\n## Hz vs Seconds (and Why Timing Matters)\n\n- **Hz = times per second**  \n  - Camera @ **30 Hz** ⇒ one frame every **33 ms**  \n  - Robot state @ **125 Hz** ⇒ one sample every **8 ms**  \n  - Heartbeat @ **1 Hz** ⇒ one tick every **1 s**\n\nPolicies need **aligned** modalities. Even **±100–200 ms** skew can corrupt supervision.\n\n---\n\n## Why Drift Happens (Even in ROS/ROS 2)\n\n- Different time sources: hardware timestamps vs ROS/wall/steady clocks.  \n- Multi-machine without **NTP/chrony/PTP** → system clock offsets.  \n- **Header time** (publisher) vs **log time** (recorder receive) differ due to network/queues.  \n- Mixed `/use_sim_time` vs wall time.\n\n**Best practice:** Choose one clock domain (ROS wall time), stamp consistently, sync machines, and preserve both header+log times.\n\n---\n\n## Heartbeat: The Metronome to Detect & Correct Drift\n\n**What:** A tiny node publishes `/heartbeat` at **1 Hz** with the **reference time** (ROS wall time).  \n**Why:** It’s a **ground-truth yardstick** in the bag. Around `/heartbeat = 10.0 s`, all topics should cluster near 10.0 s.  \n- If camera frames are ≈ 10.0 s but robot states are ≈ **10.2 s**, you’ve measured a **+200 ms** offset.  \n- Use that to **shift/resample/interpolate** during preprocessing → modalities re-align.\n\n**Minimal ROS 2 (Python) Heartbeat Node**\n```python\n# heartbeat_node.py\nimport rclpy\nfrom rclpy.node import Node\nfrom std_msgs.msg import Float64\n\nclass Heartbeat(Node):\n    def __init__(self):\n        super().__init__('heartbeat')\n        self.pub = self.create_publisher(Float64, '/heartbeat', 10)\n        self.timer = self.create_timer(1.0, self.tick)  # 1 Hz\n\n    def tick(self):\n        now = self.get_clock().now().nanoseconds / 1e9  # seconds\n        msg = Float64()\n        msg.data = now\n        self.pub.publish(msg)\n\ndef main():\n    rclpy.init()\n    node = Heartbeat()\n    rclpy.spin(node)\n    node.destroy_node()\n    rclpy.shutdown()\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    main()\n```\n\n---\n\n## From Raw Logs to Training-Ready Shards\n\n### A) Frame-Centric (Vision-Conditioned Policies) — **WebDataset**\n- Sample = **one frame** + nearest robot state.  \n- Shard into `.tar` files (e.g., 1 000 samples/shard):\n  ```\n  sample-000123.jpg\n  sample-000123.depth.png          # optional\n  sample-000123.state.npz          # q, qd, τ, TCP, wrench\n  sample-000123.json               # timestamp, camera id, label\n  ```\n\n### B) Sequence-Centric (History Windows) — **Parquet/Zarr**\n- Sample = fixed window (e.g., 1–3 s).  \n- Parquet for time-series + file paths to frames, or Zarr/HDF5 with chunked arrays.\n\n**Rule of thumb:** WebDataset for frame-conditioned; Parquet/Zarr for sequence models and analytics.\n\n---\n\n## Alignment Algorithm (Preprocessing)\n\n1. Choose a **training timeline** (e.g., 10–30 Hz).  \n2. For each frame timestamp `t`:  \n   - Pick **nearest** or **interpolated** robot state at `t`.  \n   - Enforce max skew (e.g., ≤ 40 ms), drop outliers.  \n3. If a constant offset is measured vs heartbeat, **subtract it** first.  \n4. Slice episodes by events or fixed windows.  \n5. Write shards with consistent schemas & versioned metadata.\n\n---\n\n## Pitfalls to Avoid\n\n- Logging **raw RGB** → massive bags, slow I/O.  \n- **Unbatched** high-rate floats → too many tiny messages (overhead dominates).  \n- **Mixed clocks** without a reference → silent drift.  \n- Training directly from MCAP → slower iteration; export shards instead.  \n- One giant `.npz` per session → painful slicing/versioning.\n\n---\n\n## Suggested Repo Layout & CLI\n\n```\nrobot-il-logger/\n  pyproject.toml\n  src/robot_il_logger/\n    record.py              # ROS/RTDE → MCAP (JPEG images, batched numeric)\n    inspect.py             # Topics, rates, spans; drift vs heartbeat\n    slice.py               # Cut MCAP by [t0, t1], topic filters\n    export_webdataset.py   # MCAP → WebDataset shards (frame-centric)\n    export_parquet.py      # MCAP → Parquet/Zarr (sequence-centric)\n    schemas.py             # Typed schemas for state/events/metadata\n    utils/\n      time_sync.py         # drift estimation, resampling/interp\n      compression.py       # JPEG params, Zstd helpers\n      calibration.py       # persist/load intrinsics/extrinsics\n  configs/\n    record.yaml            # topics, batching, chunk size, compression\n    export_frame.yaml      # fps, shard size, splits, jpeg quality\n    export_seq.yaml        # window length/stride, parquet schema\n  README.md\n  examples/\n    demo_record.sh\n    demo_export.sh\n```\n\n**CLI (Typer/Click examples)**\n```bash\n# Record a run\nilrec record --config configs/record.yaml --out runs/2025-09-11_run01.mcap\n\n# Inspect and sanity-check timing\nilrec inspect runs/2025-09-11_run01.mcap\n\n# Slice an episode by time\nilrec slice runs/2025-09-11_run01.mcap --t0 120s --t1 480s -o runs/run01_ep1.mcap\n\n# Export to training shards (frame-centric)\nilrec export webdataset runs/run01_ep1.mcap   --config configs/export_frame.yaml   -o datasets/robot_il_v1\n```\n\n**`configs/record.yaml` (baseline)**\n```yaml\nmcap:\n  compression: zstd\n  compression_level: 5\n  chunk_size_mb: 32\n\ntopics:\n  - name: /camera/color/compressed\n    type: sensor_msgs/msg/CompressedImage\n\n  - name: /robot/joint_states_batched\n    type: robot_il/JointStateBatch\n    batch: 100\n\n  - name: /robot/wrench_batched\n    type: robot_il/WrenchBatch\n    batch: 200\n\n  - name: /events\n    type: robot_il/Event\n\nheartbeat:\n  enable: true\n  topic: /heartbeat\n\ncalibration:\n  save_into_mcap_metadata: true\n```\n\n**`configs/export_frame.yaml` (example)**\n```yaml\nsample_rate_hz: 10\nalign:\n  lookahead_ms: 50\n  require_all_modalities: true\nwebdataset:\n  samples_per_shard: 1000\n  splits: {train: 0.9, val: 0.1}\n  jpeg_quality: 90\n  keep_original_timestamps: true\n```\n---\n\n## Checklists\n\n**Recording Checklist**\n- [ ] Cameras publish **CompressedImage** (JPEG/H.264)  \n- [ ] Depth uses **PNG** or device-native compression  \n- [ ] High-rate numeric topics **batched** (50–200 samples/msg)  \n- [ ] MCAP **zstd**, **level 5**, **chunk 32 MB**  \n- [ ] All publishers stamp with **same ROS clock**  \n- [ ] **/heartbeat** at 1 Hz enabled  \n- [ ] Calibration saved in metadata\n\n**Preprocessing Checklist**\n- [ ] Inspect topic spans & rates  \n- [ ] Measure per-topic **offset vs heartbeat**  \n- [ ] **Shift/resample/interpolate** to common timeline  \n- [ ] Export **WebDataset** (frame) or **Parquet/Zarr** (sequence)  \n- [ ] Version schemas & metadata\n\n---\n\n## Scaling & Versioning\n\n- **Shard** datasets (balanced shard sizes) for multi-GPU throughput.  \n- **Schema versioning** in code (`schemas.py`) to evolve fields safely.  \n- **Stateless converters** (MCAP → shards) so you can re-export when labels/windows change.  \n- Keep **MCAP logs immutable**; rebuild shards as needed.\n\n---\n\n**End of Notes**  \nDrop this into your README and iterate. If you want, I can scaffold the repo (package + CLI + example nodes) so you can start recording/exporting immediately.",
