    {
      "id": "vu1ytbk9",
      "title": "Controller Activation & Test Publisher Debugging",
      "content": "# Controller Activation & Test Publisher Debugging — Lessons Learned\n\n### **What was the challenge?**\n\n* Could not activate or use the `joint_trajectory_controller` (or UR’s `scaled_joint_trajectory_controller`).\n* `ros2 control switch_controllers` failed with deprecated flags and strict-mode errors.\n* Controllers stayed inactive/unconfigured.\n* UR’s test publisher kept reporting:\n  *“Start configuration is not within configured limits!”*\n  and never executed a trajectory.\n\n---\n\n### **Why did it occur?**\n\n1. **CLI changes** → `--start/--stop` were deprecated; new flags are `--activate/--deactivate`.\n2. **Strict mode** → `--strict` aborts if you try to deactivate already inactive controllers.\n3. **Controller state mismatch** → Controllers were only “loaded” but not “active.”\n4. **Test publisher config issues**:\n\n   * Node name didn’t match YAML parameter block → wrong controller targeted.\n   * `check_starting_point: true` with **tiny limits (±0.1 rad)** → publisher always rejected current joint state.\n\n---\n\n### **How did we tackle it?**\n\n**Controller activation**\n\n```bash\nros2 control set_controller_state joint_trajectory_controller active\n# or\nros2 control switch_controllers \\\n  --activate scaled_joint_trajectory_controller \\\n  --deactivate joint_trajectory_controller forward_position_controller \\\n  --best_effort --timeout 5\n```\n\n**Verification**\n\n* Check controller states:\n\n  ```bash\n  ros2 control list_controllers -v\n  ```\n* Verify action server exists:\n\n  ```bash\n  ros2 action list | grep follow_joint_trajectory\n  ```\n* Send a direct goal → worked cleanly:\n\n  ```bash\n  ros2 action send_goal /joint_trajectory_controller/follow_joint_trajectory \\\n    control_msgs/action/FollowJointTrajectory \"{\n      trajectory: {\n        joint_names: ['shoulder_pan_joint','shoulder_lift_joint','elbow_joint','wrist_1_joint','wrist_2_joint','wrist_3_joint'],\n        points: [{ positions: [0.0,-1.57,0,0,0,0], time_from_start: {sec: 4} }]\n      }}\"\n  ```\n\n**Fixing the test publisher**\n\n* Match node name (`publisher_scaled_joint_trajectory_controller`) to the YAML block you’re using.\n* Disable or widen limits:\n\n  ```yaml\n  check_starting_point: false\n  ```\n\n  or:\n\n  ```yaml\n  starting_point_limits:\n    shoulder_pan_joint: [-6.3, 6.3]\n    shoulder_lift_joint: [-3.14, 0.0]\n    elbow_joint: [-6.3, 6.3]\n    wrist_1_joint: [-6.3, 6.3]\n    wrist_2_joint: [-6.3, 6.3]\n    wrist_3_joint: [-6.3, 6.3]\n  ```\n* If publishing to the scaled controller, add a remap:\n\n  ```python\n  remappings=[('/joint_trajectory_controller/joint_trajectory',\n               '/scaled_joint_trajectory_controller/joint_trajectory')]\n  ```\n\n**Extra polish**\n\n* Create a custom YAML‑driven trajectory publisher (no start‑limit gate) for repeatable testing.\n* Suppress Fast-DDS SHM logs (benign):\n\n  ```bash\n  export RMW_FASTRTPS_TRANSPORT=udp\n  ```\n\n---\n\n### **✅ Outcome**\n\n* Controllers now activate reliably.\n* Direct `FollowJointTrajectory` goals succeed.\n* Root cause was the test publisher’s overly strict starting‑point checks (and a node/param mismatch), not the controller or robot.\n",
      "tags": [
        "learning",
        "challenges"
      ],
      "projectId": "y9081w3r",
      "dateIndex": null,
      "type": "note",
      "pinned": false,
      "createdAt": "2025-10-03T00:49:28.597Z",
      "updatedAt": "2025-10-03T00:49:41.411Z",
      "attachments": [],
      "links": [],
      "deletedAt": null
