    {
      "id": "3rl6e8xf",
      "title": "Differentiable Simulation for Deformable Object Manipulation",
      "content": "Interactive Perception and Robotics Learning Lab\n\n\nWhy do we care about the Differentiability of Simulation?\nThe Differentiability element helps to implement the Gradient descent-like optimization algorithm to obtain numerical solutions or local minimas\n\nThe promise of Differentiable Simulation\n- Gradient-based optimization of any loss function(Sim2real, reward, or cost)\nwrt to \n  - policy parameters\n  - geometry parameters\n  - physics parameters\n\nBased on any of the above, an optimization process can be performed using data from both simulation and real-world scenarios.\n\nImportant references describing problems of simulating non-rigid objects @\n- Fundamental Challenges in Deep Learning for Stiff Contact Dynamics\n- Do Differentiable Simulators Give Better Policy Gradients?",
      "tags": [],
      "projectId": "tikubsii",
      "dateIndex": null,
      "type": "note",
      "pinned": false,
      "createdAt": "2025-10-18T21:34:27.424Z",
      "updatedAt": "2025-10-19T00:26:44.298Z",
      "attachments": [],
      "links": [],
      "deletedAt": null
    },
    {
      "id": "q9hb0hrm",
      "title": "Transferring Robot Learning Policies from SIM2REAL",
      "content": "Challenges in RL:\n- Sample Inefficiency\n  - RL is typically sample inefficient. For a policy to converge, typically 10mil to 1bil data samples are required\n  - Multiple such training instances of 10mil to 1bil data samples are required for proper convergence.\n\n- Safety Concerns:\n  - The robot's behaviour is erratic and unpredictable, hence it is not recommended to be tried out in the real robot before full validation.\n\n- Practical Challenges:\n  - Training on the real robot is cumbersome as there can't be clean control of the environment\n\n\nSimulation Benefits:\n- 1 sec equates to 27 minutes of real-world experience\n- access to privileged information\n- ability to generate an infinite number of scenarios\n\n\nWhat is the Reality Gap?\n- The two domains talked about in the research community are:\n  - Source Domain (Simulation)\n  - Target Domain (Real world)\n\n\nDomains refer to all the conditions a robot might encounter, from terrain conditions to motor parameters to every other factor that defines its environment\n\nThe major reasons leading to the Reality Gaps are:\n- Approximation Errors, Model Errors, and Unmodelled Dynamics error\n\nApproximation Errors:\n- Caused by the inherent limitations of simulation in replicating the real-world physics\n\nModel Errors:\n- Inaccuracies in representing the physical robot and its environment\n  - Link Lengths, body masses, and friction coefficients mismatch\n  - Manufacturing tolerance and wear and tear \n\nUnmodelled Dynamics:\n- Sensor noise and actuator inaccuracies\n- System delays, including network latency and actuator response times\n\nSolutions:\ndomain randomization, real-to-sim transfer, and behavior regularization\n\n\nDomain Randomization\n  Domain randomization is a key technique for expanding our simulation domain and improving system robustness. Here's how we implement it:\n\n  Randomize Physical Parameters\n  We modify various physical attributes of our simulated environment:\n\n    Body mass properties of the robot and manipulated objects\n    Joint parameters for different movement characteristics\n    Friction coefficients between the various surfaces\n\n  Randomize Shapes\n  We vary the physical forms in our simulation:\n  \n    Terrain variations to expose the robot to different ground conditions\n    Object shapes and sizes for grasping tasks, helping the robot learn general concepts rather than specific instances\n\n  Randomize Tasks\n  We introduce variability in how tasks are performed:\n\n    Random initial conditions for robot joint states\n    Varied object positions and orientations\n    Diverse command sets, such as different target velocities\n\n\n    \n  Add Perturbations\n  To build robustness, we incorporate various disturbances:\n\n    Observation noise, particularly for naturally noisy signals like joint velocities, or data coming from an inertial measurement unit (IMU)\n    Physical pushes to develop recovery behaviors\n\n  Visual Randomization\n    Texture variations across different surfaces\n    Color modifications throughout the environment\n    Lighting conditions and intensities\n    Camera parameters to simulate different viewing conditions\n    Need to account for their characteristic noise patterns\n\n\n\n\n\n\n",
