    {
      "id": "jelnqvnn",
      "title": "Automated Data Collection Pipeline - Data Collection Quality Analysis",
      "content": "After implementing the data collection script, taking inspiration from ROSETTA work, the following are the key takeaways:\n- Currently, for the camera ROS graphs, the 'use sim time' is not enabled, and also the recording is kept to 'receive' and not 'header'\n  - Within the same episode, each camera tends to have incoherent frames recorded.\n    - In some episodes, there are even frames bleeding in from the previous episodes, and also, filling in random frames from the middle at the start.\n\nHypothesis:\n  - Not using the sim time and thereby relying on the receive timestamp over the header timestamp\n\nTests:\n  - Use the CLI rosbag record 3 times and evaluate if there is frame incoherence between each camera\n  - Use hot keys to record and evaluate if there is frame incoherence between each camera\n    Key Insights:\n      - The number of frames is not always the same for each of the cameras in the setup\n      - There is incoherence \nIf yes to the above,\n  - Check if all the frames consistently show the same behaviour\nIf yes\n  - Do more analysis to see if there are any configuration differences between each\nIf not\n  - It is purely due to not sticking to one single clock-based timeline\n\n\n\nAnother issue that casually came into my notice during the Automatic Data Collection is:\n - The Action Command topic, which consolidates and publishes the target joint states set for both the gripper and arm controller, has two issues:\n  - Initially, at times when the controller for neither the arm nor the gripper was invoked, it was publishing zero values, as a result of which a significant portion of the commanded trajectory of the robot was dominated by zero values.\n  - Secondly, when the action command output was relayed to the Isaacsim subscriber, the velocity values of each joint were also registered, which violated the stiffness-damping settings set in the Isaacsim, thereby leading to weird behaviour of the robot. \n  - Finally, another critical issue that was noticed was time misalignment between the commanded actions, that is, the Action Command, and the resulting response, that is, the actual joint states themselves. The expective behaviour is for the action commands to have a predictive nature as far as the resulting joint states are concerned.\n    - The way it was addressed was by using the timestamp from the headers of the controller itself, rather than using the 'time.now' itself \n  ",
      "tags": [],
      "projectId": "c7szb5bi",
      "dateIndex": null,
      "type": "note",
      "pinned": false,
      "createdAt": "2025-11-20T23:58:23.352Z",
      "updatedAt": "2025-11-24T05:03:59.197Z",
      "attachments": [],
      "links": [],
      "deletedAt": null
    },
