    {
      "id": "5gdycq47",
      "title": "2026-02-25 — Daily",
      "content": "# Top 3\n- [ ] \n- [ ] \n- [ ] \n\n## Tasks\n\n## Journal\n\n## Wins\n\n\n## Tedx - The best way to get good at something\n\n- Everyone samples a variety of skills or passions until they hyperspecialize in something and it's just no one notices this organic evolution of theirs.\n- Alot often people who have build incredible things in the past are people who have multitude of skills and had the creativity to put them together build something from the intersection of all those.\n- \"For a healthy eccosystem we need both birds and frogs\"\n\n \n## What is the best way to give a presentation?\n- The idea is to choose the best way that works best for your style\n  - One could be to put together a solid script and go by it word to word in a fully memorized fashion.\n  - Come up with plan without centering it around a rigid script\n \n- For most speakers the first option works the best way where they should write a script and go by it enough times that it has become a part of your system now\n- Also sometimes it becomes less intresting for audience to connect to a speaker who just solely recites his prepared script\n- So the key is to learn your script enough so that you go past the stage where it would feel like a recited script to actually sounding like something you know as its part of your system and also you are passionate about.\n- Another important question to ask yourself is what kind of languge you want to use?\n  - Spoken or Written language?\n\n",
      "tags": [],
      "projectId": null,
      "dateIndex": "2026-02-25",
      "type": "daily",
      "pinned": false,
      "createdAt": "2026-02-25T18:09:47.720Z",
      "updatedAt": "2026-02-26T04:26:36.134Z",
      "attachments": [],
      "links": [],
      "journal": "",
      "mood": "😐"
    },
