    {
      "id": "9klkecrk",
      "title": "Daily Research Read - Self Supervised Learning, JEPA, World Models and the Future of AI",
      "content": "Why to abandon RL?\n- Incredibly inefficient at data sampling\n- The ideal way for systems to learn is for it to teach the good representation of the world and world models from observations.\n- If you have a world model you can use it to plan a sequence of actions to arrive at goal.\n- Strenthen your world model by exploring regions of it using RL where you think the understanding of the world model is weak.\n\nRef: _https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yUmDRxV0krg&t=111s_\n\nLimitations of the current AI Models:\n - Humans and animals have mental models of the world\n - Their behaviour is driven by objectives\n - They can reason and plan complex action sequences\n\nAlthough neural networks are functional approximator not all functions especially ones that define the complex working of the human intelligence can be approximated by Feed Forward Network\n\nWhat are the requirements of Advanced Machine Intelligence\n- Systems that learn world models from sensory inputs\n  - learn intuitive physics from videos\n- Systems that have persistent memory\n  - large scale associative memories\n- Systems that can plan actions\n  - So as to fulfil an objective\n- Systems that can reason\n  - Inventing new solutions to unseen problems\n- Systems that are controllable and safe\n  - By design, not by fine-tuning\n\n**A four year old is likely to have seen more data than the biggest LLM out there**\n - Although someone could argue that most part of it is visual data which are fundamentally redundant in nature\n - However this again underscores the fact for any kind of implicit learning what is more required is redundancy over the quantity of data itself\n\nEven during Inference the most opted technique at the moment is to rely on the trained parameters of a neural network to give an additive multiple of the inputs as the output\ninstead what it should be is an inference that takes origin as result of an optimization of an objective hence the way to go about is **Energy-Based Models**\n\nSo the fundamental idea is as shown in the image 1 as below where all inference pipelines concieve the inputs and generate a representation of it which has to be further acted upon by a function like Neural Network with the aim to optimize an objective that strives to understant the compatibility or incompatibility of the inputs to the outputs. The degree of compatibility or\nincompatibility is to be measured using a scalar that could be called as Energy which could assume any non-negative values.\n\n",
      "tags": [],
      "projectId": "tikubsii",
      "dateIndex": null,
      "type": "note",
      "pinned": false,
      "createdAt": "2026-02-27T03:43:05.910Z",
      "updatedAt": "2026-03-08T06:23:56.071Z",
      "attachments": [
        {
          "id": "v58c9s61",
          "name": "Screenshot 2026-03-07 221616.png",
          "type": "image/png",
          "size": 587292
        }
      ],
      "links": [
        "dbfu8rxm"
      ],
      "deletedAt": null
