      "id": "truubky7",
      "title": "Daily Research Read - Self Supervised Learning, JEPA, World Models and the Future of AI - Part 3",
      "content": "Autoregressive models are fundamentally flawed and requires an absolute redesign\n- As humans we dont think answers as one word after another rather rather we think about an abstract concept/thought that represent this answer and put them into words\n\nAE Collapse Prevention through Architectura Constraints\n  - No connection between an input and its corresponding output\n \n\nWorld Model\n- The fundamental idea of a world model is a model  that can take the current set of states as input pass it through an encoder and given the input at that instant decode the next possible state of the environment.\n- The natural thought was to use GAI to train and produce continuous data  \n  - It does work for discreete domains, not high dim domains\n\nThe initial idea was to use a sequence of frames from a video - pass it through an encoder then use the encoded latent vector with a masking action to decode the next frames plausible \nHowever the model as expected ended up producing an average of all possible pixels in the frames\n - As the world is only partially predicatable\n\nJoint Embedding Prediction Architecture:\n - Rather than predicting all the pixel level make predictions of the representations of the pixel\n - Generative models Predicts y directly with all the details even onees which are not relevant\n - JEPA lifs the abstraction level while gen AI do not\n - This is how models are built in traditional physics:\n  - Find an **abstract state representation** that allows to make predictions \n  - Extract the state representation from observation/measurement\n  - Predict outcome resulting from an intervention/experiment \n  - Another key feature of the abstraction is that from it conciously informations that are not predictable are removed\n\n\n\n",
      "tags": [],
      "projectId": "tikubsii",
      "dateIndex": null,
      "type": "note",
      "pinned": false,
      "createdAt": "2026-03-15T03:14:02.277Z",
