      "id": "evif4skn",
      "title": "Daily Research Read - Self Supervised Learning, JEPA, World Models and the Future of AI - Part 4",
      "content": "Object Driven  AI Systems\nAI that can learn, understand the world, reason, plan and Yet is safe and controllable\n\n\nAn ideal World Model for Planning/Reasoning would be have the following components:\n  - Perception: Computes an abstract representation of the state of the world\n    - possible also combined with previous acquired information in memory\n  - World model: Predeict the state resulting from an imagined action sequence \n  - Task Objective: Measures divergence to goal - which could be done with the help of an energy function that could estimate how much of a task is completed given the action taken - It would be 0 if the task is completed and a positive number if there is considerable divergence\n  - Guardrail Objective: Immutable objective terms that ensures safety\n  - Operation: Finds an action sequence that minimizes the objectives\n  - World models can be applied at multiple time steps - Guadrail costs applied to the entire state trajectory\n    - Similar to the way model predictive control works\n  \n\nIdeal Modular Cognitive Architecture for AMI\n- Configurator\n  - Configures other modules for task\n- Perception\n  - Estimates state of the world\n- World Model\n  - Preicts fuuture world states\n- Cost\n  - Computer \"discomfort\"\n- Actor\n  - Find optimal action sequences\n- Short Term Memory\n  - Stores state-cost episodes\n\nWays to train World Models:\n  - Siamese Network\n\nThe idea of training is basically encode the current and past states into a representation and then use the predictor to predict the representation of the future\ngive the encoded representation of the present and past states probably conditioned on an action guardrails. Finally the task of the objective function is to minimize the divergence between both\n\n\nEnergy-based Functions: Implicit Functions\n- Gives low energy for compatible x and y\n- Gives higher energy for incompatible pairs\n\nThe above is the only way because for a given X there could be multiple Ys\n\nHence some of the popular cost function to achieve this are:\n  - Contrastive Methods:\n    - Push down the energy of the training samples\n    - Pullup on the energy of suitably generated contrastive samples\n    - Scales poorly with high dimensional data\n  - Regularized Methods:\n    - Regularizer minimizes the volume of space that can be occupied by low energy\n",
      "tags": [],
      "projectId": "tikubsii",
      "dateIndex": null,
      "type": "note",
      "pinned": false,
      "createdAt": "2026-03-19T03:16:30.419Z",
      "updatedAt": "2026-03-22T21:15:48.615Z",
