      "id": "2b1k82sl",
      "title": "Prompt for Creating Interview Doc",
      "content": "\n###  I want you to create a comprehensive, exhaustive interview preparation document for this project. Go through every single aspect of the project in extra detail so that I can learn about it and prepare for an interview that would grill me on my work in this project.\n\nHere's exactly what I need you to do:\n\n1. **Explore the entire workspace first.** List directories, read every important source file, config file, launch/build file, message/interface definition, and script. Don't skip anything — read large chunks in parallel to build full context before writing.\n\n2. **Create a single Markdown file called `INTERVIEW_DEEP_DIVE.md`** in the project root with the following sections:\n\n   **Section 1 — System Architecture Overview**\n   - High-level architecture diagram (ASCII art data flow)\n   - How components connect (topics, services, APIs, protocols)\n   - Startup/initialization sequence\n   - Key architectural decisions and why\n\n   **Section 2 — Hardware / Infrastructure Stack**\n   - Every piece of hardware, sensor, device, or external service used\n   - IPs, ports, data rates, protocols, connection details\n   - Data formats and message structures\n\n   **Section 3 — Core Technology Foundations**\n   - Frameworks, libraries, and middleware used (e.g., ROS2, React, gRPC, etc.)\n   - Key concepts from those frameworks that this project relies on\n   - Threading/concurrency model\n   - Communication patterns (pub/sub, request/reply, streaming, etc.)\n\n   **Section 4 — Every Major Component (one subsection per component)**\n   - For each source file / module / class that matters:\n     - Purpose and responsibilities\n     - Internal state and data flow\n     - Key algorithms with step-by-step explanation\n     - Parameters/configuration and what they control\n     - How it interfaces with other components\n     - Edge cases and error handling\n\n   **Section 5 — Mathematics & Algorithms Deep Dive**\n   - Every non-trivial algorithm, equation, or mathematical concept used\n   - Step-by-step derivations where applicable\n   - Why each approach was chosen over alternatives\n\n   **Section 6 — Build System & Deployment**\n   - How the project is built, packaged, and deployed\n   - Dependencies and their roles\n   - Any gotchas or non-obvious build quirks\n\n   **Section 7 — Debugging War Stories**\n   - Every significant bug that was discovered and fixed during development\n   - For each: symptom → investigation → root cause → fix → lesson learned\n   - Include subtle issues (race conditions, stale caches, config mismatches, silent failures)\n\n   **Section 8 — Design Decisions & Tradeoffs**\n   - Every significant design choice with:\n     - What alternatives existed\n     - Why this approach was chosen\n     - What the tradeoffs are\n     - What you'd change in hindsight\n\n   **Section 9 — Potential Interview Questions & Detailed Answers**\n   - 20+ questions spanning: architecture, algorithms, debugging, technology choices, integration, limitations, and future improvements\n   - Each answer should be 1-2 paragraphs — detailed enough to impress an interviewer\n\n   **Section 10 — Quick Reference Tables**\n   - File map: every important file with line count and one-line purpose\n   - Key numbers: all important constants, thresholds, rates, IPs, ports\n   - Glossary of project-specific terms\n\n3. **Writing style guidelines:**\n   - Be specific — use actual variable names, file paths, function names, and parameter values from the code\n   - Include code snippets where they clarify an explanation\n   - Use tables for comparisons\n   - Use ASCII diagrams for data flow and architecture\n   - Write as if explaining to someone technical who has never seen the project\n   - Don't gloss over anything — if it's in the code, it should be in the document\n\n4. **Process:** Read first, write second. Don't start writing until you've read all the important files. Read in parallel where possible to be efficient. The document should demonstrate that you understand the project at the level of someone who built it.",
      "tags": [],
      "projectId": "y9081w3r",
      "dateIndex": null,
      "type": "note",
      "pinned": false,
      "createdAt": "2026-03-23T03:17:23.747Z",
      "updatedAt": "2026-03-24T03:10:12.826Z",
