    {
      "id": "ro1tfirq",
      "title": "Automated Data Collection Pipeline Setup (Copy)",
      "content": "# Isaac Sim / Omniverse Kit Script Editor\nfrom pxr import Usd, UsdGeom, Gf, Sdf\nimport omni.usd\n\n# ─── Global configurable variables ───\nQUAD_COLORS = {\n    \"TL\": (1.0, 1.0, 1.0),   # top-left: white\n   \"TR1\": (0.0, 1.0, 0.0),   # top-right: green\n    \"BL\": (1.0, 1.0, 0.0),   # bottom-left: yellow\n    \"BR\": (1.0, 0.0, 0.0),    # bottom-right: red\n        # additional:\n    \"TR\": (0.0, 0.0, 1.0),   # blue\n    \"Extra2\": (1.0, 0.647, 0.0), # orange\n    \"Extra3\": (0.0, 0.0, 0.0),   # black\n}\n\n# Board dimensions:\nBOARD_WIDTH  = 0.40   # in meters (40 cm)\nBOARD_DEPTH  = 0.20   # in meters (20 cm)\nBOARD_THICKNESS = 0.005  # in meters (5 mm)\nZ_BASE = 0.0  # height of board bottom from world origin\n\n# ─── Helper functions ───\ndef _get_stage():\n    ctx = omni.usd.get_context()\n    if ctx is None:breakoing\n        raise RuntimeError(\"omni.usd context not available — are you in Isaac Sim Script Editor?\")\n    stage = ctx.get_stage()\n    if stage is None:\n        raise RuntimeError(\"USD stage not found/loaded.\")\n    return stage\n\ndef _define_xform(stage, path):\n    if not path.startswith(\"/\"):\n        path = \"/\" + path\n    return UsdGeom.Xform.Define(stage, Sdf.Path(path))\n\ndef _set_display_color(prim, rgb):\n    r, g, b = map(float, rgb)\n    UsdGeom.Gprim(prim).CreateDisplayColorAttr([Gf.Vec3f(r, g, b)])\n\ndef _xform_set_translate_scale(prim, t_xyz, s_xyz):\n    tx, ty, tz = map(float, t_xyz)\n    sx, sy, sz = map(float, s_xyz)\n    api = UsdGeom.XformCommonAPI(UsdGeom.Xformable(prim))\n    api.SetTranslate(Gf.Vec3d(tx, ty, tz))\n    api.SetScale(Gf.Vec3f(sx, sy, sz))\n\ndef _create_cube_quadrant(stage, parent_path, name, center_xyz, scale_xyz, color_rgb):\n    qpath = f\"{parent_path}/{name}\"\n    cube = UsdGeom.Cube.Define(stage, Sdf.Path(qpath))\n    cube.CreateSizeAttr(1.0)\n    _xform_set_translate_scale(cube.GetPrim(), center_xyz, scale_xyz)\n    _set_display_color(cube.GetPrim(), color_rgb)\n    return cube\n\n# ─── Main creation function ───\ndef create_quadrant_board(\n    root_path=\"/World\",\n    xform_name=\"QuadrantBoard\",\n    width=BOARD_WIDTH,\n    depth=BOARD_DEPTH,\n    thickness=BOARD_THICKNESS,\n    colors=QUAD_COLORS,\n    z_base=Z_BASE,\n    add_collision=False\n):\n    stage = _get_stage()\n    board_path = f\"{root_path.rstrip('/')}/{xform_name}\"\n    _define_xform(stage, board_path)\n\n    half_w = width * 0.5\n    half_d = depth * 0.5\n    quad_w = half_w\n    quad_d = half_d\n    z_center = float(z_base) + thickness * 0.5\n\n    # define centers (X,Y,Z) of 4 quadrants (TL, TR, BL, BR)\n    centers = {\n        \"TL\": (-quad_w * 0.5, +quad_d * 0.5, z_center),\n        \"TR\": (+quad_w * 0.5, +quad_d * 0.5, z_center),\n        \"BL\": (-quad_w * 0.5, -quad_d * 0.5, z_center),\n        \"BR\": (+quad_w * 0.5, -quad_d * 0.5, z_center),\n    }\n    names = {\n        \"TL\": \"Q_TL\",\n        \"TR\": \"Q_TR\",\n        \"BL\": \"Q_BL\",\n        \"BR\": \"Q_BR\",\n    }\n    scale = (quad_w, quad_d, thickness)\n\n    for key in (\"TL\",\"TR\",\"BL\",\"BR\"):\n        name  = names[key]\n        center = centers[key]\n        color = colors[key]\n        _create_cube_quadrant(stage, board_path, name, center, scale, color)\n\n    # skip saving the layer — user will save manually\n\n    print(f\"[QuadrantBoard] Created at {board_path} | total size = ({width} × {depth} × {thickness}) m\")\n    return board_path\n\n# ─── Run the creation ───\ncreate_quadrant_board(\n    xform_name=\"QuadrantBoard\"\n)\n",
      "tags": [],
      "projectId": "c7szb5bi",
      "dateIndex": null,
      "type": "note",
      "pinned": false,
      "createdAt": "2026-04-13T18:19:50.211Z",
      "updatedAt": "2026-04-13T18:19:50.211Z",
      "attachments": [],
      "links": [],
      "deletedAt": "2026-04-13T18:22:57.867Z"
    },
    {
      "id": "jbu3o6dk",
      "title": "SIm2Sim & ADC - Architecture & System Design",
      "content": "# Rosetta — Interview Deep Dive\n\n> **Comprehensive preparation guide covering every architectural decision, algorithm, debugging story, and technical nuance in this project.**\n\n---\n\n## Table of Contents\n\n1. [System Architecture Overview](#section-1--system-architecture-overview)\n2. [Hardware / Infrastructure Stack](#section-2--hardware--infrastructure-stack)\n3. [Core Technology Foundations](#section-3--core-technology-foundations)\n4. [Every Major Component](#section-4--every-major-component)\n5. [Mathematics & Algorithms Deep Dive](#section-5--mathematics--algorithms-deep-dive)\n6. [Build System & Deployment](#section-6--build-system--deployment)\n7. [Debugging War Stories](#section-7--debugging-war-stories)\n8. [Design Decisions & Tradeoffs](#section-8--design-decisions--tradeoffs)\n9. [Potential Interview Questions & Answers](#section-9--potential-interview-questions--detailed-answers)\n10. [Quick Reference Tables](#section-10--quick-reference-tables)\n\n---\n\n# Section 1 — System Architecture Overview\n\n## 1.1 High-Level Architecture\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                              ISAAC SIM                                      │\n│  ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐  ┌────────────────┐  │\n│  │camera_ee │ │camera    │ │camera    │ │camera    │  │  UR5e + Robotiq│  │\n│  │  /rgb    │ │ _egol/rgb│ │ _egor/rgb│ │_thirdeye │  │  Articulation  │  │\n│  └────┬─────┘ └────┬─────┘ └────┬─────┘ └────┬─────┘  └───────┬────────┘  │\n│       │             │            │             │                │           │\n│       │  sensor_msgs/msg/Image   │             │      sensor_msgs/msg/     │\n│       │  512×512 RGB @ ~23 Hz    │             │      JointState @ 336Hz   │\n└───────┼─────────────┼────────────┼─────────────┼────────────────┼──────────┘\n        │             │            │             │                │\n        ▼             ▼            ▼             ▼                ▼\n  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n  │                        ROS 2 HUMBLE (DDS)                          │\n  │   Topics: /camera_ee/rgb, /camera_egol/rgb, /camera_egor/rgb,     │\n  │           /camera_thirdeye/rgb, /joint_states, /action_commands    │\n  └───┬──────────────┬─────────────────────────────────┬───────────────┘\n      │              │                                  │\n      ▼              ▼                                  ▼\n┌──────────┐  ┌──────────────┐                  ┌───────────────────┐\n│ MoveIt   │  │ Behavior     │                  │ Rosetta Nodes     │\n│ Planner  │  │ Tree Engine  │                  │                   │\n│          │  │              │                  │ ┌───────────────┐ │\n│ Generates│  │ Orchestrates │─────action───────▶│ Episode        │ │\n│ motion   │  │ PnP routine  │  goals (ROS 2)  │ Recorder v2    │ │\n│ plans    │  │              │                  │ (recording)    │ │\n└────┬─────┘  └──────────────┘                  │ └───────────────┘ │\n     │                                          │ ┌───────────────┐ │\n     │    /action_commands                      │ │ Policy Bridge  │ │\n     │    pnp_msgs/ActionCommand                │ │ (inference)    │ │\n     │    @ ~34 Hz                              │ └───────────────┘ │\n     └──────────────────────────────────────────┤ ┌───────────────┐ │\n                                                │ │ Adapter Node   │ │\n                                                │ │ ActionCommand  │ │\n                                                │ │ → JointState   │ │\n                                                │ └───────────────┘ │\n                                                └───────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Workflow: Data Collection Pipeline (Training Path)\n\n```\n┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  PHASE 1: DATA COLLECTION (Isaac Sim + Behavior Tree)                  │\n│                                                                        │\n│  BT Node ──▶ record_episode (action goal)                              │\n│    ↓         ┌─────────────────────────┐                               │\n│  Robot       │  EpisodeRecorderEnhanced │                              │\n│  executes    │  - Subscribes all topics │                              │\n│  PnP via     │  - Queues → writer thread│                              │\n│  MoveIt      │  - Writes MCAP rosbag    │                              │\n│    ↓         └─────────┬───────────────┘                               │\n│  BT Node ──▶ stop recording (cancel)                                   │\n│  BT Node ──▶ evaluate_episode → save_episode OR delete_episode         │\n│                        ↓                                               │\n│             _staging/episode_dir/ → accepted/ or backup/               │\n└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n                         ↓\n┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  PHASE 2: DATASET CONVERSION (Offline)                                 │\n│                                                                        │\n│  bag_to_lerobot.py                                                     │\n│    --bags accepted/epi_1 accepted/epi_2 ...                            │\n│    --contract ur5e_robotiq_pnp.yaml                                    │\n│    --out /data/.../lerobot_dataset                                     │\n│                                                                        │\n│  Steps:                                                                │\n│   1. Load contract → shared SpecView / iter_specs()                    │\n│   2. Scan bag → decode_value() per topic (shared decoders)             │\n│   3. Resample at contract rate_hz (20 Hz)                              │\n│   4. Assemble frames: { obs.images.*, obs.state, action } per tick     │\n│   5. Write LeRobot v3: videos/ + data/*.parquet + meta/               │\n└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n                         ↓\n┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  PHASE 3: TRAINING (LeRobot)                                           │\n│                                                                        │\n│  lerobot-train --dataset.root ... --policy.type act                    │\n│                                                                        │\n│  ACT: Action Chunking Transformer                                      │\n│  - 4 camera inputs (512×512 → ResNet backbone)                         │\n│  - 14-dim state input (6 arm joints + 1 gripper × pos + vel)           │\n│  - 7-dim action output (6 arm joints + 1 gripper position)             │\n│  - VAE regularization, action chunking (25 steps @ 20 Hz = 1.25s)      │\n└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n                         ↓\n┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  PHASE 4: DEPLOYMENT (PolicyBridge)                                    │\n│                                                                        │\n│  PolicyBridge node:                                                    │\n│    1. Loads pretrained ACT model to CUDA                               │\n│    2. Subscribes to 4 cameras + /joint_states                          │\n│    3. Producer timer (20 Hz): sample obs → inference → action chunk    │\n│    4. Executor timer (20 Hz): dequeue action → publish /action_commands│\n│    5. ActionToJointStateAdapter: /action_commands → /policy_joint_cmds │\n│    6. Isaac Sim joint controller applies positions                     │\n└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n## 1.2 The Contract: Single Source of Truth\n\nThe core architectural insight of Rosetta is the **contract YAML** — a single file that describes:\n\n| Aspect | What It Declares | Who Reads It |\n|--------|------------------|--------------|\n| Observations | Topics, types, QoS, image resize, joint selectors | Recorder, Converter, PolicyBridge |\n| Actions | Publish topic, type, encoder names, clamp ranges | Recorder, Converter, PolicyBridge |\n| Timing | `rate_hz`, `max_duration_s`, `align.strategy` | Converter, PolicyBridge |\n| Recording | Storage backend (mcap) | Recorder |\n\nThis guarantees **train↔serve parity**: the exact same `decode_value()` and `encode_value()` functions run at data collection time, conversion time, and inference time.\n\n## 1.3 Key Architectural Decisions\n\n| Decision | Rationale |\n|----------|-----------|\n| Contract-driven design | Eliminates shape/type mismatches between record, convert, and deploy |\n| Always-on subscriptions | Avoids DDS re-negotiation overhead between episodes |\n| Dedicated writer thread | Prevents subscriber callbacks from blocking on I/O |\n| Per-topic message queues | Decouples receive rate from write rate |\n| Action servers (not services) | Support cancellation, feedback, and state machines (required by BTs) |\n| MCAP storage | Fast, seekable, widely supported, smaller than sqlite3 |\n| Staging workflow | Separates raw recording from quality-checked accepted data |\n\n---\n\n# Section 2 — Hardware / Infrastructure Stack\n\n## 2.1 Simulation Environment\n\n| Component | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Simulator** | NVIDIA Isaac Sim |\n| **Robot** | Universal Robots UR5e (6-DOF arm) |\n| **Gripper** | Robotiq 85 (1-DOF, parallel jaw) |\n| **Cameras** | 4 virtual cameras in Isaac Sim |\n| **Task** | Pick-and-place of a cube |\n| **Motion Planning** | MoveIt 2 (ROS 2 integration) |\n| **Orchestration** | Behavior Tree (BT) engine calling action servers |\n\n## 2.2 Camera Configuration\n\n| Camera | Topic | View | Purpose |\n|--------|-------|------|---------|\n| `camera_ee` | `/camera_ee/rgb` | End-effector mounted | Close-up of grasp |\n| `camera_egol` | `/camera_egol/rgb` | Left ego-view | Workspace left |\n| `camera_egor` | `/camera_egor/rgb` | Right ego-view | Workspace right |\n| `camera_thirdeye` | `/camera_thirdeye/rgb` | Third-person overhead | Global view |\n\nAll cameras: 512×512 pixels, RGB8 encoding, ~23 Hz from Isaac Sim, simulation time in `header.stamp`.\n\n## 2.3 Robot Joint Configuration\n\n```\nJoint Name                            | Type\n--------------------------------------|--------\nshoulder_pan_joint                    | Revolute\nshoulder_lift_joint                   | Revolute\nelbow_joint                           | Revolute\nwrist_1_joint                         | Revolute\nwrist_2_joint                         | Revolute\nwrist_3_joint                         | Revolute\nrobotiq_85_left_knuckle_joint         | Prismatic (gripper)\n```\n\n**State vector (14-dim):** 7 positions + 7 velocities\n**Action vector (7-dim):** 7 target positions (6 arm + 1 gripper)\n\n## 2.4 Data Rates & Sizes\n\n| Topic | Type | Rate | Size/msg | Bandwidth |\n|-------|------|------|----------|-----------|\n| `/camera_*/rgb` | Image 512×512×3 | ~23 Hz | ~786 KB | ~18 MB/s per cam |\n| `/joint_states` | JointState | ~336 Hz | ~0.5 KB | ~168 KB/s |\n| `/action_commands` | ActionCommand | ~34 Hz | ~0.3 KB | ~10 KB/s |\n\n**Total per episode (~30s):** ~2.1 GiB (dominated by 4 camera streams)\n\n## 2.5 Clock Domains\n\n| Source | Clock Type | `header.stamp` Example |\n|--------|------------|------------------------|\n| Isaac Sim cameras | Simulation time | `sec: 44505, nanosec: 218987794` (~12.4 hrs sim) |\n| MoveIt/joint_states | System wall clock | `sec: 1763665404` (Unix epoch) |\n| Recorder `receive` | ROS node wall clock | `sec: 1763665404` (Unix epoch) |\n\n**Critical finding:** Isaac Sim uses simulation time (starts from 0, increments per simulation tick), while MoveIt uses wall clock. The recorder's `receive` timestamp uses wall clock. This created a clock domain mismatch that needed careful handling.\n\n---\n\n# Section 3 — Core Technology Foundations\n\n## 3.1 Frameworks & Libraries\n\n| Technology | Role | Version |\n|------------|------|---------|\n| **ROS 2 Humble** | Middleware, pub/sub, action servers, DDS | Humble Hawksbill |\n| **Python 3.10** | Primary language (system Python for ROS compat) | 3.10 |\n| **rosbag2_py** | Python bindings for rosbag2 (read/write MCAP) | ROS 2 Humble |\n| **LeRobot** | Imitation learning framework (ACT, Diffusion Policy) | v3.0 |\n| **PyTorch** | Deep learning inference and training | ≥ 2.0 |\n| **NumPy** | Array operations, image processing, resampling | ≥ 1.24 |\n| **MCAP** | Bag storage format (fast, seekable) | — |\n| **colcon** | ROS 2 build system | — |\n| **matplotlib** | QC report visualizations | — |\n\n## 3.2 ROS 2 Concepts Used\n\n### 3.2.1 Action Servers (Critical)\n\nThe project heavily uses ROS 2 **action servers** rather than services because:\n\n1. **Long-running operations** — Recording episodes takes 30+ seconds\n2. **Cancellation** — BT nodes and operators need to stop recording mid-flight\n3. **Feedback** — Real-time progress reporting (messages written, time remaining)\n4. **State machine** — Goal → Executing → {Succeeded, Canceled, Aborted}\n\n**Five action servers defined in `rosetta_interfaces`:**\n\n| Action | Server | Purpose |\n|--------|--------|---------|\n| `RecordEpisode` | `/record_episode` | Start/stop recording |\n| `EvaluateEpisode` | `/evaluate_episode` | Generate QC report |\n| `SaveEpisode` | `/save_episode` | Move to `accepted/` |\n| `DeleteEpisode` | `/delete_episode` | Move to `backup/` |\n| `RunPolicy` | `/run_policy` | Run inference loop |\n\n### 3.2.2 QoS Profiles\n\nThe contract specifies QoS per-topic:\n\n```yaml\nqos: {reliability: reliable, history: keep_last, depth: 10}\n```\n\nMapped in `qos_profile_from_dict()`:\n\n```python\nQoSProfile(\n    reliability=ReliabilityPolicy.RELIABLE,\n    history=HistoryPolicy.KEEP_LAST,\n    depth=10,\n    durability=DurabilityPolicy.VOLATILE,\n)\n```\n\n**Design choice:** `RELIABLE` for all camera topics to avoid frame drops. `keep_last` with `depth=10` to bound memory without losing recent messages.\n\n### 3.2.3 Callback Groups & Executors\n\n```python\nself._cbg = ReentrantCallbackGroup()\n```\n\nThe `ReentrantCallbackGroup` allows multiple callbacks (subscriptions, timers, action servers) to execute concurrently. Combined with `MultiThreadedExecutor(num_threads=8)`, this ensures:\n\n- Subscription callbacks don't block action server callbacks\n- Timer ticks (feedback, timeout) fire independently\n- Writer thread runs in parallel\n\n## 3.3 Threading / Concurrency Model\n\n### Episode Recorder v2\n\n```\nMain Thread (ROS executor)\n    ├── Subscription callbacks (1 per topic, 6 total) → enqueue to deque\n    ├── Feedback timer (0.5s) → publish progress\n    ├── Timeout timer → stop recording\n    └── Action server callbacks\n\nWriter Thread (daemon)\n    └── Round-robin drain queues → write to MCAP\n\nHotkey Thread (daemon, optional)\n    └── Read stdin → trigger actions\n\nStatus Display Thread (daemon, optional)\n    └── Print recording status every 0.5s\n```\n\n**Synchronization primitives:**\n- `self._ws.writer_lock` — `threading.Lock` guarding writer access\n- `self._episode_lock` — `threading.Lock` guarding `_current_bag_dir` access\n- `self._episode_done_evt` — `threading.Event` for blocking wait\n- `self._flags` — Shared `Flags` dataclass (mutable attributes, no lock needed for booleans on CPython due to GIL)\n\n### PolicyBridge\n\n```\nMain Thread (ROS executor)\n    ├── Observation subscription callbacks → push to StreamBuffer\n    ├── Producer timer (step_sec) → run inference → enqueue actions\n    ├── Executor timer (step_sec) → dequeue action → publish\n    ├── Feedback timer (0.5s) → publish progress\n    └── Deadline timer (0.2s) → check timeout\n\nNo separate threads — all on ROS timer callbacks.\n```\n\n**Synchronization primitives:**\n- `self._queue_lock` — `threading.Lock` guarding action queue\n- `self._running_event`, `self._stop_requested`, `self._done_event`, `self._finishing` — `threading.Event` for lifecycle\n\n## 3.4 Communication Patterns\n\n| Pattern | Where Used | How |\n|---------|------------|-----|\n| **Pub/Sub** | Camera, JointState, ActionCommand topics | DDS-based, decoupled |\n| **Action** | Recording lifecycle, policy execution | Goal→Execute→Result |\n| **Service** | Cancel, pause, status queries | Request→Response |\n| **Shared state** | Writer thread ↔ sub callbacks | Lock-protected queues |\n| **File I/O** | Bag writing, metadata, QC reports | Sequential writer + thread |\n\n---\n\n# Section 4 — Every Major Component\n\n## 4.1 `episode_recorder_v2.py` — EpisodeRecorderServerEnhanced\n\n**File:** `rosetta/rosetta/episode_recorder_v2.py`\n**Lines:** ~1614\n**Purpose:** Stream-to-bag writer with action-based control, staging workflow, QC reports, and hotkey override.\n\n### 4.1.1 Lifecycle\n\n```\nNode Startup\n    ├── Load contract → parse observations, tasks, actions\n    ├── Create QoS profiles from contract\n    ├── Create subscriptions (once, persistent)\n    ├── Initialize per-topic deques (maxlen=100)\n    ├── Start writer thread (daemon)\n    ├── Create 4 action servers + 3 services\n    └── Optionally start hotkey + status threads\n\nEpisode Recording\n    ├── Goal received → goal_callback() → ACCEPT if not recording\n    ├── execute_callback():\n    │   ├── Clear all queues (prevent cross-episode contamination)\n    │   ├── Reset counters\n    │   ├── Set is_recording = True\n    │   ├── Open MCAP writer + register topics\n    │   ├── Start feedback + timeout timers\n    │   ├── Block on _episode_done_evt (with 0.1s poll for cancel)\n    │   ├── Finalize: drain queues → close writer → write metadata\n    │   └── Return Result (success, path, counts, duration)\n    └── Sub callbacks: serialize msg → enqueue (topic, data, ts_ns)\n\nWriter Thread\n    └── Round-robin drain queues → writer.write(topic, data, ts_ns)\n```\n\n### 4.1.2 Subscription Callback (Critical Path)\n\n```python\ndef cb(msg: Any, _topic: str = tinfo.name) -> None:\n    cnt = self._ws.counts.get(_topic)\n    if cnt:\n        cnt.seen += 1\n\n    if (not self._flags.is_recording or self._flags.shutting_down or self._flags.paused):\n        return  # <-- Early exit when not recording\n\n    now_ns = self.get_clock().now().nanoseconds\n    ts_ns = now_ns  # default: receive time\n\n    if self._timestamp_source == \"header\":\n        # Extract header.stamp if available\n        hdr = getattr(msg, \"header\", None)\n        if hdr is not None:\n            st = getattr(hdr, \"stamp\", None)\n            if st is not None:\n                header_ns = getattr(st, \"nanoseconds\", None)\n                if header_ns is not None and header_ns > 0:\n                    ts_ns = header_ns\n\n    data = serialize_message(msg)  # CDR serialization\n\n    q = self._ws.queues.get(_topic)\n    if q is not None:\n        if len(q) >= MAX_QUEUE_SIZE:  # 100\n            q.popleft()  # Drop oldest\n            if cnt:\n                cnt.dropped += 1\n        q.append((_topic, data, ts_ns))\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `is_recording` flag gates enqueuing (NOT subscription existence)\n- `serialize_message()` is called in the callback (CPU cost)\n- Deque `maxlen=100` acts as bounded buffer; oldest dropped on overflow\n- Timestamp policy configurable: `\"receive\"` vs `\"header\"`\n\n### 4.1.3 Writer Thread\n\n```python\ndef _writer_loop(self) -> None:\n    topic_names = list(self._ws.queues.keys())\n    idx = 0\n    while self._run_writer:\n        if self._ws.writer is None:\n            time.sleep(0.01)\n            continue\n        total_queued = sum(len(q) for q in self._ws.queues.values())\n        if not self._flags.is_recording and total_queued == 0:\n            time.sleep(0.01)\n            continue\n        wrote_any = False\n        for _ in range(len(topic_names)):\n            topic = topic_names[idx % len(topic_names)]\n            idx += 1\n            q = self._ws.queues.get(topic)\n            if q and len(q) > 0:\n                _topic, data, ts_ns = q.popleft()\n                with self._ws.writer_lock:\n                    if self._ws.writer is not None:\n                        self._ws.writer.write(_topic, data, ts_ns)\n                        ...\n                wrote_any = True\n        if not wrote_any:\n            time.sleep(0.001)\n```\n\n**Round-robin fairness:** Each iteration processes one message from each topic, preventing high-rate topics (336 Hz joint states) from starving low-rate topics (23 Hz cameras).\n\n### 4.1.4 Staging Workflow\n\n```\n_staging/\n  └── 1763665414_099009275/    ← Raw recording (episode_name = unix_timestamp)\n        ├── metadata.yaml       ← Rosbag2 standard metadata\n        ├── episode_meta.json   ← Enhanced metadata (git SHA, system info, topic stats)\n        ├── *.mcap              ← Actual bag data\n        ├── qc_report.html      ← QC report (after evaluate)\n        └── qc_rates.png        ← Rate plot\n\naccepted/\n  └── 1763665414_099009275/    ← Quality-checked, ready for conversion\n\nbackup/\n  └── 1763665414_099009275/    ← Rejected episodes (not deleted, for review)\n```\n\n### 4.1.5 Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Default | Description |\n|-----------|---------|-------------|\n| `contract_path` | `\"\"` (required) | Path to YAML contract |\n| `bag_base_dir` | `\"/tmp/episodes\"` | Root for staging/accepted/backup |\n| `storage_preset_profile` | `\"\"` | MCAP compression preset |\n| `storage_config_uri` | `\"\"` | Custom storage config |\n| `timestamp_source` | `\"receive\"` | `\"receive\"` or `\"header\"` |\n| `enable_hotkeys` | `True` | Enable keyboard shortcuts |\n\n---\n\n## 4.2 `policy_bridge_node.py` — PolicyBridge\n\n**File:** `rosetta/rosetta/policy_bridge_node.py`\n**Lines:** ~1063\n**Purpose:** Contract-driven live policy inference with action chunking and temporal execution.\n\n### 4.2.1 Architecture: Producer-Executor Pattern\n\n```\nObservation Streams (4 cameras + joint states)\n    │\n    ▼\nStreamBuffer (per-stream, last-value-hold)\n    │\n    ▼\nProducer Timer (step_sec = 1/20 = 0.05s)\n    ├── _obs_ready()? → All streams have ≥1 sample?\n    ├── _sample_obs_frame(t) → Dict[str, ndarray]\n    ├── _prepare() → Dict[str, Tensor]  (HWC→CHW, normalize, to device)\n    ├── preprocessor() → policy-specific pre-processing\n    ├── policy.predict_action_chunk() → [chunk_size × action_dim] Tensor\n    ├── postprocessor() → unnormalize\n    └── Enqueue (scheduled_time, action_vec) pairs → _queue\n\nExecutor Timer (step_sec = 0.05s)\n    ├── Find action nearest to now within tolerance\n    ├── Publish via encode_value() → ActionCommand msg\n    └── Publish to /action_commands\n```\n\n### 4.2.2 Action Chunking\n\nThe ACT policy predicts a **chunk** of future actions at once:\n\n```python\nchunk = self.policy.predict_action_chunk(batch)  # → [1, chunk_size, action_dim]\nchunk = chunk.squeeze(0)                          # → [chunk_size, action_dim]\nchunk = self._postprocess_actions(chunk)          # unnormalize\n\n# Schedule each action at its future time step\nbase_t = self._next_exec_tick_ns(now_wall + self.step_ns)\nfor i in range(k):  # k = actions_per_chunk = 25\n    t_i = base_t + i * self.step_ns  # 50ms apart\n    self._producer_buffer.append((t_i, chunk[i].numpy()))\n```\n\n**Why chunking matters:** Instead of predicting one action per inference call (which is slow for 4×512×512 images through a ResNet), the model predicts 25 actions at once. At 20 Hz, this covers 1.25 seconds of robot motion. The executor then replays them at the correct times.\n\n**Refill policy:** Produce a new chunk when the queue falls below `chunk_size_threshold * actions_per_chunk` (default: 50% = 12 actions remaining).\n\n### 4.2.3 Observation Sampling with StreamBuffer\n\n```python\nclass StreamBuffer:\n    def __init__(self, policy: str, step_ns: int, tol_ns: int = 0):\n        self.policy = policy  # \"hold\" | \"asof\" | \"drop\"\n        self.last_ts = None\n        self.last_val = None\n\n    def push(self, ts_ns: int, val: Any) -> None:\n        if self.last_ts is None or ts_ns >= self.last_ts:\n            self.last_ts, self.last_val = ts_ns, val\n\n    def sample(self, tick_ns: int):\n        if self.policy == \"hold\":\n            return self.last_val  # always return latest\n        elif self.policy == \"asof\":\n            return self.last_val if (tick_ns - self.last_ts <= self.tol_ns) else None\n        elif self.policy == \"drop\":\n            return self.last_val if (self.last_ts > tick_ns - self.step_ns) else None\n```\n\nThis is the **online** (constant-memory) version of the resampling logic also used offline in `bag_to_lerobot.py`.\n\n### 4.2.4 Image Preprocessing Pipeline\n\n```python\ndef _prepare(self, obs_frame):\n    for k, v in obs_frame.items():\n        if isinstance(v, np.ndarray):\n            t = torch.from_numpy(v)\n            if t.ndim == 3 and t.shape[2] in (1, 3, 4):\n                # HWC → CHW → batch dim → normalize to [0,1] → to device\n                t = t.permute(2, 0, 1).unsqueeze(0).contiguous()\n                t = t.to(self.device, dtype=torch.float32) / 255.0\n                batch[k] = t\n```\n\n**Important:** Images arrive as `uint8 [0,255]` HWC arrays from the decoder. They are permuted to CHW, normalized to `[0,1]`, and sent to GPU. The LeRobot `preprocessor` further applies ImageNet normalization (`mean=[0.485,0.456,0.406], std=[0.229,0.224,0.225]`).\n\n### 4.2.5 Safety Behavior\n\n```python\nself._safety_behavior = \"hold\"  # From contract: safety_behavior: hold\n\ndef _create_safety_vector(self) -> np.ndarray:\n    if self._safety_behavior == \"hold\" and self._last_action is not None:\n        return self._last_action.copy()  # Keep arm where it is\n    else:\n        return np.zeros((total_size,), dtype=np.float32)  # Zero velocities\n```\n\nFor UR5e: `hold` is used so the arm freezes in place when inference stops, rather than going limp.\n\n---\n\n## 4.3 `bag_to_lerobot.py` — Dataset Conversion\n\n**File:** `rosetta/scripts/bag_to_lerobot.py`\n**Lines:** ~696\n**Purpose:** Convert rosbag2 episodes to LeRobot v3 dataset format.\n\n### 4.3.1 Conversion Pipeline\n\n```\n1. Load contract → iter_specs() → SpecView list\n2. Build features dict: { \"observation.images.camera_ee\": {dtype: \"video\", shape: (512,512,3)}, ... }\n3. For each bag:\n   a. Open SequentialReader\n   b. Plan streams: map contract topics → bag topics\n   c. Single-pass decode: while reader.has_next() → decode_value() → append to _Stream\n   d. Choose anchor start time + calculate ticks at rate_hz\n   e. Resample each stream to ticks: resample_hold / resample_asof / resample_drop\n   f. Write frames: for each tick → assemble {obs, state, action} dict → ds.add_frame()\n4. ds.save_episode()\n5. Repeat for all bags\n```\n\n### 4.3.2 Timestamp Selection Policy\n\n```python\nif timestamp_source == \"receive\":\n    ts_sel = int(bag_ns)                     # Bag receive time\nelif timestamp_source == \"header\":\n    ts_sel = stamp_from_header_ns(msg) or int(bag_ns)  # Header preferred\nelse:  # \"contract\"\n    ts_sel = int(bag_ns)\n    if sv.stamp_src == \"header\":\n        hdr = stamp_from_header_ns(msg)\n        if hdr is not None:\n            ts_sel = int(hdr)\n```\n\n**Critical design lesson:** Using `receive` timestamps for all topics ensures a single monotonic timeline. Mixed header/receive timestamps caused a 35-billion-frame allocation bug (see Section 7).\n\n### 4.3.3 Multiple Observation State Consolidation\n\nThe UR5e contract has a single `observation.state` key but data comes from `/joint_states`. The TurtleBot contract has *three* `observation.state` keys from different topics (`/joint_states`, `/odom`, `/imu`):\n\n```python\n# Multiple state specs → concatenate into one vector\nif state_specs:\n    state_values = []\n    for sv in state_specs:\n        unique_key = f\"{sv.key}_{sv.topic.replace('/', '_')}\"\n        stream_val = resampled.get(unique_key, [None] * n_ticks)[i]\n        if stream_val is not None:\n            state_values.append(np.asarray(stream_val, dtype=np.float32).reshape(-1))\n    frame[\"observation.state\"] = np.concatenate(state_values)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4.4 `contract_utils.py` — The Contract Engine\n\n**File:** `rosetta/rosetta/common/contract_utils.py`\n**Lines:** ~624\n**Purpose:** Load contracts, define shared dataclasses, decode/encode dispatch, resampling algorithms.\n\n### 4.4.1 Contract Datamodel\n\n```python\nContract\n  ├── name: str\n  ├── version: int\n  ├── rate_hz: float           # 20.0 for UR5e\n  ├── max_duration_s: float    # 120.0\n  ├── robot_type: str          # \"ur5e_robotiq\"\n  ├── observations: List[ObservationSpec]\n  │     ├── key: str           # \"observation.images.camera_ee\"\n  │     ├── topic: str         # \"/camera_ee/rgb\"\n  │     ├── type: str          # \"sensor_msgs/msg/Image\"\n  │     ├── image: {resize: [512,512]}\n  │     ├── selector: {names: [\"position.shoulder_pan_joint\", ...]}\n  │     ├── align: AlignSpec(strategy=\"hold\", stamp=\"receive\", tol_ms=10000)\n  │     └── qos: {reliability: reliable, history: keep_last, depth: 10}\n  ├── actions: List[ActionSpec]\n  │     ├── key: str           # \"action\"\n  │     ├── publish_topic: str # \"/action_commands\"\n  │     ├── type: str          # \"pnp_msgs/msg/ActionCommand\"\n  │     ├── selector: {names: [\"position.shoulder_pan_joint\", ...]}\n  │     ├── from_tensor: {clamp: [-3.14, 3.14]}\n  │     └── safety_behavior: \"hold\"\n  └── recording: {storage: \"mcap\"}\n```\n\n### 4.4.2 Decoder/Encoder Registry Pattern\n\n```python\nDECODERS: Dict[str, DecoderFn] = {}\n\ndef register_decoder(type_str: str):\n    def _wrap(fn):\n        DECODERS[type_str] = fn\n        return fn\n    return _wrap\n\n# Usage:\n@register_decoder(\"sensor_msgs/msg/Image\")\ndef _dec_image(msg, spec):\n    ...\n\n# Dispatch:\ndef decode_value(ros_type: str, msg, spec) -> Any:\n    fn = DECODERS.get(ros_type)\n    return fn(msg, spec)\n```\n\nThis pattern allows adding support for new message types (e.g., `pnp_msgs/msg/ActionCommand`) without modifying core code — just add a new file that imports and uses `@register_decoder`.\n\n### 4.4.3 Contract Fingerprinting\n\n```python\ndef contract_fingerprint(contract) -> str:\n    fingerprint_data = {\n        \"observations\": [...],  # key, topic, ros_type, selector, image_resize\n        \"actions\": [...],       # key, topic, ros_type, selector\n    }\n    json_str = json.dumps(fingerprint_data, sort_keys=True)\n    return hashlib.sha256(json_str.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n```\n\nThe fingerprint is stored in the LeRobot dataset at training time and validated at inference time. If the contract structure changes between training and deployment, the PolicyBridge logs a warning.\n\n---\n\n## 4.5 `decoders.py` / `custom_decoders_encoders.py`\n\n### 4.5.1 Image Decoding Pipeline\n\n```python\ndef decode_ros_image(msg, expected_encoding=None, resize_hw=None) -> np.ndarray:\n    enc = msg.encoding.lower()\n\n    if enc in (\"32fc1\", \"32fc\"):\n        # Depth: float32 meters → normalize [0,50m] → [0,1] → replicate to 3ch\n        arr = raw.view(np.float32).reshape(h, w)\n        return np.repeat(np.clip(arr, 0, 50) / 50, 3, axis=-1)\n\n    elif enc in (\"rgb8\", \"bgr8\"):\n        # Color: reshape → BGR→RGB if needed → resize → normalize to [0,1]\n        arr = raw.reshape(h, w, 3)\n        hwc_rgb = arr if enc == \"rgb8\" else arr[..., ::-1]\n        if resize_hw:\n            hwc_rgb = _nearest_resize_rgb(hwc_rgb, rh, rw)\n        return hwc_rgb.astype(np.float32) / 255.0\n```\n\n**Key insight:** Images are normalized to `[0,1] float32` at decode time (not uint8). This matches what the PolicyBridge does at inference time, maintaining train↔serve parity.\n\n### 4.5.2 JointState Decoder with Dotted Selectors\n\n```python\ndef dot_get(obj, path: str):\n    parts = path.split(\".\")\n    # JointState-like fast path: \"position.elbow_joint\"\n    if len(parts) == 2 and hasattr(obj, \"name\") and hasattr(obj, parts[0]):\n        field, key = parts\n        idx = list(obj.name).index(key)\n        return getattr(obj, field)[idx]\n```\n\nThe selector `\"position.shoulder_pan_joint\"` means: find `\"shoulder_pan_joint\"` in `msg.name[]`, get its index, return `msg.position[index]`. This works for any JointState-like message.\n\n### 4.5.3 ActionCommand Encoder\n\n```python\n@register_encoder(\"pnp_msgs/msg/ActionCommand\")\ndef _enc_action_command(names, action_vec, clamp):\n    msg = ActionCommand()\n    msg.header = Header()\n    # Parse \"position.shoulder_pan_joint\" → field=\"position\", joint=\"shoulder_pan_joint\"\n    for i, name in enumerate(names):\n        field, joint_name = name.split('.', 1)\n        idx = joint_names.index(joint_name)\n        if field == 'position':\n            positions[idx] = float(action_vec[i])\n    msg.name = joint_names\n    msg.position = positions\n    return msg\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4.6 `action_to_jointstate_adapter.py`\n\n**File:** `rosetta/rosetta/action_to_jointstate_adapter.py`\n**Lines:** ~93\n**Purpose:** Converts `/action_commands` (ActionCommand) → `/policy_joint_commands` (JointState).\n\n**Why needed:** Isaac Sim's joint controller subscribes to `sensor_msgs/JointState`. The PolicyBridge publishes `pnp_msgs/ActionCommand`. The adapter bridges this gap.\n\n**Critical detail:**\n```python\njoint_state.velocity = []  # IMPORTANT: Zero out velocity!\njoint_state.effort = []\n```\nThe motion planner includes velocity commands, but for position control in Isaac Sim, only positions matter. Passing velocities through can interfere with the position controller.\n\n---\n\n# Section 5 — Mathematics & Algorithms Deep Dive\n\n## 5.1 Resampling Algorithms\n\n### Problem\nRaw ROS messages arrive at irregular times and different rates. Training requires uniformly-spaced frames at exactly `rate_hz` (20 Hz = every 50ms).\n\n### 5.1.1 Last-Value-Hold (Primary Strategy)\n\nUsed for all observations in the UR5e pipeline (`align.strategy: hold`).\n\n```\nInput:  Messages at irregular times [t1, t2, t3, ...]\nOutput: Values at uniform ticks [T0, T1, T2, ...]\n\nAlgorithm:\n  For each tick T:\n    Find last message at time ≤ T\n    Output that message's value\n\nExample:\n  Messages:  [t=0ms: v1] [t=60ms: v2] [t=120ms: v3]\n  Ticks@20Hz: T=0ms → v1, T=50ms → v1, T=100ms → v2, T=150ms → v3\n```\n\n```python\ndef resample_hold(ts_ns, vals, ticks_ns):\n    out, j, last = [], 0, None\n    if len(ts_ns) > 0 and ticks_ns[0] < ts_ns[0]:\n        last = vals[0]  # Forward-fill for early ticks\n    for t in ticks_ns:\n        while j + 1 < len(ts_ns) and ts_ns[j + 1] <= t:\n            j += 1\n        if j < len(vals) and ts_ns[j] <= t:\n            last = vals[j]\n        out.append(last)\n    return out\n```\n\n**Time complexity:** O(N + M) where N = messages, M = ticks (single sweep).\n\n### 5.1.2 As-Of Resampling\n\nUsed when freshness matters. Returns `None` if the last value is older than `tol_ns`.\n\n```python\ndef resample_asof(ts_ns, vals, ticks_ns, tol_ns):\n    for t in ticks_ns:\n        # Find last message\n        ok = ts_ns[j] <= t and (t - ts_ns[j]) <= tol_ns\n        out.append(vals[j] if ok else None)\n```\n\n### 5.1.3 Drop Resampling\n\nOnly returns a value if a message arrived within the last step (window-based).\n\n```python\ndef resample_drop(ts_ns, vals, ticks_ns, step_ns):\n    out.append(vals[j] if (ts_ns[j] > t - step_ns) else None)\n```\n\n## 5.2 Image Resizing: Nearest-Neighbor\n\n```python\ndef _nearest_resize_rgb(img, rh, rw):\n    y = np.linspace(0, img.shape[0]-1, rh).astype(np.int64)\n    x = np.linspace(0, img.shape[1]-1, rw).astype(np.int64)\n    return img[y][:, x]\n```\n\n**Why nearest-neighbor?** Pure NumPy (no OpenCV dependency), deterministic, fast enough for 512×512 images, and the ResNet backbone is robust to interpolation artifacts.\n\n## 5.3 Depth Image Normalization\n\n```python\n# REP 117 compliance:\n# -Inf → too close, NaN → invalid, +Inf → no return\nhwc_normalized = np.where(\n    np.isfinite(hwc),\n    np.clip(hwc, 0, 50) / 50,  # Cap at 50m, normalize to [0,1]\n    hwc  # Preserve special values\n)\nhwc_3ch = np.repeat(hwc_normalized, 3, axis=-1)  # Replicate to 3 channels\n```\n\nDepth is normalized to `[0,1]` using a 50-meter maximum range. Special IEEE 754 values (NaN, ±Inf) are preserved through `np.where(np.isfinite(...))`.\n\n## 5.4 Action Timing: Next-Tick Alignment\n\n```python\ndef _next_exec_tick_ns(self, now_ns: int) -> int:\n    return ((now_ns + self.step_ns - 1) // self.step_ns) * self.step_ns\n```\n\nThis is **ceiling division** to align to the next tick boundary. At 20 Hz with `step_ns = 50,000,000`:\n\n```\nnow_ns = 123,456,789 → next tick = 150,000,000\nnow_ns = 150,000,000 → next tick = 150,000,000\nnow_ns = 150,000,001 → next tick = 200,000,000\n```\n\nActions are always scheduled at future tick boundaries, never in the past.\n\n## 5.5 QC Statistics\n\n```python\n# Per-topic gap analysis\nhz = (count - 1) * 1e9 / duration_ns  # Estimated rate\ngap_p50 = np.percentile(gaps, 50)     # Median inter-message gap\ngap_p99 = np.percentile(gaps, 99)     # Tail latency\nmax_gap = np.max(gaps)                 # Worst case\n```\n\nThe QC report computes percentile-based jitter metrics rather than mean, because network delays follow a heavy-tailed distribution. P99 reveals worst-case behavior that mean would hide.\n\n---\n\n# Section 6 — Build System & Deployment\n\n## 6.1 Package Structure\n\n```\nrosetta/                          # ament_python package\n  ├── package.xml                 # ROS 2 manifest (dependencies)\n  ├── setup.py                    # Python package + entry_points\n  ├── setup.cfg                   # ament_python config\n  ├── rosetta/                    # Source package\n  │   ├── __init__.py\n  │   ├── episode_recorder.py     # v1 recorder (basic)\n  │   ├── episode_recorder_v2.py  # v2 recorder (enhanced)\n  │   ├── policy_bridge_node.py\n  │   ├── action_to_jointstate_adapter.py\n  │   └── common/\n  │       ├── contract_utils.py\n  │       ├── decoders.py\n  │       ├── encoders.py\n  │       └── custom_decoders_encoders.py\n  ├── scripts/                    # CLI tools\n  ├── contracts/                  # Contract YAML files\n  ├── launch/                     # Launch files\n  └── configs/                    # Training configs\n\nrosetta_interfaces/               # ament_cmake package (generates .action)\n  ├── CMakeLists.txt\n  ├── package.xml\n  └── action/\n      ├── RecordEpisode.action\n      ├── EvaluateEpisode.action\n      ├── SaveEpisode.action\n      ├── DeleteEpisode.action\n      └── RunPolicy.action\n```\n\n## 6.2 Entry Points\n\n```python\nentry_points={\n    'console_scripts': [\n        'episode_recorder = rosetta.episode_recorder:main',\n        'episode_recorder_enhanced = rosetta.episode_recorder_v2:main',\n        'policy_bridge_node = rosetta.policy_bridge_node:main',\n        'action_to_jointstate_adapter = rosetta.action_to_jointstate_adapter:main',\n        'bag_to_lerobot = scripts.bag_to_lerobot:main',\n        'validate_contract = scripts.validate_contract:main',\n    ],\n}\n```\n\n## 6.3 Build & Deploy\n\n```bash\n# Build\ncd /data/tvp_ws/rlearning_ws\nsource /opt/ros/humble/setup.bash\ncolcon build --packages-select rosetta_interfaces rosetta\n\n# Source overlay\nsource install/setup.bash\n\n# Run recorder\nros2 run rosetta episode_recorder_enhanced --ros-args \\\n  -p contract_path:=.../ur5e_robotiq_pnp.yaml \\\n  -p enable_hotkeys:=true\n\n# Run policy bridge\nros2 launch rosetta ur5e_policy_bridge.launch.py\n```\n\n## 6.4 Dependencies\n\n| Dependency | Package | Why |\n|------------|---------|-----|\n| `rclpy` | ROS 2 Python client | Node, pub/sub, action server |\n| `rosbag2_py` | Rosbag2 bindings | Read/write MCAP bags |\n| `rosidl_runtime_py` | Message utilities | `get_message()`, `serialize_message()` |\n| `std_srvs` | Service types | `Trigger` for cancel/pause |\n| `sensor_msgs` | Common msg types | `Image`, `JointState`, `Imu` |\n| `lerobot` | LeRobot framework | Policy classes, dataset format |\n| `torch` | PyTorch | Inference, tensor operations |\n| `numpy` | NumPy | Array ops, image processing |\n| `pnp_msgs` | Custom messages | `ActionCommand` (from separate package) |\n\n## 6.5 Gotchas\n\n- **Python 3.10 required:** ROS 2 Humble binaries are compiled against system Python 3.10. Using conda Python will cause import errors for `rclpy`.\n- **Build order:** `rosetta_interfaces` must be built before `rosetta` (generates `.action` Python bindings).\n- **LeRobot install:** Must be installed in the same Python environment as ROS 2, typically via `pip install -e .` in a system-Python-based venv.\n\n---\n\n# Section 7 — Debugging War Stories\n\n## 7.1 The 35-Billion Frame Bug (Timestamp Domain Mismatch)\n\n### Symptom\n`bag_to_lerobot.py` crashed with memory allocation error: attempted to create 35 billion frames for a 20-second recording.\n\n### Investigation\n```python\n# Duration calculation:\nts_max - start_ns = 1762293953848768627 - 5954100310530\n#                  = 1762288... (≈ 55 years in nanoseconds!)\n```\n\n### Root Cause\nMixed timestamp reference frames:\n- Camera observations used **header timestamps** (Isaac Sim epoch: ~1.76 billion seconds)\n- Action commands used **bag receive timestamps** (relative: ~5-20 seconds)\n- `start_ns` came from action timestamps (small) but `ts_max` from camera headers (huge)\n\n### Fix\nChanged contract to use `stamp: receive` for ALL topics, ensuring a single monotonic timeline.\n\n### Lesson\n**Never mix clock domains in a data pipeline.** Even if headers seem more \"accurate,\" consistency across all topics matters more than individual accuracy.\n\n---\n\n## 7.2 The Cross-Episode Camera Contamination Bug\n\n### Symptom\nWhen replaying recorded bags, camera frames from a **failed episode** appeared at the beginning of the **next successful episode**. Specifically:\n- Frame 1-50: Robot near pick position (from failed Episode N)\n- Frame 51+: Robot at HOME (current Episode N+1)\n\n### Investigation\n\nRan custom diagnostic script (`diagnose_camera_sync.py`) on a recorded bag:\n\n```\nCross-Camera Alignment:\n/camera_ee/rgb:        First message at t=0.010s   ✅\n/camera_egol/rgb:      First message at t=10.030s   ❌ 10 SECONDS LATE!\n/camera_egor/rgb:      First message at t=0.049s   ✅\n/camera_thirdeye/rgb:  First message at t=0.021s   ✅\n\nMaximum spread: 10020.06ms → ❌ SEVERE\n```\n\n### Root Cause\n**Per-topic message queues were never cleared between episodes.**\n\n```python\n# Bug: queues created once at startup, never cleared\nself._ws.queues[tinfo.name] = deque(maxlen=MAX_QUEUE_SIZE)\n\n# At episode start, only counters were reset:\nfor k in list(self._ws.counts.keys()):\n    self._ws.counts[k] = _TopicCounter()  # ← counters reset\n    # ← queues NOT cleared! Old frames still in queues!\n```\n\nAfter a failed episode (robot at pick position), queues contained ~50-100 old camera frames. When the next episode started, the writer thread drained these old frames first, creating time-reversed recordings.\n\n### Fix\n```python\ndef execute_callback(self, goal_handle):\n    # CRITICAL: Clear all queues BEFORE setting is_recording\n    self._clear_all_queues()\n\n    # Reset counters\n    for k in list(self._ws.counts.keys()):\n        self._ws.counts[k] = _TopicCounter()\n\n    # NOW safe to start recording\n    self._flags.is_recording = True\n```\n\n### Lesson\n**Persistent subscriptions with bounded queues require explicit cleanup at state boundaries.** The queue design was correct for throughput but wrong for temporal isolation between episodes.\n\n---\n\n## 7.3 The Policy Ignores Visual Input\n\n### Symptom\nTrained ACT policy executed the exact same trajectory regardless of object position. It completely ignored camera input.\n\n### Investigation\nTemporal causality analysis revealed action commands were **reactive** (arrived AFTER the robot reached the target position):\n\n```\nMean lead time: +744.10 ms (REACTIVE)\nExpected: -100ms to -500ms (PREDICTIVE)\n```\n\n### Root Cause (External Component)\n`pnp_actionlib/action_command_aggregator.cpp` used `this->now()` for `action_msg.header.stamp` instead of the controller's original timestamp. By publication time, the robot had already reached the commanded position.\n\n**Result:** The model learned `observation(t) → current_position(t)` instead of `observation(t) → future_position(t+Δ)`. Since proprioceptive state already perfectly predicts current position, cameras became redundant.\n\n### Fix\nPropagate the controller's original timestamp through the aggregator so actions appear **predictive** (lead joint states by 100-500ms).\n\n### Lesson\n**Temporal causality in imitation learning data is critical.** Action labels must be predictive (future-looking) for visual observations to provide useful information. If actions merely echo current state, proprioception always dominates vision.\n\n---\n\n## 7.4 Isaac Sim Simulation Time vs Wall Clock\n\n### Symptom\nHeader timestamps from cameras showed `sec: 44505` (~12.4 hours) while wall clock was `sec: 1763665404` (Unix epoch Nov 2025).\n\n### Investigation\n```bash\nros2 topic echo /camera_ee/rgb --once\nheader:\n  stamp:\n    sec: 44505          # ← Simulation time, NOT wall clock!\n    nanosec: 218987794\n```\n\n### Root Cause\nIsaac Sim publishes camera messages with **simulation clock** timestamps, which start from 0 and increment per simulation tick. All cameras share this clock, making them perfectly synchronized within the sim. However, the recorder was using `receive` (wall clock) timestamps, discarding this synchronization.\n\n### Implication\nFor Isaac Sim recordings, switching to `header` timestamps would provide **perfect camera synchronization** (<1ms spread vs 100-170ms with receive timestamps). But this must be done consistently across ALL topics to avoid the clock domain mismatch bug (see 7.1).\n\n---\n\n# Section 8 — Design Decisions & Tradeoffs\n\n## 8.1 Contract-Driven Architecture\n\n| Alternative | Why Rejected |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| Hardcoded topics in each node | Fragile, different for every robot |\n| ROS parameter files (not YAML) | Can't express nested structures (image resize, align, QoS) |\n| Protobuf/JSON schemas | Not idiomatic for ROS 2, harder to read |\n| Discovery-based (auto-detect topics) | Non-deterministic, can't guarantee train/serve parity |\n\n**Tradeoff:** Requires maintaining a YAML contract per robot. But this is *by design* — the contract is the documentation, the configuration, and the test fixture all in one.\n\n## 8.2 Always-On Subscriptions\n\n| Alternative | Why Rejected |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| Create/destroy subs per episode | DDS discovery latency (~1-5 seconds), messages lost during subscription setup |\n| Create subs, pause/unpause | ROS 2 doesn't support pausing subscriptions natively |\n\n**Tradeoff:** Memory used for subscription objects even when idle. But subscriptions are lightweight (~KB each), and the alternative (re-discovery) would lose the first seconds of each episode.\n\n## 8.3 Writer Thread + Queues vs Direct Write\n\n| Alternative | Why Rejected |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| Write directly in subscription callback | Blocks callback, risks DDS message loss at high rates |\n| ROS 2 timer-based batch writes | Timer jitter could cause bursty I/O |\n| `asyncio`-based writer | Incompatible with ROS 2's threading model |\n\n**Tradeoff:** Added complexity (thread, queues, locks). But necessary because `rosbag2_py.SequentialWriter.write()` can block on I/O (especially with compression), and blocking a subscription callback at 336 Hz (joint states) would cause DDS drops.\n\n## 8.4 MCAP vs SQLite3 for Bag Storage\n\n| Factor | MCAP | SQLite3 |\n|--------|------|---------|\n| File size | ~30% smaller | Larger |\n| Seek performance | O(log N) | O(N) for topic-specific queries |\n| Write speed | Faster (append-only) | Slower (B-tree inserts) |\n| Compression | Built-in (zstd) | External |\n| Tooling | Growing (Foxglove, MCAP CLI) | Universal |\n\n**Decision:** MCAP for all recordings. The size and speed advantages matter for 4-camera streams at 18 MB/s each.\n\n## 8.5 Receive Timestamps vs Header Timestamps\n\n| Factor | Receive | Header |\n|--------|---------|--------|\n| Consistency | ✅ Single clock domain | ❌ Mixed if different sources |\n| Network jitter | ❌ Included | ✅ Not included |\n| Sim sync | ❌ No | ✅ Perfect (for Isaac Sim) |\n| Simplicity | ✅ Always available | ❌ Not all messages have headers |\n\n**Current decision:** `receive` for safety (avoids 35B frame bug). **Recommended future:** `header` with guard rails (validate all topics use same clock domain).\n\n## 8.6 Action Chunking Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Value | Rationale |\n|-----------|-------|-----------|\n| `actions_per_chunk` | 25 | 25 × 50ms = 1.25s lookahead; covers typical grasp motion |\n| `chunk_size_threshold` | 0.5 | Refill when 50% consumed; balances latency vs freshness |\n| `publish_tolerance_ns` | 3 × step_ns | 150ms tolerance; accounts for Isaac Sim timing jitter |\n\n**Tradeoff:** Larger chunks = fewer inference calls but staler actions. Smaller chunks = fresher actions but more GPU overhead.\n\n---\n\n# Section 9 — Potential Interview Questions & Detailed Answers\n\n### Q1: Walk me through the complete data flow from a camera frame being captured in Isaac Sim to it being used as a training sample.\n\n**A:** The camera in Isaac Sim renders a 512×512 RGB frame at the simulation timestep and publishes it as a `sensor_msgs/msg/Image` on `/camera_ee/rgb` with the simulation clock in `header.stamp`. The ROS 2 DDS middleware delivers this to the `EpisodeRecorderServerEnhanced` subscription callback, which serializes it via `serialize_message()` and enqueues the CDR-serialized bytes along with a timestamp into a bounded `deque(maxlen=100)`. A dedicated writer thread drains queues round-robin, calling `rosbag2_py.SequentialWriter.write()` to persist each message to an MCAP file on disk.\n\nAfter collection, `bag_to_lerobot.py` opens the MCAP with a `SequentialReader`, deserializes each image message, and passes it to `decode_value(\"sensor_msgs/msg/Image\", msg, spec)` which calls the registered `_dec_image` decoder. This decoder calls `decode_ros_image()`, which interprets the encoding (RGB8), reshapes the byte buffer to `(512, 512, 3)`, applies nearest-neighbor resize if needed, and normalizes to `float32 [0,1]`. The resulting array is stored in a `_Stream`, then resampled at 20 Hz using last-value-hold, and written as a uint8 frame via `LeRobotDataset.add_frame()` which encodes it to H.264/MP4 video.\n\n### Q2: What is the \"contract\" and why is it the centerpiece of the architecture?\n\n**A:** The contract is a YAML file that declares every ROS topic a policy consumes or produces, including message types, QoS profiles, image resize dimensions, field selectors, timestamp alignment strategies, and action encoding parameters. It's the centerpiece because it's the single source of truth shared by three otherwise independent components: the episode recorder (which subscribes to exactly the topics listed), the bag-to-LeRobot converter (which decodes and resamples using the same specs and `decode_value()` functions), and the PolicyBridge (which subscribes, decodes, runs inference, and publishes using the same specs and `encode_value()` functions). This eliminates the most common source of bugs in robotics ML pipelines — shape mismatches, missing topics, or different preprocessing between training and serving. The contract also includes a SHA-256 fingerprint that gets embedded in the dataset and validated at inference time.\n\n### Q3: You discovered that camera frames from a failed episode appeared in the next episode's recording. Explain the root cause and fix.\n\n**A:** Subscriptions in the recorder are created once at startup and persist across episodes to avoid DDS re-negotiation overhead. Each subscription callback enqueues serialized messages into a per-topic `deque(maxlen=100)`. When an episode ended — especially a failed one that stopped abruptly with the robot at the pick position — these queues retained up to 100 frames showing the robot near the object. When the next episode started (robot back at HOME), the `execute_callback()` set `is_recording=True` and the writer thread began draining queues. It wrote the old frames first (showing pick position), then new frames (showing HOME position), creating a time-reversed sequence in the bag. The fix was to explicitly call `_clear_all_queues()` before setting `is_recording=True`, ensuring no stale data crosses episode boundaries. Additionally, the ordering was changed: queues are cleared first, then counters are reset, then `is_recording` is set, preventing a race where new messages arrive during clearing.\n\n### Q4: Why does the project use ROS 2 action servers instead of simpler services for recording control?\n\n**A:** Action servers provide three features that services lack: (1) **cancellation** — a behavior tree node can cancel a recording mid-flight, which is essential for the failed-episode workflow where the BT detects a grasp failure and needs to stop recording immediately; (2) **feedback** — the recorder publishes 2 Hz updates with total messages written, dropped count, and time remaining, which the BT or operator can monitor; and (3) **state machine semantics** — the goal transitions through ACCEPTED → EXECUTING → SUCCEEDED/CANCELED/ABORTED, which maps cleanly to behavior tree tick/success/failure semantics. Services are fire-and-forget, which doesn't model the long-running nature of a 30-second recording.\n\n### Q5: Explain the Producer-Executor pattern in the PolicyBridge.\n\n**A:** The PolicyBridge separates inference from publishing using two independent ROS timers running at the same rate (20 Hz). The **Producer** timer runs neural network inference: it samples observations from `StreamBuffer`s, builds a batch tensor, runs `policy.predict_action_chunk()` to get 25 future actions, and enqueues them with scheduled timestamps into a thread-safe `deque`. The **Executor** timer runs at each tick: it finds the action in the queue whose scheduled time is closest to \"now\" (within a tolerance), removes it, encodes it as a `pnp_msgs/ActionCommand`, and publishes. This decoupling is necessary because inference takes variable time (50-200ms for 4 camera images through ResNet + Transformer on GPU), but actions must be published at a steady 20 Hz cadence. The queue acts as a temporal buffer, absorbing inference jitter.\n\n### Q6: How does the resampling algorithm work, and why is it necessary?\n\n**A:** Raw ROS messages arrive at irregular intervals — cameras at ~23 Hz with jitter, joint states at ~336 Hz, action commands at ~34 Hz. Training requires uniformly-spaced frames at exactly 20 Hz. The `resample_hold()` function implements last-value-hold: for each target tick at `t = start + i * step_ns`, it finds the latest message with timestamp ≤ t using a single linear sweep (O(N+M) total). This carries forward the most recent value until a newer one arrives. It handles edge cases like the first tick occurring before any messages (forward-fills with the first available value). Alternative strategies `asof` (returns None if data is too stale) and `drop` (only returns values received within the last step) are available but `hold` is the default because it never produces gaps, which is essential for ACT's temporal attention mechanism.\n\n### Q7: What timestamp issues did you encounter and how did you resolve them?\n\n**A:** Three distinct timestamp issues were identified. First, a **clock domain mismatch bug** where camera headers used Isaac Sim's simulation clock (~44,505 seconds) while action commands used bag receive timestamps (~5-20 seconds relative). When `bag_to_lerobot.py` computed duration as `ts_max - ts_min`, the massive difference produced 35 billion frames. Fixed by standardizing on `receive` timestamps for all topics. Second, a **reactive action label bug** where `action_command_aggregator.cpp` stamped messages with `this->now()` instead of the controller's original timestamp, making actions appear simultaneous with or lagging behind joint states. This caused the trained policy to ignore vision. Fixed in the external aggregator component. Third, **cross-camera temporal skew** due to stale queue contamination producing up to 10-second misalignment between cameras. Fixed by clearing queues at episode boundaries.\n\n### Q8: Describe the image preprocessing pipeline and how you ensure train-serve parity.\n\n**A:** Images undergo the same pipeline in both `bag_to_lerobot.py` and `PolicyBridge` because they share the same decoder function `decode_ros_image()`. The pipeline is: (1) parse encoding from message (`rgb8`, `bgr8`, `32fc1`, etc.), (2) reshape raw bytes to HWC array, (3) convert BGR→RGB if needed, (4) nearest-neighbor resize to 512×512, (5) normalize to float32 `[0,1]`. For training, the converter then converts back to uint8 `[0,255]` for video encoding (LeRobot's dataloader re-normalizes). For inference, `_prepare()` permutes HWC→CHW, adds batch dimension, and moves to GPU. Both paths then apply the same LeRobot `preprocessor` (ImageNet normalization with `mean=[0.485,0.456,0.406]`). The shared decoder function and the contract-driven feature shapes guarantee consistency.\n\n### Q9: How does the staging workflow benefit automated data collection?\n\n**A:** The staging workflow (`_staging → accepted/backup`) provides a gating mechanism between raw recording and training data. After each episode, the BT can call `evaluate_episode` to generate a QC report (rate analysis, gap histograms, HTML report). If the episode passes quality checks (e.g., no large gaps, sufficient frame counts), the BT calls `save_episode` to move it to `accepted/`. If it fails (e.g., robot didn't complete the task, excessive frame drops), `delete_episode` moves it to `backup/` (not actually deleted — available for review). This is critical for automated collection because not every pick-and-place attempt succeeds, and training on failed demonstrations would degrade policy quality. The workflow ensures only good demonstrations enter the training pipeline.\n\n### Q10: What is the QC report and what metrics does it compute?\n\n**A:** The QC report (`qc_report.html`) analyzes a recorded bag to assess data quality. It computes per-topic: message count, duration, estimated Hz, and inter-message gap percentiles (p50, p90, p99, max). It generates matplotlib visualizations: a horizontal bar chart of per-topic rates and per-topic gap histograms showing the distribution of inter-message intervals in milliseconds. Large gaps (>5× mean) are flagged as potential issues. The report is generated by `summarize_bag()` which performs a single sequential pass through the bag, tracking timestamps per topic. This approach reveals issues like: topic publishing slower than expected, bursty message delivery, or individual topics dropping out mid-recording — all of which would degrade training data quality.\n\n### Q11: How do you handle multiple `observation.state` specs from different topics?\n\n**A:** The TurtleBot contract defines three `observation.state` keys from `/joint_states`, `/odom`, and `/imu`. These must be concatenated into a single state vector for the policy. In `bag_to_lerobot.py`, each spec gets a unique internal key (`observation.state_/joint_states`, `observation.state_/odom`, etc.) and its own stream buffer. During frame assembly, all state streams are individually resampled at 20 Hz, then concatenated in contract order: `np.concatenate([joint_values, odom_values, imu_values])`. The PolicyBridge mirrors this by creating separate subscriptions and `StreamBuffer`s with the same unique keys, then concatenating in `_sample_obs_frame()`. The total shape is stored in the dataset features as `(14,)` for UR5e or `(21,)` for TurtleBot, ensuring the policy receives a consistent vector.\n\n### Q12: Why use a `deque(maxlen=100)` per topic instead of unbounded queues or a single queue?\n\n**A:** Per-topic bounded queues solve three problems. First, **memory safety**: at 336 Hz × 786 KB/frame for images, unbounded queues would exhaust memory in seconds during a write stall. The 100-message cap limits each camera queue to ~78 MB. Second, **fairness**: separate queues prevent high-rate topics (joint states at 336 Hz) from flooding a single queue and starving low-rate camera topics. The round-robin drain ensures each topic gets written. Third, **drop isolation**: if one camera temporarily blocks (network hiccup), only that camera's oldest messages are dropped; other topics continue unaffected. The `maxlen=100` was chosen to hold ~4 seconds of camera data (100 / 23 Hz ≈ 4.3s), providing sufficient buffer for I/O bursts without risking memory pressure.\n\n### Q13: How does the PolicyBridge handle GPU inference latency?\n\n**A:** The ACT model processes 4×512×512 images through a ResNet-18 backbone plus a Transformer encoder/decoder, which takes 50-200ms on a CUDA GPU. At 20 Hz, this exceeds the 50ms step period. Action chunking solves this: instead of one action per inference call, the model predicts 25 actions (1.25 seconds of motion). The producer timer runs inference when the queue falls below 50% capacity, filling it with 25 future-scheduled actions. The executor timer, running independently at 20 Hz, merely dequeues and publishes. This means the GPU only needs to run inference every ~0.625 seconds (when 12-13 of 25 actions are consumed), comfortably within the time budget. The tolerance window (`3 × step_ns = 150ms`) accounts for scheduling jitter.\n\n### Q14: What would you change if you were starting this project from scratch?\n\n**A:** Three changes: (1) Use header (simulation) timestamps from the start with proper clock domain validation, rather than defaulting to receive timestamps — the perfect synchronization of Isaac Sim's simulation clock is wasted by adding network jitter through receive timestamps. (2) Implement an approximate time synchronizer (like `message_filters.ApproximateTimeSynchronizer`) for camera frames rather than independent queues — this would guarantee cross-camera coherence at the middleware level rather than relying on queue clearing heuristics. (3) Design the recorder with episode isolation as a first-class concern from day one — clearing queues, validating initial frame timestamps, and adding a warm-up period before committing data to the bag.\n\n### Q15: How does `contract_fingerprint()` prevent train-serve mismatches?\n\n**A:** The function extracts structural elements from the contract (observation keys, topics, types, selectors, image dimensions, action specs) into a canonical JSON string, hashes it with SHA-256, and truncates to 16 hex characters. This fingerprint is embedded in the LeRobot dataset's `meta/info.json` during conversion (`rosetta_fingerprint`). When the PolicyBridge loads a trained model, it computes the current contract's fingerprint and compares it against the stored one. A mismatch (e.g., someone added a camera, changed image resolution, or renamed a joint) triggers a warning log. This catches silent configuration drift that would otherwise produce incorrect inference results without any error.\n\n### Q16: Explain the decoder registry pattern and why it matters for extensibility.\n\n**A:** Decoders are registered via `@register_decoder(\"sensor_msgs/msg/Image\")` decorators that store function references in a global `DECODERS` dict keyed by ROS type string. When `decode_value(ros_type, msg, spec)` is called, it dispatches to the registered function. This allows adding support for new robot-specific message types (like `pnp_msgs/msg/ActionCommand`) by creating a new file (`custom_decoders_encoders.py`) with decorated functions — no changes to the core pipeline code. The same pattern applies to encoders. Both files are imported at module load time (`import rosetta.common.decoders  # noqa: F401`) to trigger registration. This is essentially a plugin system built on Python decorators.\n\n### Q17: What are the different episode failure modes and how does the system handle each?\n\n**A:** Four failure modes: (1) **Grasp failure** — BT detects object not grasped, immediately cancels recording via action cancel, deletes episode. Queue contamination was the main issue here. (2) **Planning failure** — MoveIt fails to find a path, BT cancels recording. (3) **Timeout** — Recording exceeds `max_duration_s` (120s), timeout timer fires, episode saved normally. (4) **Writer error** — Disk full or I/O error, `fatal_error` flag set, episode aborted. The `execute_callback` handles all cases through the same loop: `while is_recording and not fatal_error and not stop_requested`. Terminal state is determined by which flag was set: `goal_handle.abort()` for errors, `goal_handle.canceled()` for cancel/stop, `goal_handle.succeed()` for normal completion.\n\n### Q18: How would you scale this system to collect data on a fleet of 100 robots?\n\n**A:** The contract-driven design already provides most of the abstraction needed. Each robot would run its own recorder node with the same contract but different `bag_base_dir` (e.g., `/data/fleet/robot_042/`). A fleet manager node would send action goals to each robot's recorder. Bags would be collected to a central NFS or object storage. `bag_to_lerobot.py` already supports `--bags` for multiple bags. Key scaling changes: (1) replace local MCAP with streaming to cloud storage, (2) add robot ID metadata to each bag for provenance, (3) parallelize `bag_to_lerobot.py` across bags, (4) add a quality gate service that automatically evaluates and accepts/rejects episodes. The contract fingerprint ensures all robots use compatible data schemas.\n\n### Q19: What's the difference between episode_recorder.py (v1) and episode_recorder_v2.py?\n\n**A:** V1 writes messages directly in the subscription callback under a writer lock — simpler but risks blocking the callback at high message rates, especially if MCAP I/O stalls. V2 adds: (1) per-topic bounded queues + dedicated writer thread for non-blocking writes, (2) staging workflow (`_staging/` → `accepted/` or `backup/`), (3) three additional action servers (evaluate, save, delete), (4) QC report generation with matplotlib plots, (5) hotkey control for manual operation, (6) pause/resume functionality, (7) enhanced metadata (git SHA, system metrics, per-topic drop counts), (8) configurable timestamp source (header vs receive), (9) thread-safe episode access with `_episode_lock`, and (10) queue drain at finalization. V1 is still available for simple use cases; V2 is the production version for automated collection.\n\n### Q20: How does the ACT policy work at a high level, and what are its key hyperparameters?\n\n**A:** ACT (Action Chunking Transformer) is a transformer-based imitation learning policy that predicts a chunk of future actions from current observations. It has a ResNet-18 backbone per camera (or shared) that encodes 512×512 images to feature vectors, which are combined with the proprioceptive state (14-dim) as input tokens to a transformer encoder (4 layers, 512-dim, 8 heads). A transformer decoder (7 layers) auto-regressively generates the action chunk. A VAE (Variational Autoencoder) regularizer with KL weight=10.0 improves generalization. Key hyperparameters: `dim_model=512` (hidden size — was later reduced to 256 to force visual grounding), `n_action_steps=1` (predict full chunk at once), `temporal_ensemble_coeff=0.01` (blending weight for overlapping chunks). Training uses batch_size=8, lr=1e-5 (backbone), 100K steps with warmup, and data augmentation (brightness, contrast, saturation, hue, sharpness).\n\n---\n\n# Section 10 — Quick Reference Tables\n\n## 10.1 File Map\n\n| File | Lines | Purpose |\n|------|-------|---------|\n| `rosetta/episode_recorder_v2.py` | ~1614 | Enhanced recorder with staging, QC, hotkeys |\n| `rosetta/policy_bridge_node.py` | ~1063 | Live policy inference with action chunking |\n| `rosetta/episode_recorder.py` | ~685 | Basic recorder (v1, direct write) |\n| `rosetta/action_to_jointstate_adapter.py` | ~93 | ActionCommand → JointState converter |\n| `rosetta/common/contract_utils.py` | ~624 | Contract loader, specs, resampling, registries |\n| `rosetta/common/decoders.py` | ~351 | ROS message → numpy decoders |\n| `rosetta/common/encoders.py` | ~209 | numpy → ROS message encoders |\n| `rosetta/common/custom_decoders_encoders.py` | ~209 | pnp_msgs decoders/encoders |\n| `scripts/bag_to_lerobot.py` | ~696 | Rosbag → LeRobot v3 converter |\n| `scripts/validate_contract.py` | ~391 | Contract YAML validator |\n| `scripts/validate_lerobot_dataset.py` | ~551 | Dataset structure validator |\n| `scripts/validate_multi_episode_dataset.py` | ~1369 | Comprehensive multi-episode validator |\n| `scripts/train_ur5e_act.sh` | ~199 | Training launch script |\n| `scripts/diagnose_camera_sync.py` | ~400 | Camera synchronization diagnostic |\n| `contracts/ur5e_robotiq_pnp.yaml` | ~97 | UR5e 4-camera contract |\n| `contracts/turtlebot.yaml` | ~78 | TurtleBot diff-drive contract |\n| `configs/train_act_ur5e.yaml` | ~97 | ACT training config |\n| `launch/ur5e_policy_bridge.launch.py` | ~145 | PolicyBridge + adapter launch |\n\n## 10.2 Key Numbers\n\n| Constant | Value | Location |\n|----------|-------|----------|\n| `FEEDBACK_PERIOD_S` | 0.5s | `episode_recorder_v2.py:107` |\n| `MAX_QUEUE_SIZE` | 100 | `episode_recorder_v2.py:111` |\n| `DEFAULT_QOS_DEPTH` | 10 | `episode_recorder_v2.py:110` |\n| `METADATA_RETRIES` | 20 | `episode_recorder_v2.py:108` |\n| `rate_hz` | 20 | `ur5e_robotiq_pnp.yaml` |\n| `max_duration_s` | 120.0 | `ur5e_robotiq_pnp.yaml` |\n| Camera resolution | 512×512 | `ur5e_robotiq_pnp.yaml` |\n| Camera rate | ~23 Hz | Isaac Sim measured |\n| Joint state rate | ~336 Hz | Isaac Sim measured |\n| Action command rate | ~34 Hz | MoveIt measured |\n| `actions_per_chunk` | 25 | PolicyBridge default |\n| `chunk_size_threshold` | 0.5 | PolicyBridge default |\n| `publish_tolerance_ns` | 3 × step_ns = 150ms | PolicyBridge |\n| Training batch size | 8 | `train_act_ur5e.yaml` |\n| Training max steps | 100,000 | `train_act_ur5e.yaml` |\n| ACT dim_model | 256 (reduced from 512) | `train_act_ur5e.yaml` |\n| ACT decoder layers | 4 (reduced from 7) | `train_act_ur5e.yaml` |\n| KL weight | 10.0 | `train_act_ur5e.yaml` |\n| Depth cap | 50 meters | `decoders.py` |\n| `_FEEDBACK_PERIOD_S` | 0.5s | `policy_bridge_node.py` |\n| Executor threads | 8 (recorder), 4 (bridge) | `main()` functions |\n\n## 10.3 Glossary\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|------------|\n| **Contract** | YAML file declaring all topics, types, QoS, rates for a robot policy |\n| **SpecView** | Runtime-normalized view of a contract observation or action spec |\n| **StreamBuffer** | Online constant-memory resampler (last-value-hold, as-of, or drop) |\n| **Action Chunking** | Predicting N future actions per inference call instead of 1 |\n| **Staging Workflow** | `_staging/` → `accepted/` (good) or `backup/` (rejected) |\n| **QC Report** | Per-topic rate/gap/jitter analysis generated after recording |\n| **Receive Timestamp** | Wall clock time when the recorder node received the message |\n| **Header Timestamp** | Time embedded in the message's `header.stamp` by the publisher |\n| **CDR** | Common Data Representation — ROS 2 serialization format |\n| **MCAP** | High-performance columnar bag file format (replacement for SQLite3) |\n| **ACT** | Action Chunking Transformer — imitation learning policy architecture |\n| **VAE** | Variational Autoencoder — regularization layer in ACT |\n| **Last-Value-Hold** | Resampling strategy: carry forward most recent value |\n| **Round-Robin Drain** | Writer thread processes one message per topic per cycle |\n| **BT** | Behavior Tree — orchestrates robot task sequences |\n| **DDS** | Data Distribution Service — ROS 2 middleware protocol |\n| **Train-Serve Parity** | Guarantee that training and inference use identical data processing |\n| **Contract Fingerprint** | SHA-256 hash of contract structure for mismatch detection |\n| **LeRobot v3** | Dataset format: Parquet + MP4 videos + JSON metadata |\n| **REP 117** | ROS Enhancement Proposal for depth image encoding conventions |\n",
