    {
      "id": "v6z8u8r1",
      "title": "SIm2Sim & ADC - ACT Policy: Control Rate vs Inference Rate",
      "content": "# ACT Policy: Control Rate vs Inference Rate\n\n## Key Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Value | Set At | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `chunk_size` | 100 | **Training time** (cannot change) | Number of actions the model predicts per forward pass |\n| `actions_per_chunk` | 10 (tunable) | **Inference time** | How many of those 100 actions to actually execute before re-querying |\n| Control rate | 20 Hz | **Inference time** | How often an action is sent to the robot (one every 50ms) |\n\n## The Two Clocks\n\nACT decouples two rates:\n\n1. **Control rate (20 Hz)** — how often the robot receives a joint command. This is always 20 Hz (every 50ms), matching the training data frequency.\n\n2. **Inference rate** — how often the neural network runs a forward pass to produce a fresh chunk of actions. This depends on `actions_per_chunk`:\n\n```\nInference rate = Control rate / actions_per_chunk = 20 / 10 = 2 Hz\n```\n\n## Step-by-Step Timeline (actions_per_chunk = 10)\n\n```\nt = 0.000s  →  INFERENCE #1: camera images + joint state fed to model\n               → model outputs 100 predicted actions [a0, a1, ..., a99]\n               → send a0 to robot\nt = 0.050s  →  send a1 to robot\nt = 0.100s  →  send a2 to robot\nt = 0.150s  →  send a3 to robot\nt = 0.200s  →  send a4 to robot\nt = 0.250s  →  send a5 to robot\nt = 0.300s  →  send a6 to robot\nt = 0.350s  →  send a7 to robot\nt = 0.400s  →  send a8 to robot\nt = 0.450s  →  send a9 to robot  ← 10th action executed, chunk exhausted\n\n               → actions [a10, a11, ..., a99] are DISCARDED (stale prediction)\n\nt = 0.500s  →  INFERENCE #2: FRESH camera images + joint state fed to model\n               → model outputs NEW 100 predicted actions [a0', a1', ..., a99']\n               → send a0' to robot\nt = 0.550s  →  send a1' to robot\n...\nt = 0.950s  →  send a9' to robot  ← chunk exhausted again\n\nt = 1.000s  →  INFERENCE #3: fresh observation → new chunk\n...and so on\n```\n\n## Why This Matters\n\nThe remaining 90 actions (indices 10-99) are thrown away each time. This is intentional — they were predicted from an increasingly stale observation. By re-querying with a **fresh observation** every 10 steps, the policy can **course-correct** for any drift.\n\n## Comparison Across Settings\n\n| `actions_per_chunk` | Actions used per chunk | Time between inferences | Inferences/sec | Actions discarded |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 10 | 10 of 100 | 0.50s | 2.0 Hz | 90 |\n| 20 | 20 of 100 | 1.00s | 1.0 Hz | 80 |\n| 50 | 50 of 100 | 2.50s | 0.4 Hz | 50 |\n| 75 | 75 of 100 | 3.75s | 0.27 Hz | 25 |\n\n## Offline Diagnostic Results (Model A, 15 episodes)\n\n| `actions_per_chunk` | Arm MAE (rad) | Worst-case Max Error (rad) | Joint |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 10 | 0.00871 | 0.120 | wrist_3 |\n| 20 | 0.00902 | 0.111 | wrist_3 |\n| 50 | 0.01087 | 0.425 | wrist_3 |\n| 75 | 0.01294 | 0.435 | wrist_3 |\n\n**Key takeaway:** More frequent re-inference (smaller `actions_per_chunk`) reduces worst-case error by **3.6x** (0.435 → 0.120 rad) because the policy gets to see fresh camera images and correct its trajectory more often. The cost is more GPU compute, but 2 inferences/sec is well within the capacity of an RTX 6000 Ada.\n",
      "tags": [
        "learning",
        "sim2sim",
        "imitation"
      ],
