    {
      "id": "y80bjoqp",
      "title": "Comparison between different Lerobot + ROS2 frameworks",
      "content": "# ROS 2 and LeRobot Integration for Data Collection, Training, and Deployment\n\n## Executive summary\n\nThe highest-confidence conclusion from the current public ecosystem is that there is **no single official, turn-key repository today that ships a complete, reusable ROS 2 + LeRobot stack for arbitrary industrial manipulators such as UR5/UR10 with Robotiq**. Instead, the best path is a **layered architecture**: use official LeRobot from entity[\"company\",\"Hugging Face\",\"ai company\"] for dataset/training/inference, pair it with **Rosetta** for ROS 2 bag-first integration, and use official or high-quality hardware layers such as the ROS 2 driver from entity[\"company\",\"Universal Robots\",\"robotics company\"] and the ROS 2 gripper stack from entity[\"company\",\"PickNik Robotics\",\"robotics software company\"]. If your hardware is in the ROBOTIS ecosystem, the most official end-to-end experience is **Physical AI Tools** from entity[\"company\",\"ROBOTIS\",\"robotics company\"]. citeturn32view0turn33view0turn27view0turn28view0turn22search0turn24view0turn16view0turn17search1\n\nFor ranking, I would put the repositories in this order for **practical end-to-end value**: **LeRobot** as the canonical core; **ROBOTIS physical_ai_tools** as the strongest official full workflow on supported robots; **iblnkn/rosetta** as the best generic ROS 2 ⇄ LeRobot bridge with explicit rosbag-to-LeRobot conversion; **legalaspro/so101-ros-physical-ai** as the best high-quality community example of a full real-hardware pipeline; and **ycheng517/lerobot-ros** as the best lightweight direct LeRobot/ROS bridge, although it is not centered on rosbag conversion. citeturn32view0turn33view0turn16view0turn17search1turn27view0turn28view0turn29view0turn30view0turn12view0turn31search0\n\nFor a **UR5/UR10 + Robotiq minimal reproducible pipeline**, the strongest recommendation is: **UR ROS 2 Driver + Robotiq ROS 2 gripper + Rosetta contract + a tiny action-mux adapter + LeRobot training**. The reason is architectural: Rosetta’s contracts are topic-oriented and support `std_msgs/msg/Float64MultiArray`, while the UR stack already supports **streaming position control** through `forward_position_controller`; that pairing is simpler and more reproducible than forcing a trajectory-action interface into a bag-first topic contract. citeturn39search0turn39search1turn40search4turn41view2\n\nThe safest model choice for a first working system is **ACT**, not a larger VLA. Hugging Face’s own documentation recommends ACT as the first policy because it is lightweight, trains in hours on a single GPU, and can often work with on the order of ~50 demonstrations, while SmolVLA and other VLAs are better second-stage upgrades after the pipeline itself is already stable. citeturn10search0turn28view0turn35search1\n\n## Ranking framework\n\nI ranked repositories by five criteria: **end-to-end completeness**, **source authority** (official over community when quality is comparable), **generality outside one robot**, **maintenance signals** such as stars/commits/recent activity, and **clarity of the actual data path** from teleoperation or recording through conversion, training, and deployment. That framework strongly favors repositories that expose real implementation seams such as contracts, controller mappings, dataset schemas, and inference launch points rather than only demos. citeturn27view0turn28view0turn29view0turn30view0turn16view0turn17search1turn12view0turn31search0\n\nA crucial scope note is that some high-value repositories are **end-to-end, but not bag-first**. LeRobot itself records directly into LeRobotDataset. ROBOTIS Physical AI Tools records directly to a LeRobot dataset and can also store rosbag2 as a **side artifact**. Rosetta and the legalaspro SO-101 stack are the clearest public examples of the **teleop/record → rosbag2 → LeRobot dataset → training → deployment** pattern the user asked for. citeturn36search0turn18search0turn28view0turn29view0\n\nBecause your target stack is **UR5/UR10 + Robotiq**, I also treated the **hardware-driver layer** as part of the answer even when those repos are not themselves end-to-end learning pipelines. For this use case, the UR ROS 2 driver and a maintained Robotiq ROS 2 package are not optional details; they are the substrate that makes controller selection, topic mapping, and deployment semantics concrete. citeturn22search0turn26search0turn24view0turn25search11\n\n## Top repositories and related resources\n\n### Ranked comparison\n\n| Rank | Repository / resource | Source type | What it actually covers | Maturity snapshot | Why it ranks here |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | `huggingface/lerobot` citeturn32view0turn33view0turn36search0turn10search0 | Official core | Canonical dataset format, recording, training, evaluation, async inference, hardware plugin model | ~23.7k stars, 1,425 commits, latest visible commit Apr. 24, 2026 | The non-negotiable core for training/inference and the reference data model |\n| 2 | `ROBOTIS-GIT/physical_ai_tools` citeturn16view0turn17search1turn18search0turn15search3 | Official vendor | Teleop, recording, direct LeRobot dataset generation, optional rosbag2 side recording, training, deployment, web UI | ~134 stars, 1,147 commits, release 0.8.2 on Mar. 18, 2026 | Best official full workflow on supported ROBOTIS platforms |\n| 3 | `iblnkn/rosetta` citeturn6view0turn8view0turn27view0turn28view0turn38view0 | High-quality community | Contract-driven ROS 2 recording to rosbag2, bag-to-LeRobot conversion, training handoff, deployment through ROS 2 actions | ~71 stars, 101 commits, latest visible commit Feb. 26, 2026 | Best generic ROS 2 ⇄ LeRobot bridge for arbitrary robots |\n| 4 | `legalaspro/so101-ros-physical-ai` citeturn29view0turn30view0turn15search0 | High-quality community | Real hardware teleop, episode recording, rosbag-to-LeRobot conversion, training workflow, sync/async policy inference | ~66 stars, 113 commits, latest visible commit Mar. 20, 2026 | Best public worked example of a complete rosbag-first real-robot pipeline |\n| 5 | `ycheng517/lerobot-ros` citeturn12view0turn31search0turn31search3 | High-quality community | Direct LeRobot robot/teleop integration for ROS 2 arms through ros2_control / MoveIt | ~187 stars, 15 commits, updated Nov. 6, 2025 | Best lightweight bridge, but not centered on rosbag conversion |\n| Related | `UniversalRobots/Universal_Robots_ROS2_Driver` citeturn22search0turn26search0turn39search0 | Official hardware layer | ROS 2 driver, controllers, MoveIt config, real/sim startup for UR arms | ~755 stars, 733 commits, release 5.0.0 Apr. 9, 2026 | Critical substrate for a UR-based stack |\n| Related | `PickNikRobotics/ros2_robotiq_gripper` citeturn24view0turn37search6turn25search11 | High-quality hardware layer | Robotiq driver, controller, description packages for ROS 2 | ~163 stars, 137 commits, org page updated Nov. 10, 2025 | Best current maintained ROS 2 Robotiq package I found |\n| Related | `ros2/rmw_zenoh` citeturn19search6turn19search2 | Official transport layer | ROS 2 middleware alternative based on Zenoh | Active in Apr. 2026 | Useful for distributed ROS 2 transport, but not a LeRobot pipeline by itself |\n\n### Repository-by-repository analysis\n\n**`huggingface/lerobot`** is the canonical center of gravity. It provides the `LeRobotDataset` format, `lerobot-record`, `lerobot-replay`, `lerobot-train`, the policy zoo, async inference, and a formal plugin model for custom robots and teleoperators. The most important implementation paths are `src/lerobot/`, `examples/`, `docs/`, and the hardware integration conventions documented in “Bring Your Own Hardware.” Its strongest fit is as the **training/runtime substrate**, not the ROS 2 integration layer. The main limitation for ROS-heavy shops is that it does not, by itself, solve ROS 2 controller mapping, rosbag semantics, or message contracts for arbitrary robots. citeturn32view0turn33view0turn9search0turn36search0turn9search1turn10search1\n\nA representative LeRobot command sequence is:\n\n```bash\nlerobot-record \\\n  --dataset.repo_id=${HF_USER}/record-test \\\n  --dataset.num_episodes=5 \\\n  --dataset.single_task=\"Grab the black cube\"\n\nlerobot-train \\\n  --dataset.repo_id=${HF_USER}/your_dataset \\\n  --policy.type=act \\\n  --output_dir=outputs/train/act_your_dataset\n```\n\nThose commands, together with replay/evaluation flows, come from the official “Imitation Learning on Real-World Robots” and ACT documentation. citeturn36search0turn10search0\n\n**`ROBOTIS-GIT/physical_ai_tools`** is the strongest official full workflow I found, but it is **ecosystem-shaped** rather than robot-agnostic. The repository structure includes `physical_ai_server`, `physical_ai_manager`, `rosbag_recorder`, `docker`, and an embedded `lerobot` subtree; the published docs add Web UI flows for recording, training, and inference on AI Worker/OMX/OMY-class platforms. A major architectural difference from Rosetta is that Physical AI Tools records the LeRobot dataset **directly**, while rosbag2 can be optionally stored in parallel. That makes it extremely usable on supported ROBOTIS platforms, but less generic as a reusable industrial manipulator bridge. citeturn16view0turn17search1turn18search0turn17search4turn18search5\n\nRepresentative commands and paths are vendor-documented rather than buried in code. Training via CLI is documented as entering the Physical AI Tools container, moving to `/root/ros2_ws/src/physical_ai_tools/lerobot`, and running:\n\n```bash\npython -m lerobot.scripts.train \\\n  --dataset.repo_id=${HF_USER}/ffw_test \\\n  --policy.type=act \\\n  --output_dir=outputs/train/act_ffw_test \\\n  --policy.device=cuda\n```\n\nRecorded datasets are stored under `~/physical_ai_tools/docker/huggingface/lerobot/${HF_USER}/`, and optional rosbag2 side data can be stored under `~/physical_ai_tools/docker/workspace/rosbag2/{User ID}/`. citeturn17search1turn18search0\n\n**`iblnkn/rosetta`** is the most important generic ROS 2 repository in this survey. It exposes a reusable architecture built around a **contract YAML** that maps ROS 2 topics to LeRobot keys, an `episode_recorder_node` that records contract-specified topics to rosbag2, `port_bags.py` for bag-to-LeRobot conversion, and a `rosetta_client_node` for policy deployment using LeRobot’s async gRPC server. The key implementation paths are `contracts/`, `launch/`, `params/`, `rosetta/`, and the documented package split involving `rosetta_interfaces`, `lerobot_robot_rosetta`, and `lerobot_teleoperator_rosetta`. citeturn27view0turn28view0\n\nRosetta’s exact end-to-end command path is unusually clear:\n\n```bash\nros2 launch rosetta episode_recorder_launch.py contract_path:=contract.yaml\n\nros2 action send_goal /episode_recorder/record_episode \\\n  rosetta_interfaces/action/RecordEpisode \"{prompt: 'pick up red block'}\"\n\npython -m rosetta.port_bags \\\n  --raw-dir ./datasets/bags \\\n  --contract my_contract.yaml \\\n  --repo-id my-org/my-dataset \\\n  --root ./datasets/lerobot\n\nlerobot-train \\\n  --dataset.repo_id=my-org/my-dataset \\\n  --policy.type=act \\\n  --output_dir=outputs/train/my_policy\n\nros2 launch rosetta rosetta_client_launch.py \\\n  contract_path:=contract.yaml \\\n  pretrained_name_or_path:=my-org/my-policy\n```\n\nThe main limitation is that Rosetta is **topic-oriented**, so robots whose primary control surface is an action interface or complex service graph usually need a small adapter node or custom encoder/decoder. That matters directly for UR + Robotiq. citeturn27view0turn28view0turn41view2\n\n**`legalaspro/so101-ros-physical-ai`** is the best public community repository that actually demonstrates the entire bag-first workflow on real hardware. It includes `episode_recorder/`, `rosbag_to_lerobot/`, `so101_bringup/`, `so101_inference/`, `policy_server/`, `so101_description/`, `so101_moveit_config/`, and `pixi.toml`. The important part is not the SO-101 hardware itself; it is that the repo exposes a concrete, auditable reference implementation of how to wire ros2_control, cameras, episode recording, conversion, training, and remote inference together. citeturn29view0turn15search0\n\nIts documented command path is exactly the sort of thing missing from many ROS-learning repos:\n\n```bash\nros2 launch so101_bringup teleop.launch.py\n\nros2 launch so101_bringup recording_session.launch.py \\\n  experiment_name:=pick_and_place \\\n  task:=\"Pick up the cube and place it in the container.\" \\\n  use_rerun:=true\n\npixi run -e lerobot convert -- \\\n  --input-dir ~/.ros/so101_episodes/pick_and_place \\\n  --config ~/ros2_ws/src/so101-ros-physical-ai/rosbag_to_lerobot/config/so101.yaml \\\n  --repo-id local/so101_test\n```\n\nIt then supports synchronous ACT/SmolVLA inference on-device and asynchronous inference via a remote `policy_server`. The main limitation is generality: it is a **robot-specific worked example**, not a universal bridge. citeturn29view0turn15search0\n\n**`ycheng517/lerobot-ros`** is architecturally elegant and likely the best option if you want a **native LeRobot device plugin** over a ROS 2 robot without committing to a bag-first design. It supports joint position control, joint trajectory control, MoveIt Servo Cartesian velocity control, and relation to gripper action controllers. The important paths are `lerobot_robot_ros/`, `lerobot_teleoperator_devices/`, and specifically the extension points documented as `robot.py` and `config.py`. citeturn12view0turn31search0\n\nIts quickstart is centered on direct LeRobot teleoperation in simulation:\n\n```bash\nlerobot-teleoperate \\\n  --robot.type=so101_ros \\\n  --robot.id=my_awesome_follower_arm \\\n  --teleop.type=keyboard_joint \\\n  --teleop.id=my_awesome_leader_arm \\\n  --display_data=true\n```\n\nThe repo explicitly says that once teleoperation works, standard LeRobot features can be used as usual. The limitation, for your requested workflow, is that **this repo is not itself a rosbag-to-LeRobot porter**. It is stronger as a direct-control bridge than as a data-portability bridge. citeturn31search0\n\n## Integration patterns compared\n\nThe ecosystem splits into a small number of durable integration patterns, and understanding those patterns is more useful than fixating on a single repository. citeturn27view0turn28view0turn36search0turn18search0\n\n| Pattern | Representative resources | Data collection path | Training path | Deployment path | Why it matters | Main tradeoff |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Native LeRobot device/plugin** | `huggingface/lerobot`, `ycheng517/lerobot-ros` citeturn9search0turn36search0turn12view0turn31search0 | Direct LeRobot recording | Direct `lerobot-train` | Native LeRobot eval/inference | Cleanest if you want LeRobot-first semantics | Weakest fit for bag-centric ROS debugging/reprocessing |\n| **Bag-first YAML contract bridge** | `iblnkn/rosetta` citeturn27view0turn28view0turn38view0 | ROS topics → rosbag2 via contract | `python -m rosetta.port_bags` → `lerobot-train` | `rosetta_client_node` + LeRobot async server | Best generic pattern for arbitrary ROS 2 systems | Usually needs controller/topic adapters for industrial robots |\n| **Robot-specific full ROS stack** | `legalaspro/so101-ros-physical-ai` citeturn29view0turn30view0 | Built-in episode recorder → rosbag | Built-in converter + Pixi/LeRobot | Sync or async real-hardware inference | Best worked example to copy architecture from | Less reusable without refactoring |\n| **Direct LeRobot dataset with optional rosbag sidecar** | `ROBOTIS-GIT/physical_ai_tools` citeturn18search0turn17search1 | Web UI records LeRobot dataset directly; rosbag2 optional | Web UI or LeRobot CLI | Web UI or CLI deployment | Most operator-friendly official workflow | Less transparent if you want contract-first portability |\n| **Transport-layer distribution** | `ros2/rmw_zenoh` citeturn19search6turn19search2 | Orthogonal to dataset semantics | Orthogonal | Better distributed ROS 2 transport | Useful when robot and compute are separated | Not a learning/data pipeline on its own |\n| **ros2_control-centric action/command abstraction** | UR driver docs, ros2_control controller docs, `lerobot-ros` citeturn39search0turn39search1turn40search4turn31search0 | Collection is separate | Training is separate | Controllers selected by action/topic surface | The right level to standardize manipulators | Requires careful controller choice before dataset collection |\n\nThe most important analytic takeaway is this: **for ROS 2 + LeRobot, “dataset semantics” and “control semantics” are separate problems**. Rosetta solves dataset semantics brilliantly with contracts and bag conversion. UR and Robotiq drivers solve control semantics. The best practical system is the one where those seams are made explicit, versioned, and testable. citeturn28view0turn22search0turn24view0\n\n## Recommended minimum reproducible pipeline for UR5 and UR10 with Robotiq\n\nBecause the **OS/distribution and exact UR model variant are unspecified**, the safest recommendation is a modular stack that can survive distro changes. If you are starting clean, **Ubuntu 24.04 + ROS 2 Jazzy** is the most coherent baseline across the current examples I reviewed: legalaspro targets Jazzy, `lerobot-ros` says it is tested on Jazzy, ROBOTIS ships a `jazzy` branch, and Universal Robots publishes Jazzy documentation. If your broader environment requires older binary availability, **Humble remains viable** for several pieces, including the PickNik gripper stack. citeturn29view0turn12view0turn16view0turn26search2turn24view0\n\n### Pipeline diagram\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n    A[Teleop source\\nMoveIt Servo / SpaceMouse / leader arm / custom node]\n    B[ROS 2 control graph\\nUR driver + Robotiq controller + cameras]\n    C[Rosetta recorder\\ncontract YAML]\n    D[rosbag2 MCAP episodes]\n    E[rosetta.port_bags\\ncontract-based conversion]\n    F[LeRobot Dataset v3]\n    G[lerobot-train\\nACT first]\n    H[Checkpoint / HF Hub model]\n    I[Rosetta client]\n    J[Action mux adapter]\n    K[UR forward_position_controller + gripper controller]\n    L[Real robot execution]\n\n    A --> B\n    B --> C\n    C --> D\n    D --> E\n    E --> F\n    F --> G\n    G --> H\n    H --> I\n    I --> J\n    J --> K\n    K --> L\n```\n\nThis flow is directly aligned with Rosetta’s contract/record/convert/train/deploy architecture, LeRobot’s dataset/training runtime, and the UR driver’s controller model. citeturn27view0turn28view0turn22search0turn39search0\n\n### Recommended package layout\n\n```text\nur_lerobot_ws/\n├── src/\n│   ├── Universal_Robots_ROS2_Driver/\n│   ├── ros2_robotiq_gripper/\n│   ├── rosetta/\n│   ├── ur_lerobot_adapter/\n│   │   ├── ur_lerobot_adapter/\n│   │   │   ├── action_mux.py\n│   │   │   └── topic_normalizer.py\n│   │   ├── config/\n│   │   │   ├── ur_lerobot_contract.yaml\n│   │   │   ├── ur_forward_position_controller.yaml\n│   │   │   └── cameras.yaml\n│   │   ├── launch/\n│   │   │   ├── collect.launch.py\n│   │   │   └── deploy.launch.py\n│   │   └── package.xml\n│   └── ur_cell_description/\n│       ├── urdf/\n│       └── config/\n├── datasets/\n│   ├── bags/\n│   └── lerobot/\n└── outputs/\n    └── train/\n```\n\nThe key reusable component is `ur_lerobot_adapter`: it gives you one place to version command normalization, contract files, and any UR/gripper muxing logic. That is preferable to scattering one-off remaps through launch files. citeturn27view0turn28view0turn22search0turn24view0\n\n### Essential packages and why they are in the stack\n\nUse the **UR ROS 2 Driver** for robot bring-up and controller management, **ros2_control** forward or position controllers for streamable joint commands, **PickNik’s Robotiq package** for gripper description/driver/controller support, **Rosetta** for contract-driven recording and bag conversion, and **LeRobot** for training and inference. Rosetta supports `sensor_msgs/msg/JointState`, `sensor_msgs/msg/CompressedImage`, and `std_msgs/msg/Float64MultiArray`, which is exactly why a `Float64MultiArray` action path into a forward position controller is such a useful minimum path. citeturn22search0turn26search0turn40search4turn24view0turn25search11turn38view0turn41view2\n\n### Topic mapping recommendation\n\n| LeRobot key | ROS 2 topic | ROS 2 type | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `observation.state` | `/joint_states` | `sensor_msgs/msg/JointState` | Select 6 UR joints plus 1 gripper signal if it is published in `joint_states` |\n| `observation.images.top` | `/camera_top/image_raw/compressed` | `sensor_msgs/msg/CompressedImage` | Main scene camera |\n| `observation.images.wrist.right` | `/camera_wrist/image_raw/compressed` | `sensor_msgs/msg/CompressedImage` | Optional but recommended for VLA fine-tuning |\n| `action` | `/ur_lerobot/action_cmd` | `std_msgs/msg/Float64MultiArray` | 7-dim vector: 6 arm joints + 1 gripper dimension |\n| `adjunct` | `/tf`, `/diagnostics` | recorded only | Keep for debugging and future reprocessing |\n\nThis mapping follows Rosetta’s contract model and supported message types. The action topic is intentionally **not** sent directly to the UR trajectory action. Instead, a small adapter node should split the vector and forward the first six values to the UR controller and the last value to the gripper path. That keeps the dataset/model side stable even if the hardware side changes. citeturn41view2turn38view0turn26search0turn39search0turn40search4\n\n### Rosetta contract for a UR cell\n\n```yaml\nrobot_type: ur_with_robotiq\nfps: 15\n\nobservations:\n  - key: observation.state\n    topic: /joint_states\n    type: sensor_msgs/msg/JointState\n    selector:\n      names:\n        - position.shoulder_pan_joint\n        - position.shoulder_lift_joint\n        - position.elbow_joint\n        - position.wrist_1_joint\n        - position.wrist_2_joint\n        - position.wrist_3_joint\n        - position.robotiq_finger_joint\n    align:\n      strategy: hold\n      stamp: header\n\n  - key: observation.images.top\n    topic: /camera_top/image_raw/compressed\n    type: sensor_msgs/msg/CompressedImage\n    image:\n      resize: [480, 640]\n\n  - key: observation.images.wrist.right\n    topic: /camera_wrist/image_raw/compressed\n    type: sensor_msgs/msg/CompressedImage\n    image:\n      resize: [480, 640]\n\nactions:\n  - key: action\n    publish:\n      topic: /ur_lerobot/action_cmd\n      type: std_msgs/msg/Float64MultiArray\n    safety_behavior: hold\n\ntasks:\n  - key: task\n    topic: /task_prompt\n    type: std_msgs/msg/String\n\nadjunct:\n  - topic: /tf\n    type: tf2_msgs/msg/TFMessage\n  - topic: /diagnostics\n    type: diagnostic_msgs/msg/DiagnosticArray\n```\n\nThis is a synthesized configuration, but every element follows Rosetta’s contract schema and supported message types. The decisive design choice is using `Float64MultiArray` for `action`, because Rosetta supports it and UR-compatible forward command controllers accept `Float64MultiArray` on `~/commands`. citeturn41view2turn38view0turn40search4\n\n### Bring-up and collection commands\n\nA minimal real-robot bring-up sequence for a UR arm is:\n\n```bash\nros2 launch ur_robot_driver ur_control.launch.py \\\n  ur_type:=ur5e \\\n  robot_ip:=192.168.0.10\n```\n\nFor dry runs, the UR driver documents `use_mock_hardware:=true`; for deployment you can switch controllers from the default `scaled_joint_trajectory_controller` to `forward_position_controller` when you want streaming commands. citeturn22search0turn26search7turn39search1turn39search0\n\nThe controller switch that makes Rosetta-friendly streaming easier is:\n\n```bash\nros2 control switch_controllers \\\n  --deactivate scaled_joint_trajectory_controller \\\n  --activate forward_position_controller\n```\n\nThat switch is directly documented by Universal Robots. The reason to prefer it for the minimum reproducible path is that `forward_position_controller` is a streaming controller, whereas Rosetta’s minimal action path is topic-based rather than `FollowJointTrajectory`-action-based. citeturn39search1turn39search0\n\nA first-pass recording sequence is then:\n\n```bash\nros2 launch rosetta episode_recorder_launch.py \\\n  contract_path:=src/ur_lerobot_adapter/config/ur_lerobot_contract.yaml \\\n  bag_base_dir:=datasets/bags\n\nros2 action send_goal /episode_recorder/record_episode \\\n  rosetta_interfaces/action/RecordEpisode \\\n  \"{prompt: 'pick up the block and place it in the bin'}\"\n```\n\nRosetta recommends MCAP by default, and the bag-first design is specifically intended to preserve raw data so that you can revise the contract later without re-recording. citeturn28view0\n\n### Conversion, training, and deployment commands\n\nFor conversion:\n\n```bash\npython -m rosetta.port_bags \\\n  --raw-dir ./datasets/bags \\\n  --contract ./src/ur_lerobot_adapter/config/ur_lerobot_contract.yaml \\\n  --repo-id local/ur_pick_place_v1 \\\n  --root ./datasets/lerobot\n```\n\nFor training, start with ACT:\n\n```bash\nlerobot-train \\\n  --dataset.repo_id=local/ur_pick_place_v1 \\\n  --policy.type=act \\\n  --output_dir=outputs/train/act_ur_pick_place_v1 \\\n  --policy.device=cuda\n```\n\nFor deployment:\n\n```bash\nros2 launch rosetta rosetta_client_launch.py \\\n  contract_path:=src/ur_lerobot_adapter/config/ur_lerobot_contract.yaml \\\n  pretrained_name_or_path:=outputs/train/act_ur_pick_place_v1/checkpoints/last/pretrained_model\n```\n\nThese command shapes are directly aligned with Rosetta’s documented flow and LeRobot’s ACT training flow. Using ACT first is the strongest default because it is explicitly recommended as the easiest starting model. citeturn28view0turn27view0turn10search0\n\n### Why I recommend a tiny action-mux adapter\n\nFor UR + Robotiq specifically, I recommend one small bridge node, for example `action_mux.py`, that subscribes to `/ur_lerobot/action_cmd` and splits the 7-element vector into:  \n`[q1..q6] → /forward_position_controller/commands` and `[g] → gripper controller input`. That bridge is the cleanest place to handle clamping, unit normalization, and gripper-controller differences. It also prevents the dataset contract from becoming polluted with vendor-specific controller mechanics. This is an architectural recommendation inferred from Rosetta’s topic-centric action contract, the UR driver controller model, and ros2_control’s `~/commands` interface semantics. citeturn41view2turn39search0turn40search4\n\n## Validation, pitfalls, and next steps\n\nThe validation plan should be **stage-gated**, not “train and hope.” First verify robot/controller semantics, then sensor timing, then recording, then conversion, then training, then deployment. A practical gating table is below. citeturn28view0turn36search0turn10search1\n\n| Stage | Minimal test | Pass criterion | Typical failure mode |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Bring-up | Start UR driver and list controllers | `joint_state_broadcaster` active; chosen motion controller active | Wrong distro/driver setup; calibration not applied |\n| Streaming control | Publish a tiny command to the active controller path | Smooth joint motion at low amplitude | Using trajectory action path while expecting topic streaming |\n| Cameras | Echo and preview compressed topics | Stable timestamps and image rate | Compression or USB latency mismatch |\n| Recording | Record 3 short bag episodes | 3 MCAP bags created with expected topics | Missing QoS or stale topic selection |\n| Conversion | Run `rosetta.port_bags` on those 3 bags | LeRobot dataset created with expected feature names and videos | Bad selectors, missing gripper dimension, wrong image key names |\n| Dataset sanity | Visualize / inspect first episode | State/action dimensionality matches contract | Joint order mismatch |\n| Training | Overfit on 10–20 episodes first | Training loss drops quickly; replay looks plausible | Normalization bug or bad action/state alignment |\n| Deployment | Run policy at low speed with wide safety margins | Stable closed-loop execution without runaway commands | Controller mismatch, stale observations, unbounded gripper commands |\n\nThis staged approach is strongly supported by the underlying source behavior: UR controllers have distinct semantics; Rosetta’s alignment strategy can hold or reject stale messages; LeRobot’s dataset tooling and ACT path are modular enough that you can isolate errors one phase at a time. citeturn39search0turn39search1turn38view0turn36search5turn10search0\n\nThe main pitfalls are predictable. **Controller mismatch** is the big one: UR’s best-known action path is trajectory-based, while a contract-based bag/deploy bridge is topic-oriented. **Timestamp/QoS drift** is next: Rosetta explicitly exposes alignment strategies because asynchronous camera and robot topics are otherwise easy to mis-sample. **Storage blow-up** is also real: ROBOTIS explicitly documents that rosbag side recordings can take about nine times the space of the LeRobot dataset. Finally, **streaming controllers shift more responsibility to you**: UR’s own docs warn that with streaming position or velocity controllers, the user is responsible for safe and achievable commands, and those paths do not automatically account for speed scaling in the same way trajectory-based controllers do. citeturn39search0turn39search5turn38view0turn18search0\n\nMy actionable next steps would be these. First, stand up the UR arm in **mock hardware or URSim** and prove the **controller abstraction** before touching data. Second, implement the `ur_lerobot_adapter` package as a reusable module with the contract, mux node, and launch files under version control. Third, collect a **small ACT-first dataset** with one top camera and one simple task. Fourth, only after ACT works, add a wrist camera and language prompts for SmolVLA or another VLA. Fifth, if the robot-side machine is resource-constrained, move deployment to Rosetta’s remote async path / LeRobot policy server. citeturn26search7turn10search0turn35search1turn28view0turn9search1\n\nThe main open limitations from the current evidence base are straightforward. Your **exact OS/distribution and UR variant are unspecified**, so the best distro choice still depends on the rest of your shop. Your **exact Robotiq model and connection method** are also unspecified, and that materially affects whether the gripper should be exposed as a position-command joint, a parallel gripper controller, or an action-backed adapter. Most importantly, among the official and high-quality public repos I reviewed, I did **not** find a single already-maintained repository that ships the full **UR5/UR10 + Robotiq + Rosetta + LeRobot** pipeline as a ready-made product; the strongest solution today is still a clean composition of proven layers rather than a single monolith. citeturn22search0turn24view0turn27view0turn32view0turn16view0",
