      "id": "jss61tmj",
      "title": "KV Cache",
      "content": "Optimization of LLM Inference: Understanding the KV Cache\n\nExecutive Summary\n\nLarge Language Models (LLMs) generate text autoregressively, producing one token at a time. In a standard implementation, this process is computationally inefficient because the model recomputes representations for every token in the sequence at every generation step. As the sequence grows, this leads to quadratic growth in computation time.\n\nThe Key-Value (KV) Cache is a critical optimization technique designed to eliminate this redundancy. By storing the Key (K) and Value (V) representations of previously processed tokens in memory, the model can reuse them in subsequent steps, computing only the representations for the newest token. This shifts the computational complexity of attention from quadratic to linear, significantly increasing generation speed. However, this performance gain comes at the cost of substantial memory consumption, which scales with the sequence length, batch size, and model architecture.\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nThe Computational Inefficiency of Autoregressive Generation\n\nDuring the text generation process, an LLM predicts the next token based on all preceding tokens. Without optimization, the model performs the following at every step:\n\n1. Recomputation: Even though the weights of the model and the initial tokens remain constant, the model re-projects every token in the context into Query (Q), Key (K), and Value (V) representations.\n2. Quadratic Growth: As the sequence length (n) increases, the attention mechanism must compute dot products between every query and every key, resulting in an n \\times n matrix of attention scores.\n3. Performance Degradation: Because the model \"re-learns\" the context at every single step, generation becomes progressively slower as the output gets longer.\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nMechanics of the KV Cache\n\nThe KV Cache optimizes inference by leveraging the fact that once a token is processed, its Key and Value representations do not change.\n\nThe Core Optimization\n\nInstead of recomputing the entire sequence, the KV Cache implementation follows these principles:\n\n* Selective Computation: The model only computes the Query, Key, and Value vectors for the latest token generated.\n* Retrieval: The Key and Value vectors for all previous tokens are retrieved from a pre-allocated cache.\n* Targeted Attention: The model only needs the Query vector of the newest token to determine how much it should attend to all previous tokens (the Keys). This reduces the n \\times n attention matrix to a 1 \\times n row.\n\nWhy Queries are Not Cached\n\nQuery representations for previous tokens are not needed during the generation of a new token. The Query is only used to find relevant information from the past; once a token's representation is used to help predict the next token in its own step, its Query vector becomes obsolete for future steps.\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nTechnical Implementation Details\n\nImplementing a KV Cache requires specific modifications to the Transformer architecture’s attention module and the generation loop.\n\n1. Attention Module Modifications\n\nThe self-attention module must be updated to handle cache state:\n\n* Cache Tensors: Tensors for Keys and Values are pre-allocated with a shape of [Batch Size, Number of Heads, Maximum Context Size, Head Dimension].\n* Cache Tracking: A cache_length variable tracks the number of valid positions currently stored in the cache.\n* Incremental Updates: When a new token is processed, its newly computed K and V vectors are written into the cache at the index corresponding to the current cache_length.\n\n2. Positional Embedding Adjustments\n\nIn a baseline model, positional embeddings are usually generated from 0 to T (the total sequence length). With KV caching, since the model often receives only a single token as input, the system must manually track the token's actual position in the overall sequence (e.g., if 100 tokens were previously processed, the new token must receive the embedding for position 100) to ensure the model maintains spatial awareness.\n\n3. The Generation Loop Workflow\n\nThe inference process is split into two distinct phases:\n\n* The Prefill Phase (First Step): The entire prompt is passed through the model. The cache is filled with the K and V values for all prompt tokens.\n* The Decoding Phase (Subsequent Steps): Only the single, most recently generated token is passed into the model. The model retrieves the rest of the context from the KV Cache.\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nImpact on Performance and Resources\n\nSpeed and Computational Efficiency\n\nThe use of a KV Cache results in a dramatic improvement in generation speed. In experimental trials using a small model (4 layers, 4 heads, 128 hidden size), the KV Cache provided a 7x to 8x speedup in tokens generated per second.\n\nMetric\tWithout KV Cache\tWith KV Cache\nComputation Complexity\tQuadratic (O(n^2))\tLinear (O(n))\nTime per Token\tIncreases as sequence grows\tRemains nearly constant\nRedundant Projection\tHigh (all tokens re-projected)\tLow (only new token projected)\n\nThe Memory Trade-off\n\nWhile the KV Cache saves time, it consumes significant GPU memory. This is often referred to as the \"memory wall\" in LLM serving.\n\nMemory Requirement Formula: The total memory required for the KV Cache is calculated as: \\text{Layers} \\times \\text{Heads} \\times \\text{Head Dimension} \\times \\text{Sequence Length} \\times 2 \\times \\text{Bytes per Value} (The factor of 2 accounts for both Keys and Values.)\n\nCase Study: Modern LLM (FP16 Precision) For a model with 80 layers, 8 heads, a head dimension of 128, and a context length of 8,000 tokens:\n\n* Batch Size 1: Significant memory usage.\n* Batch Size 4: Approximately 10 GB of dedicated VRAM just for the KV Cache.\n\nThis linear growth in memory relative to sequence length and batch size makes the KV Cache a primary constraint when scaling LLM deployments to handle many concurrent users or very long documents.\n",
      "tags": [
        "llm",
        "robotlearning"
      ],
