    {
      "id": "bwaywkyb",
      "title": "Prefile vs Decode",
      "content": "Why is AI inference slow?\n- It's neither a problem of the hardware nor a problem of the software\n- It's mainly because of the way AI algorithms are deployed hence its a system problem\n# Decode vs Prefill in LLM Inference\n\nLLM inference has two major phases: **prefill** and **decode**.\n\nA simple way to remember it:\n\n> **Prefill = read the prompt**  \n> **Decode = write the answer**\n\nWhen you send a prompt to an LLM, the model does not immediately start writing the answer. First, it processes the entire input prompt. This first phase is called **prefill**.\n\nDuring **prefill**, the model reads all input tokens, computes attention over them, and builds an internal memory called the **KV cache**.\n\nExample prompt:\n\n```text\nExplain robot learning in simple terms.\n```\n\nThe model processes the prompt tokens roughly like this:\n\n```text\n[Explain] [robot] [learning] [in] [simple] [terms]\n     ↓        ↓          ↓       ↓        ↓        ↓\n          Process full prompt and build KV cache\n```\n\nAfter prefill is complete, the model is ready to generate the first output token.\n\nThe second phase is called **decode**. During decode, the model generates the answer **one token at a time**. It does not generate the full response in one shot.\n\nFor example, the output:\n\n```text\nRobot learning is the process...\n```\n\nis generated like this:\n\n```text\nStep 1: \"Robot\"\nStep 2: \" learning\"\nStep 3: \" is\"\nStep 4: \" the\"\nStep 5: \" process\"\n...\n```\n\nEach new token depends on the original prompt and all previously generated tokens. This is why decode is sequential: the model cannot generate token 10 before token 9 exists.\n\nA visual example:\n\n```text\nInput prompt:\n[A] [B] [C] [D] [E] [F]\n\nPrefill:\nProcess [A] [B] [C] [D] [E] [F] together\nBuild KV cache\n\nDecode:\nUse prompt context              → generate [G]\nUse prompt context + [G]         → generate [H]\nUse prompt context + [G] [H]     → generate [I]\nUse prompt context + [G] [H] [I] → generate [J]\n```\n\nThe **KV cache** is what makes decoding efficient. KV means **Key-Value**, referring to the key and value tensors used inside the transformer attention mechanism.\n\nFor a beginner-friendly mental model, think of the KV cache as:\n\n```text\nStored memory of already-processed tokens\n```\n\nWithout KV cache, the model would need to reprocess the entire prompt and previous output tokens every time it generates a new token.\n\nWithout KV cache:\n\n```text\nGenerate G:\nReprocess A B C D E F\n\nGenerate H:\nReprocess A B C D E F G\n\nGenerate I:\nReprocess A B C D E F G H\n```\n\nThis would be very slow.\n\nWith KV cache:\n\n```text\nPrefill:\nProcess A B C D E F once\nStore KV cache\n\nDecode:\nGenerate G using cached prompt memory\nGenerate H using cached prompt + G memory\nGenerate I using cached prompt + G + H memory\n```\n\nSo during decode, the model avoids recomputing old tokens and only processes the newest token while reusing the cached information from previous tokens.\n\nThe main difference between prefill and decode is the shape of the workload.\n\n**Prefill is parallel-friendly** because the full prompt is already available. The GPU can process many input tokens together using large matrix operations. This makes prefill mostly **compute-heavy**.\n\n**Decode is sequential** because each new token depends on the previous generated token. The model usually generates only one new token per sequence per step. This makes decode harder to parallelize across time and often **memory-bandwidth-heavy**, because the model repeatedly reads weights and KV cache to produce each next token.\n\nTwo important LLM serving metrics are directly connected to prefill and decode:\n\n```text\nTTFT = Time To First Token\nTPOT = Time Per Output Token\n```\n\n**TTFT**, or **Time To First Token**, is the time between sending the prompt and receiving the first generated token. TTFT is mostly affected by **prefill**.\n\nA long prompt increases TTFT because the model must process more input tokens before it can generate the first output token.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nPrompt:\n\"Summarize this 50-page paper in 3 bullets.\"\n\nWorkload:\nLarge input, small output\n\nDominant cost:\nPrefill\n```\n\n**TPOT**, or **Time Per Output Token**, is the average time required to generate each next token after the first one. TPOT is mostly affected by **decode**.\n\nA long answer increases total decode time because the model must generate many tokens one by one.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nPrompt:\n\"Write a 3000-word tutorial on LLM inference optimization.\"\n\nWorkload:\nSmall input, large output\n\nDominant cost:\nDecode\n```\n\nFor long prompt plus long output, both phases matter.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nPrompt:\n\"Read this entire codebase and generate a detailed refactoring plan.\"\n\nWorkload:\nLarge input, large output\n\nDominant cost:\nBoth prefill and decode\n```\n\nIn practical LLM inference optimization, different techniques target different parts of the inference process.\n\nPrefill optimization focuses on processing input tokens faster.\n\nCommon prefill-related optimizations include:\n\n```text\nFast attention kernels\nPrompt caching\nChunked prefill\nTensor parallelism\nEfficient batching\n```\n\nDecode optimization focuses on generating output tokens faster.\n\nCommon decode-related optimizations include:\n\n```text\nKV cache optimization\nPaged attention\nContinuous batching\nSpeculative decoding\nQuantization\nEfficient sampling\n```\n\nThe same transformer model is used in both phases, but the workload behavior is different.\n\nPrefill workload:\n\n```text\nMany tokens processed at once\nLarge matrix operations\nGood GPU utilization\nMostly compute-bound\n```\n\nDecode workload:\n\n```text\nOne new token per sequence per step\nRepeated memory reads\nHarder to parallelize across time\nOften memory-bandwidth-bound\n```\n\nThis difference is central to understanding LLM inference optimization. Many serving systems are designed around the fact that prefill and decode stress the GPU differently.\n\nA useful mental model:\n\n```text\nPrefill is expensive when the input is long.\nDecode is expensive when the output is long.\n```\n\nAnother compact version:\n\n```text\nPrefill = prompt cost\nDecode  = generation cost\n```\n\n## Copy-Ready Summary\n\nLLM inference has two major phases: **prefill** and **decode**.\n\n**Prefill** is the phase where the model processes the full input prompt before generating the first output token. It reads all prompt tokens, computes attention over them, and creates the **KV cache**. Prefill mainly affects **TTFT**, or **Time To First Token**. Since the full prompt is available upfront, the model can process many input tokens in parallel using large GPU matrix operations. Therefore, prefill is usually **compute-heavy** and **parallel-friendly**. Long prompts, long chat histories, RAG contexts, PDFs, and codebase inputs increase prefill cost.\n\n**Decode** is the phase where the model generates the output one token at a time. Each generated token depends on the prompt and all previously generated tokens. Decode mainly affects **TPOT**, or **Time Per Output Token**, and the overall streaming speed of the response. Decode uses the KV cache created during prefill so the model does not need to recompute the entire prompt for every new token. However, decode is still sequential because token `n+1` cannot be generated before token `n`. Decode is often **memory-bandwidth-heavy** because each step repeatedly reads model weights and KV cache.\n\nThe **KV cache** stores the key/value attention states of already-processed tokens. During prefill, the model creates the KV cache for the input prompt. During decode, the model reuses this cache and only processes the newest token. This makes generation much faster than recomputing the full sequence at every step.\n\nThe core intuition is:\n\n```text\nPrefill = read and understand the prompt\nDecode  = write the answer token by token\n```\n\nPerformance intuition:\n\n```text\nLong prompt  → prefill dominates\nLong answer  → decode dominates\nLong prompt + long answer → both matter\n```\n\nServing metrics:\n\n```text\nTTFT = Time To First Token → mostly prefill cost\nTPOT = Time Per Output Token → mostly decode cost\n```\n\nOptimization intuition:\n\n```text\nPrefill optimization = make prompt processing faster\nDecode optimization = make token generation faster\nKV cache optimization = store and reuse attention memory efficiently\nBatching optimization = keep GPU utilization high across many users\n```\n\nThe key expert-level point is that prefill and decode use the same model but create different hardware workloads. Prefill processes many tokens at once and is usually compute-heavy with good GPU utilization. Decode processes one new token at a time and is often memory-bandwidth-heavy, latency-sensitive, and harder to parallelize across time.\n\n\n\nWhat is the pain point of the current execution:\n-  ",
