      "id": "k1e5qyn3",
      "title": "DIRECT: When and Where Should You Allocate Test-Time Compute in Embodied Planners?",
      "content": "# DIRECT: When and Where Should You Allocate Test-Time Compute in Embodied Planners?\n\n**Added:** 2026-06-16  **Status:** #status/skim\n**Tags:** #paper\n\n## Metadata\n- **Authors:** Jadelynn Dao, Milan Ganai, Yasmina Abukhadra, Ajay Sridhar, Mozhgan Nasr Azadani, Katie Luo, Clark Barrett, Jiajun Wu, Chelsea Finn, Marco Pavone\n- **Venue / Year:** 2026\n- **Link:** [arxiv.org/abs/2606.12402](https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.12402)\n- **Code:**\n- **DOI / arXiv id:** 2606.12402\n\n## TL;DR (3 lines, in your own words)\n- The project is about how efficient routing frameworks could reduce test-time compute to improve performance. Inspired by the world idea of model routing from the world of llms\n\n## Problem\n- A lot of work is around high level VLM planners(or hierarchical VLAs) that break down abstract instructions into sub skills for a low-level policy - System 1 - System 2 decomposition\n- However these works commit to a single high level model with fixed capability and cost \n\n## Method\n- This work proposes to use the high level planner as a dynamic variable, dispatching to different VLMs based on each task's inferred cognitive demands - Dynamic Routing\n\n## Results\n- DIRECT is a routing framework that optimizes embodied AI by dynamically selecting the most cost-effective VLM planner for each specific task rather than using a single, static model.\n- The framework employs a \"synthetic data\" pipeline, allowing the router to learn task-specific quality-cost trade-offs offline, enabling zero-shot deployment on physical robots.\n-  Experimental validation shows that DIRECT recovers the performance of expensive, \"thinking\" models while significantly reducing latency and compute costs across diverse reasoning, model-size, and memory-context axes.\n\n## My take (so what? does it change anything I do?)\n- If you are building systems that balance conflicting metrics (like speed vs. accuracy), avoid using simple arithmetic averages to report performance.\n- For complex, multi-step tasks, DIRECT proves that routing should happen per-step, not just per-task.\n- Move Beyond \"One-Size-Fits-All\" Architectures\n\n## Connections\n- Related to: [[GroundSG AND  mEMer]]\n- Builds on: [[ ]]\n- Contradicts: [[ ]]\n- Relevant to topic map: [[🗺️ Topic Map — VLA]] \n\n## Quotes / snippets worth keeping\n> Effective allocation requires routing policies that infer task demands from scene and instruction context and match them to the\ncompute configuration with the best quality–cost tradeoff.\n\n## Follow-ups\n- [ ] Read and note down what MemER and GroundSG work does\n- [ ] Understand how the standard benchmarks like VLABENCH could be salvaged\n",
      "tags": [
        "paper",
        "research"
      ],
      "projectId": null,
      "dateIndex": null,
      "type": "page",
