      "id": "wjcxc7lu",
      "title": "GPU-Accelerated Hydroelastic Contact via Signed Distance Fields",
      "content": "# GPU-Accelerated Hydroelastic Contact via Signed Distance Fields\n\n**Added:** 2026-06-22  **Status:** #status/skim\n**Tags:** #paper\n\n## Metadata\n- **Authors:** Lennart Röstel, Yang Liu, Jessica Yin, Miguel Angel Zamora Mora, Miles Macklin, Philipp Reist, Tobias Widmer\n- **Venue / Year:** IEEE ICRA 2026 Workshop CR2\n- **Link:** [openreview.net/forum](https://openreview.net/forum?id=ogndqznZyY)\n- **Code:** [openreview.net/forum](https://openreview.net/forum?id=ogndqznZyY)\n- **DOI / arXiv id:**\n\n## TL;DR (3 lines, in your own words)\n- This paper introduces a GPU-accelerated method to perform high-fidelity hydroelastic contact simulations by using Signed Distance Fields (SDFs) instead of traditional meshes.\n- By using \"marching cubes\" on SDFs and a hierarchical pruning strategy, it achieves high physical accuracy for complex geometries while remaining computationally efficient.\n- It includes a novel contact reduction scheme that compresses massive contact point data into a manageable set of constraints for standard physics solvers.\n\n## Problem\n- Limitations of Point-Contact: Standard simulators rely on point-contact, which is fast but lacks \"area-dependent\" realism, leading to physical artifacts like unstable wobbling or incorrect friction behavior.\n- Complexity of Hydroelasticity: While the hydroelastic contact model is physically superior, previous implementations (based on mesh-to-mesh intersection) are too slow for real-time or large-scale robotic simulation, especially with complex, non-convex objects.\n\n## Method\n- SDF Representation: Objects are represented as Signed Distance Fields, allowing for quick mathematical determination of contact surfaces via the difference of stiffness-weighted SDFs.\n- Hierarchical Pruning: To maximize GPU efficiency, the simulation ignores grid cells that are not in the contact zone, drastically reducing the number of calculations needed.\n- Contact Reduction Scheme: The method takes thousands of raw contact points generated by the SDF surface and aggregates them into a small, optimized set of contact constraints that maintain the original net force and torque (\"wrench\").\n\n## Results\n-\n\n## My take (so what? does it change anything I do?)\n-\n\n## Connections\n- Related to: [[Hydroelastic Contact Model (Elandt et al. 2019)]], [[Newton Project]]\n- Builds on: [[Signed Distance Fields]], [[Marching Cubes Algorithm]]\n- Contradicts: [[Traditional Point-Contact Methods]]\n- Relevant to topic map: [[🗺️ Topic Map — Physical AI & Robotic Simulation]]\n\n## Quotes / snippets worth keeping\n> We introduce a GPU-accelerated implementation of hydroelastic contacts that is purely based on Signed Distance Fields, enabling fast, high-fidelity contact simulation\n\n## Follow-ups\n- [ ] Explore if the contact reduction scheme affects simulation stability when using PBVS.\n- [ ] Review the Newton project documentation for integration into your current pipeline.\n",
      "tags": [
        "paper",
        "research"
      ],
      "projectId": null,
      "dateIndex": null,
      "type": "page",
      "pinned": false,
      "notebookId": "wvskhat9",
