    {
      "id": "zggrunwy",
      "title": "Learn about editable install & packages in Python",
      "status": "BACKLOG",
      "due": null,
      "noteId": null,
      "projectId": "y9081w3r",
      "priority": "medium",
      "description": "Reference @\nhttps://chatgpt.com/c/68d3320e-5fa0-8328-b234-63669eb35ab7\n \n# Python Package Template — ready for `pip install -e .`\n\nBelow is a clean, **src-layout**, modern packaging template using **PEP 621** (`pyproject.toml` with setuptools). It includes:\n\n* Editable install (`pip install -e .`)\n* CLI via `console_scripts`\n* Optional `python -m yourpkg` entry\n* Dev extras (`.[dev]`), tests (pytest), pre-commit, lint/type configs\n* Single-source versioning\n\n> Replace every occurrence of `yourpkg` and `Your Package` with your real package name.\n\n---\n\n## 1) Folder layout\n\n```\nyourpkg/\n├─ pyproject.toml\n├─ README.md\n├─ LICENSE\n├─ .gitignore\n├─ .pre-commit-config.yaml\n├─ src/\n│  └─ yourpkg/\n│     ├─ __init__.py\n│     ├─ __main__.py\n│     ├─ cli.py\n│     └─ core/\n│        ├─ __init__.py\n│        └─ logic.py\n└─ tests/\n   ├─ test_cli.py\n   └─ test_logic.py\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2) `pyproject.toml` (PEP 621 + setuptools)\n\n```toml\n[build-system]\nrequires = [\"setuptools>=69\", \"wheel\"]\nbuild-backend = \"setuptools.build_meta\"\n\n[project]\nname = \"yourpkg\"\nversion = \"0.1.0\"\ndescription = \"Short one-line summary of what this package does.\"\nreadme = \"README.md\"\nrequires-python = \">=3.9\"\nlicense = { file = \"LICENSE\" }\nauthors = [{ name = \"Your Name\", email = \"you@example.com\" }]\nclassifiers = [\n  \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3\",\n  \"License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License\",\n  \"Operating System :: OS Independent\",\n]\ndependencies = [\n  # \"typer>=0.12.0\",  # Uncomment if you prefer Typer for the CLI\n]\n\n[project.optional-dependencies]\ndev = [\n  \"pytest>=8\",\n  \"pytest-cov>=5\",\n  \"pre-commit>=3.7\",\n  \"mypy>=1.10\",\n  \"ruff>=0.5\",  # linter/formatter\n  # \"types-setuptools\", \"types-requests\",  # add stub pkgs as needed\n]\n\n[project.scripts]\n# exposes a `yourpkg` command\nyourpkg = \"yourpkg.cli:main\"\n\n[tool.setuptools.packages.find]\nwhere = [\"src\"]\n\n[tool.setuptools]\ninclude-package-data = true\n\n[tool.mypy]\npython_version = \"3.9\"\nstrict = true\nwarn_unused_ignores = true\nwarn_redundant_casts = true\n\n[tool.ruff]\nline-length = 100\nextend-select = [\"I\"]  # import sorting\n\n[tool.pytest.ini_options]\naddopts = \"-ra --cov=yourpkg --cov-report=term-missing\"\npythonpath = [\"src\"]\n```\n\n> **Why `src/` layout?** Prevents tests from accidentally importing the in-tree code instead of the installed package, catching packaging bugs early.\n\n---\n\n## 3) Minimal package code\n\n### `src/yourpkg/__init__.py`\n\n```python\n__all__ = [\"__version__\"]\n__version__ = \"0.1.0\"\n```\n\n### `src/yourpkg/__main__.py`\n\n```python\nfrom .cli import main\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n```\n\n### `src/yourpkg/cli.py`\n\n```python\nfrom __future__ import annotations\nimport argparse\nfrom .core.logic import add\nfrom . import __version__\n\n\ndef build_parser() -> argparse.ArgumentParser:\n    p = argparse.ArgumentParser(prog=\"yourpkg\", description=\"YourPkg command-line interface\")\n    p.add_argument(\"a\", type=float, help=\"First number\")\n    p.add_argument(\"b\", type=float, help=\"Second number\")\n    p.add_argument(\"--version\", action=\"version\", version=f\"yourpkg {__version__}\")\n    return p\n\n\ndef main(argv: list[str] | None = None) -> int:\n    parser = build_parser()\n    args = parser.parse_args(argv)\n    result = add(args.a, args.b)\n    print(result)\n    return 0\n```\n\n### `src/yourpkg/core/logic.py`\n\n```python\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\ndef add(a: float, b: float) -> float:\n    \"\"\"Example reusable function (replace with your core logic).\"\"\"\n    return a + b\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4) Tests (pytest)\n\n### `tests/test_logic.py`\n\n```python\nfrom yourpkg.core.logic import add\n\ndef test_add():\n    assert add(2, 3) == 5\n```\n\n### `tests/test_cli.py`\n\n```python\nimport subprocess, sys\n\ndef run_cli(*args: str) -> str:\n    out = subprocess.check_output([sys.executable, \"-m\", \"yourpkg\", *args])\n    return out.decode().strip()\n\ndef test_cli_add():\n    assert run_cli(\"2\", \"3\") == \"5.0\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5) Pre-commit hooks\n\n### `.pre-commit-config.yaml`\n\n```yaml\nrepos:\n  - repo: https://github.com/astral-sh/ruff-pre-commit\n    rev: v0.5.7\n    hooks:\n      - id: ruff\n        args: [\"--fix\"]\n      - id: ruff-format\n  - repo: https://github.com/pre-commit/mirrors-mypy\n    rev: v1.10.0\n    hooks:\n      - id: mypy\n```\n\nRun once:\n\n```bash\npre-commit install\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6) README.md (starter)\n\n````md\n# Your Package\n\nShort description of what it does and why.\n\n## Install\n\n```bash\npip install -e .\n````\n\n## Usage\n\n### As a module\n\n```bash\npython -m yourpkg 2 3\n```\n\n### As a CLI\n\n```bash\nyourpkg 2 3\n# -> 5.0\n```\n\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7) .gitignore\n\n```\n\n**pycache**/\n\\*.py\\[cod]\n\\*.egg-info/\n.dist/\n.build/\n.pytest\\_cache/\n.mypy\\_cache/\n.coverage\nhtmlcov/\n.venv/\n.env\n\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8) LICENSE\n\nUse any OSI-approved license (MIT shown here):\n\n```\n\nMIT License\n\nCopyright (c) 2025 Your Name\n\nPermission is hereby granted, free of charge, to any person obtaining a copy\n... (standard MIT text) ...\n\n````\n\n---\n\n## 9) Developer workflow\n\n```bash\n# create & activate env (example with uv or venv)\npython -m venv .venv && source .venv/bin/activate\n\n# install in editable mode with dev tools\npip install -e .[dev]\n\n# run tests\npytest\n\n# run lints/type checks\nruff check . && mypy src/yourpkg\n\n# run the CLI\npython -m yourpkg 2 3\nyourpkg 2 3\n````\n\n---\n\n## 10) Optional niceties (pick as needed)\n\n* **Dynamic versioning:** use `setuptools-scm` instead of hardcoding:\n\n  ```toml\n  [build-system]\n  requires = [\"setuptools>=69\", \"wheel\", \"setuptools-scm>=8\"]\n\n  [tool.setuptools_scm]\n  version_scheme = \"no-guess-dev\"\n  local_scheme = \"node-and-date\"\n  write_to = \"src/yourpkg/_version.py\"\n  ```\n\n  And in `__init__.py`:\n\n  ```python\n  try:\n      from ._version import version as __version__\n  except Exception:\n      __version__ = \"0.0.0\"\n  ```\n* **Config in `pyproject.toml`:** centralize tool configs (already shown for pytest/mypy/ruff).\n* **Extras:** add `cli`, `viz`, etc. under `[project.optional-dependencies]`, then `pip install -e .[dev,cli]`.\n* **Data files:** if shipping non-code assets, add `MANIFEST.in` or `package_data`.\n* **Typed package:** include `py.typed` to signal type hints to downstream users.\n\n---\n\n## 11) Quick checklist (copy into your issue tracker)\n\n* [ ] Rename `yourpkg` and metadata\n* [ ] Choose versioning (static vs setuptools-scm)\n* [ ] Decide CLI lib (argparse vs Typer); add dependency if Typer\n* [ ] Add core modules under `src/yourpkg/core/`\n* [ ] Add tests for public API and CLI\n* [ ] Enable pre-commit and CI (GitHub Actions)\n* [ ] Publish to PyPI when ready (`python -m build && twine upload dist/*`)\n\n---\n\n## 12) Design prompts (for future-proofing)\n\n* What parts of your code are **reusable modules** vs app-specific? Put reusable bits in `yourpkg/core` with clean function/class APIs.\n* If you scaled to **10× features** or **10× data**, which boundaries (CLI ↔ core ↔ I/O) would you harden?\n* Do you want a **stable public API**? If yes, version functions and avoid breaking changes; add tests as contracts.\n* Make it **shareable**: write a crisp README, examples, and `--help` output that doubles as documentation.\n",
      "subtasks": [],
      "createdAt": "2025-09-23T23:59:10.198Z",
      "completedAt": null,
      "updatedAt": "2025-09-23T23:59:10.198Z",
      "tags": [],
      "deletedAt": null
    },
