    {
      "id": "4u1jbtk2",
      "title": "Look @ the possibilities of integrating Isaaclab 2.3",
      "status": "BACKLOG",
      "due": null,
      "noteId": null,
      "projectId": "c7szb5bi",
      "priority": "medium",
      "description": "Reference @ https://developer.nvidia.com/blog/streamline-robot-learning-with-whole-body-control-and-enhanced-teleoperation-in-nvidia-isaac-lab-2-3/?ncid=so-link-100608-vt48&linkId=100000384917699\nBriefing: Key Capabilities and Enhancements in NVIDIA Isaac Lab 2.3\n\nExecutive Summary\n\nThe early developer preview of NVIDIA Isaac Lab 2.3 marks a significant advancement in streamlining robot learning through a simulation-first methodology. This release addresses the high cost, slow pace, and generalization limits of real-world training by introducing powerful new capabilities for developing, training, and evaluating robot policies in a simulated environment. Key enhancements include advanced whole-body control and locomotion for humanoid robots, expanded teleoperation support with devices like Meta Quest VR, and new workflows for automated data generation. The introduction of SkillGen improves the creation of collision-free manipulation data, while a new loco-manipulation pipeline enables the synthesis of complex tasks combining movement and object interaction. Furthermore, a collaboration with Lightwheel has produced NVIDIA Isaac Lab – Arena, an open-source framework designed for scalable, simulation-based policy evaluation. These updates collectively aim to accelerate robotics research and development by lowering risks, reducing costs, and enabling the creation of more adaptable and robust robot behaviors.\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\n1. Advancing Robot Learning with Simulation-First Development\n\nTraining robot policies directly from real-world demonstrations presents significant challenges, including high costs, slow development cycles, and a tendency for policies to overfit, which limits their ability to generalize across different tasks and environments. Isaac Lab 2.3 champions a \"sim-first\" approach to mitigate these issues. This methodology streamlines development, lowers financial and physical risks, and facilitates the creation of safer, more adaptable robots for real-world deployment.\n\n2. Core Enhancements in Isaac Lab 2.3\n\nThis release introduces a suite of new features and improvements focused on humanoid control, dexterous manipulation, data generation, and navigation.\n\n2.1. Reinforcement and Imitation Learning Capabilities\n\nIsaac Lab 2.3 enhances support for complex dexterous manipulation tasks with several new features designed to improve Reinforcement Learning (RL) training at scale.\n\n* Advanced Training Techniques: Incorporates Automatic Domain Randomization (ADR) and Population Based Training (PBT) to improve the scaling and robustness of RL training. These features build upon the foundations established in prior research such as DexPBT and Visuomotor Policies to Grasp Anything with Dexterous Hands.\n* Dictionary Observation Space: Introduces a dictionary observation space to better manage perception and proprioception data.\n* New Benchmarking Environments: Expands benchmarking capabilities with the inclusion of new environments featuring suction grippers, adding CPU-based surface gripper support to the manager-based workflow for imitation learning.\n\n2.2. Expanded Teleoperation for Dexterous Manipulation\n\nTeleoperation, the remote control of a robot by a human operator, is critical for collecting high-quality demonstration data. Isaac Lab 2.3 significantly improves this process.\n\n* Dexterous Retargeting: A core improvement is the implementation of dexterous retargeting, a process that translates human hand configurations to robot hand joint positions. This enables more efficient human-to-robot skill transfer and yields richer demonstration data for training robust manipulation policies, particularly for contact-rich, in-hand tasks.\n* Expanded Robot and Device Support:\n  * Adds teleoperation support for the Unitree G1 robot, including dexterous retargeting for both its three-finger hand and the Inspire five-finger hand.\n  * Broadens support for input devices to include Meta Quest VR and Manus gloves.\n* Improved Upper Body Control: The Pink IK (Inverse Kinematics) controller has been improved to maintain a more natural posture for bimanual robots like the Fourier GR1T2 and Unitree G1, reducing unnecessary \"elbow flare\" and increasing the robot's reachable workspace. This is complemented by new environments that permit torso rotation.\n* UI Enhancements: The user interface now provides more intuitive feedback to teleoperators, including alerts for IK controller errors (e.g., at-limit joints, no-solve states) and a pop-up notification to signal the conclusion of a demonstration collection session.\n\n2.3. Automated and Scalable Data Generation Workflows\n\nThe platform introduces new and improved workflows for generating high-quality synthetic data for training.\n\n* SkillGen for Manipulation Data: Isaac Lab 2.3 introduces SkillGen, a workflow for generating adaptive, collision-free manipulation demonstrations. It improves upon the previous MimicGen implementation by combining human-provided subtask segments with GPU-accelerated motion planning. Key features of SkillGen include:\n  * Multiphase Planning: Supports distinct planning phases for approach, contact, and retreat motions.\n  * Dynamic Object Handling: Manages dynamic attachment and detachment of objects with appropriate collision sphere management.\n  * State Synchronization: Respects kinematics and obstacles when stitching skills together to ensure consistent and reproducible trajectories.\n* End-to-End Navigation for Mobile Robots: A new mobility workflow allows developers to post-train NVIDIA COMPASS, a vision-based mobility pipeline. This end-to-end process includes:\n  * Synthetic Data Generation (SDG): Utilizes Isaac Sim for SDG, with Cosmos Transfer technology employed to reduce the sim-to-real gap.\n  * Integrated Libraries: Combines NVIDIA Isaac CUDA-accelerated libraries for a complete navigation stack: cuVSLAM for localization, cuVGL for mapping, and COMPASS for scene understanding and action generation.\n  * Foundation Model Support: COMPASS can generate synthetic data for training advanced Vision Language Action (VLA) foundation models like GR00T.\n* Loco-manipulation SDG for Humanoids: This workflow addresses \"loco-manipulation,\" the coordinated execution of locomotion and manipulation as a single, coupled task.\n  * Integrated Control: It synthesizes task demonstrations by integrating navigation with a whole-body controller (WBC).\n  * Data Augmentation: It augments manipulation-only human demonstrations by randomizing pick-and-place locations, destinations, and ground obstacles, effectively restructuring data collection into segments separated by locomotion. This process enables the creation of large-scale datasets for training humanoids on combined tasks.\n\n3. Scalable Evaluation and Ecosystem Integration\n\nBeyond training, Isaac Lab 2.3 provides new tools for evaluation and is supported by a growing hardware and software ecosystem.\n\n3.1. NVIDIA Isaac Lab – Arena: A Policy Evaluation Framework\n\nTo address the challenge that evaluating robot skills on real hardware does not scale, NVIDIA and Lightwheel are co-developing Isaac Lab – Arena, an open-source framework for scalable, simulation-based experimentation.\n\n* Core Purpose: To streamline and execute complex, large-scale evaluations, allowing developers to focus on policy iteration rather than system-building.\n* Key Features:\n  * Simplified, customizable task definitions.\n  * Extensible libraries for metrics, evaluation, and diversification.\n  * Parallelized, GPU-accelerated evaluations using Isaac Lab.\n  * Interoperability with data generation, training, and deployment frameworks.\n* Orchestration: For large-scale workloads, Isaac Lab – Arena can be orchestrated with NVIDIA OSMO, a cloud-native platform for scheduling robotics pipelines across on-premise and cloud compute. The framework will be available soon.\n\n3.2. Infrastructure Support and Ecosystem Adoption\n\n* Hardware Platforms: Isaac Lab 2.3 is supported on NVIDIA RTX PRO Blackwell Servers and NVIDIA DGX Spark, which is powered by the NVIDIA GB10 Grace Blackwell Superchip.\n* Platform Limitations: On DGX Spark, teleoperation with XR/AVP and Imitation Learning in Isaac Lab Mimic are not supported in this release.\n* Industry Adoption: Leading robotics developers are utilizing NVIDIA libraries and models, including Agility Robotics, Boston Dynamics, Booster Robotics, Dexmate, Figure AI, Hexagon, Lightwheel, General Robotics, maxon, and Skild AI.\n\n3.3. Access and Further Information\n\n* The early developer release of Isaac Lab 2.3 is available via its GitHub repository and accompanying documentation.\n* Related research is being showcased at the CoRL and Humanoids conferences.\n* The platform is featured in the 2025 BEHAVIOR Challenge, a robotics benchmark focused on household tasks.\n",
      "subtasks": [],
      "createdAt": "2025-10-06T02:02:30.420Z",
      "completedAt": null,
      "updatedAt": "2025-10-06T02:02:30.420Z",
      "tags": [],
      "deletedAt": null
    },
